title: Greek alphabet
paragraph: The Greek alphabet has been used to write the Greek language since the late 9th century BC or early 8th century BC. [SBD]  It was derived from the earlier Phoenician alphabet, and was the first alphabetic script to have distinct letters for vowels as well as consonants. [SBD]  It is the ancestor of the Latin and Cyrillic scripts. Apart from its use in writing the Greek language, in both its ancient and its modern forms, the Greek alphabet today also serves as a source of technical symbols and labels in many domains of mathematics, science and other fields.

title: United Kingdom local elections, 2004
paragraph: The United Kingdom local elections of 2004 were held on 10 June, as part of the 2004 set of elections along with the European elections and the London mayoral and Assembly elections.

title: Nanny (disambiguation)
paragraph: A nanny is a child's caregiver.

title: Kuna de Madugandí
paragraph: Kuna de Madugandi (] ) is a comarca in Panamá. [SBD]  It was created in 1996 from the east part of the province of Panamá, in the district of Chepo. [SBD]  The primary ethnicity is Kuna.

title: Kaohsiung County
paragraph: Kaohsiung County was a county in southern Taiwan. [SBD]  The county capital was Fongshan City.

title: Kuna de Wargandí
paragraph: Kuna de Wargandí (] ) is a "comarca indígena" (indigenous territory) and corregimiento in Pinogana District, Darién Province, Panama with a population of 1,914 as of 2010. [SBD]  It was created by Law 34 of July 25, 2000, from the province of Darién, from the district of Pinogana. [SBD]  It has an area of 775 km2 . [SBD]  It is inhabited by the Kuna people.

title: Yume Bitsu
paragraph: Yume Bitsu (meaning "dream beats" in Japanese) was a shoegaze / space rock /ambient rock/ experimental band from Portland, Oregon. [SBD]  Active between 1995 and 2002.

title: Fort Lauderdale Sun
paragraph: Fort Lauderdale Sun was a U.S. soccer team which played two seasons in the United Soccer League. [SBD]  In 1984, the team was known as the Fort Lauderdale Sun. [SBD]  Before the 1985 season they changed their name to the South Florida Sun.

title: Cider apple
paragraph: Cider apples are a group of apple cultivars grown for their use in cider production, distinguished from "cookers" and "eaters" by their generally poor qualities for these uses, often because of bitterness or dryness of flavour. [SBD]  Some apples are considered to occupy more than one category.

title: Snakebite (drink)
paragraph: A snakebite is an alcoholic drink made with equal parts of lager and cider.

title: Snakebite
paragraph: A snakebite is an injury caused by the bite of a snake, especially a venomous snake. [SBD]  A common symptom of a bite from a venomous snake is the presence of two puncture wounds from the animal's fangs. Sometimes venom injection from the bite may occur. [SBD]  This may result in redness, swelling, and severe pain at the area, which may take up to an hour to appear. [SBD]  Vomiting, trouble seeing, tingling of the limbs, and sweating may result. [SBD]  Most bites are on the hands or arms. [SBD]  Fear following a bite is common with symptoms of a racing heart and feeling faint. [SBD]  The venom may cause bleeding, kidney failure, a severe allergic reaction, tissue death around the bite, or breathing problems. [SBD]  Bites may result in the loss of a limb or other chronic problems. [SBD]  The outcome depends on the type of snake, the area of the body bitten, the amount of venom injected, and the health conditions of the person. [SBD]  Problems are often more severe in children than adults, due to their smaller size.

title: Ralph Lane
paragraph: Sir Ralph Lane (c. 1532 – October 1603) was an English explorer of the Elizabethan era. [SBD]  He was part of the unsuccessful attempt in 1585 to colonise Roanoke Island, North Carolina. [SBD]  He also served the Crown in Ireland and was knighted by the Queen in 1593.

title: David Tom
paragraph: David Tom (born March 23, 1978) is an American actor.

title: NBA Coach of the Year Award
paragraph: The National Basketball Association's Coach of the Year is an annual National Basketball Association (NBA) award given since the 1962–63 NBA season. [SBD]  The winner receives the Red Auerbach Trophy, which is named in honor of the head coach who led the Boston Celtics to nine NBA Championships from 1956 to 1966. [SBD]  The winner is selected at the end of regular season by a panel of sportswriters from the United States and Canada, each of whom casts a vote for first, second and third place selections. [SBD]  Each first-place vote is worth five points; each second-place vote is worth three points; and each third-place vote is worth one point. [SBD]  The person with the highest point total, regardless of the number of first-place votes, wins the award.

title: Green–Schwarz mechanism
paragraph: The Green–Schwarz mechanism (sometimes called the Green–Schwarz anomaly cancellation mechanism) is the main discovery that started the first superstring revolution in superstring theory.

title: Salvor Hardin
paragraph: Salvor Hardin is a fictional character who appears in two parts of Isaac Asimov's novel "Foundation". [SBD]  The two parts were initially published as short stories before being published in novel form. [SBD]  Hardin is the first mayor of Terminus City, the sole inhabited location on the planet Terminus.

title: Old soldiers' home
paragraph: An old soldiers' home is a military veteran's retirement home, nursing home, or hospital, or sometimes even an institution for the care of the widows and orphans of a nation's soldiers, sailors, and marines, etc.

title: Burgundy wine
paragraph: Burgundy wine ( or "vin de Bourgogne ") is wine made in the Burgundy region in eastern France, in the valleys and slopes west of the Saône, a tributary of the Rhône. [SBD]  The most famous wines produced here—those commonly referred to as "Burgundies"—are dry red wines made from Pinot noir grapes and white wines made from Chardonnay grapes.

title: Mary Stuart (actress)
paragraph: Mary Stuart (July 4, 1926 – February 28, 2002) was an American actress, guitarist, singer, and songwriter.

title: Dud Dudley
paragraph: Dudd (Dud) Dudley (1600–1684) was an English metallurgist, who fought on the Royalist side in the English Civil War as a soldier, military engineer, and supplier of munitions. [SBD]  He was one of the first Englishmen to smelt iron ore using coke.

title: Finishing (whisky)
paragraph: Finishing (also known as "double matured" or "wood-finished") is the procedure that some whiskeys undergo whereby the spirit is matured in a cask of a particular origin and then spends time in a cask of different origin (from a couple of months up to the entire maturation) Typically, the first cask is an American oak cask formerly used to mature bourbon. [SBD]  The second cask may be one that has been used to mature some sort of fortified wine, often sherry, though sometimes port, madeira, or even wines such as red burgundy or chardonnay are used.

title: Grey teal
paragraph: The grey teal ("Anas gracilis") is a dabbling duck found in open wetlands in Australia and New Zealand.

title: Parallel Line Internet Protocol
paragraph: The Parallel Line Internet Protocol (PLIP) is a computer networking protocol for direct computer-to-computer communications using the parallel port normally used for connections to a printer.

title: Brass quintet
paragraph: A brass quintet is a five-piece musical ensemble composed of brass instruments. [SBD]  As a common ensemble group, the brass quintet has a broad repertoire containing musical genres from madrigals to jazz.

title: La Albuera
paragraph: La Albuera is a village southeast of Badajoz, Extremadura, Spain. [SBD]  s of 2009 it had a population of c. 2,000 inhabitants.

title: Peter Steele
paragraph: Petrus Thomas Ratajczyk (January 4, 1962 – April 14, 2010), better known by his stage name Peter Steele, was the lead singer, bassist and composer for the gothic metal band Type O Negative. [SBD]  Before forming Type O Negative, he had created the metal group Fallout and the thrash band Carnivore.

title: Madrona Marsh
paragraph: The Madrona Marsh Preserve, in the city of Torrance in the South Bay region of Southern California, is a seasonal wetland with vernal pools. [SBD]  The 43 acres was a former site of oil wells and is one of the few natural areas remaining within an urban landscape.

title: Lincoln Park Zoo
paragraph: Lincoln Park Zoo is a 35 acre zoo located in Lincoln Park in Chicago, Illinois. [SBD]  The zoo was founded in 1868, making it among the oldest of zoos in North America. [SBD]  It is also one of a few free admission zoos in the United States. [SBD]  The zoo is an accredited member of the Association of Zoos and Aquariums (AZA).

title: Guard band
paragraph: In radio, a guard band is an unused part of the radio spectrum between radio bands, for the purpose of preventing interference.

title: List of Canadian electoral districts 1987–96
paragraph: This is a list of the Canadian electoral districts used between 1987 and 1996. [SBD]  During this period, the House of Commons had 295 seats. [SBD]  This arrangement was used in the 1988 and 1993 elections.

title: Palm Springs Aerial Tramway
paragraph: The Palm Springs Aerial Tramway in Palm Springs, California, is the largest rotating aerial tramway in the world. [SBD]  It was opened in September 1963 as a way of getting from the floor of the Coachella Valley to relatively near the top of San Jacinto Peak and was constructed in rugged Chino Canyon. [SBD]  Before its construction, the only way to the top of the mountain was to hike a number of hours from Idyllwild.

title: Thorotrast
paragraph: Thorotrast is a suspension containing particles of the radioactive compound thorium dioxide, ThO, that was used as a radiocontrast agent in medical radiography in the 1930s and 1940s. [SBD]  (Use in some countries, such as the U.S., continued into the 1950s.)

title: Ken Aston
paragraph: Kenneth George Aston, MBE (1 September 1915 – 23 October 2001) was an English teacher, soldier, and football referee, who was responsible for many important developments in football refereeing - including the yellow and red card system.

title: SSTH Ocean Arrow
paragraph: SSTH "Ocean Arrow" is a super slender twin hull (SSTH) car ferry operating in Japan. [SBD]  Prof. Hideaki Miyata at Tokyo University developed the SSTH, a high-speed catamaran-hulled boat, as a joint work with IHI Corporation.

title: Alicia Coppola
paragraph: Alicia Coppola (born April 12, 1968) is an American television and film actress.

title: Delivery point
paragraph: In a postal system, a delivery point (sometimes DP) is a single mailbox or other place at which mail is delivered. [SBD]  It differs from a street address, in that each address may in fact have several delivery points, such as an apartment, office department, or other room. [SBD]  Such buildings (mainly only residential) are often called multiple-dwelling units (MDUs) by the USPS.

title: JournalServer
paragraph: JournalServer is an Oxford-based international initiative to create a digital library of academic journals freely available to the public. [SBD]  It involves the collaboration of several leading universities across the world.

title: General Hospital
paragraph: General Hospital (commonly abbreviated GH) is an American daytime television medical drama. [SBD]  It is listed in "Guinness World Records" as the longest-running American soap opera in production and the second longest-running drama in television in American history after "Guiding Light". [SBD]  Concurrently, it is the world's second longest-running scripted drama series in production after British serials "The Archers" and "Coronation Street", as well as the world's second-longest-running televised soap opera still in production. [SBD]  "General Hospital" premiered on the ABC television network on April 1, 1963. [SBD]  Same-day broadcasts as well as classic episodes were aired on SOAPnet from January 20, 2000, to December 31, 2013, following Disney-ABC's decision to discontinue the network. [SBD]  "General Hospital" is the longest-running serial produced in Hollywood, and the longest-running entertainment program in ABC television history. [SBD]  It holds the record for most Daytime Emmy Awards for Outstanding Drama Series, with 13 wins.

title: Arab Hellenic Bank
paragraph: The Arab Hellenic Bank was an internationally owned bank based in Greece.

title: David Peck Todd
paragraph: David Peck Todd (March 19, 1855 – June 1, 1939) was a noted American astronomer. [SBD]  He produced a complete set of photographs of the 1882 transit of Venus.

title: Tuggeranong
paragraph: The District of Tuggeranong is one of the original eighteen districts of the Australian Capital Territory used in land administration. [SBD]  The district is subdivided into divisions (suburbs), sections and blocks and is the southernmost town centre of Canberra, the capital city of Australia. [SBD]  The district comprises nineteen suburbs and occupies 117 km2 to the east of the Murrumbidgee River.

title: James Whiteside McCay
paragraph: Lieutenant General Sir James Whiteside McCay, (21 December 1864 – 1 October 1930), who often spelt his surname M’Cay, was an Australian general and politician.

title: Internal passport
paragraph: An internal passport is an identity document that may or may not be used by a country to control and monitor the internal movement and residence of its people. [SBD]  When passports first emerged, there was no clear distinction between internal and international ones. [SBD]  Later, some countries developed sophisticated systems of passports for various purposes and various groups of population. [SBD]  Uses for internal passports have included restricting citizens of a subdivided state to employment in their own area (preventing their migration to richer cities or regions), clearly recording the ethnicity of citizens to enforce segregation or prevent passing, and controlling access to sensitive sites or closed cities.

title: Capacitance Electronic Disc
paragraph: The Capacitance Electronic Disc (CED) is an analog video disc playback system developed by RCA, in which video and audio could be played back on a TV set using a special needle and high-density groove system similar to phonograph records.

title: Piraeus Bank
paragraph: Piraeus Bank A.E. (Greek: Τράπεζα Πειραιώς ΑΕ ), is a Greek multinational financial services company with its headquarters in Athens, Greece.

title: O'Dea Castle
paragraph: O'Dea Castle, also known as Dysert O'Dea Castle, is an Irish fortified tower house, loosely described as a castle at Dysert O'Dea (Irish: "Dísert" , meaning "hermitage" ), the former O'Dea clan stronghold, 5 km from Corofin, County Clare just off the R476 road. [SBD]  It was built between 1470 and 1490 by Diarmaid O'Dea, Lord of Cineal Fearmaic, and stands some 50 ft high on a limestone outcrop base measuring 20 by . [SBD]  The tower is adjacent to Dysert O'Dea Monastery.

title: List of Canadian electoral districts 1872–73
paragraph: This is a list of electoral districts or "ridings" in Canada for the Canadian federal election, 1872. [SBD]  New seats were added in 1873 when Prince Edward Island became a province.

title: Cholon, Ho Chi Minh City
paragraph: Chợ Lớn (  ) is a quarter of Ho Chi Minh City (formerly Saigon), in Vietnam. [SBD]  It lies on the west bank of the Saigon River, having Bình Tây Market as its central market. [SBD]  Cholon consists of the western half of District 5 as well as several adjoining neighborhoods in District 6 and District 11. [SBD]  The quarter is long inhabited by Chinese people, and is considered the largest Chinatown in the world by area.

title: Phascogale
paragraph: The phascogales (members of the eponymous genus "Phascogale"), also known as wambengers, are carnivorous Australian marsupials of the family Dasyuridae. [SBD]  There are three species: the brush-tailed phascogale ("Phascogale tapoatafa"), the red-tailed phascogale ("Phascogale calura"), and the northern brush-tailed phascogale ("Phascogale pirata"). [SBD]  As with a number of dasyurid species, the males live for only one year, dying after a period of frenzied mating. [SBD]  The term "Phascogale" was coined in 1824 by Coenraad Jacob Temminck in reference to the brush-tailed phascogale, and means "pouched weasel". [SBD]  All three species are listed as either Near Threatened or Vulnerable by the IUCN.

title: List of Canadian electoral districts 1871–72
paragraph: This is a list of electoral districts or "ridings" in Canada from 1871 to 1872, according to the British North America Act. [SBD]  No elections were held at this time, except to elect new members from Manitoba which joined confederation in 1870. [SBD]  New seats were added in 1872 as British Columbia had joined Confederation as a province the year before, with special byelections being called to fill the seats and temporary seatnames until the general election. [SBD]  Of these, only two seats (New Westminster District and Vancouver, were contested, the others being filled by acclamation.

title: Bank of Athens
paragraph: Historically, there have been two Greek banks named Bank of Athens, both of which were headquartered in Athens, Greece. [SBD]  The first was founded in 1893 and operated in the Balkans and Eastern Mediterranean until its acquisition by the National Bank of Greece in 1953. [SBD]  The second Bank of Athens was founded in 1993 and merged with Eurobank Ergasias in 1999. [SBD]  Additionally, numerous banks in the United States of America have incorporated Bank of Athens into their name.

title: Sarah Chalke
paragraph: Sarah Chalke ( ; born August 27, 1976) is a Canadian actress. [SBD]  She is known for portraying Dr. Elliot Reid on the NBC/ABC comedy series "Scrubs", the second Rebecca "Becky" Conner on the ABC sitcom "Roseanne", Stella Zinman on the CBS sitcom "How I Met Your Mother", and Beth Smith on Adult Swim's adult animated science-fiction series "Rick and Morty". [SBD]  She also had a recurring role on the third season of the ABC/TBS sitcom "Cougar Town".

title: Descent (aeronautics)
paragraph: A descent during air travel is any portion where an aircraft decreases altitude, and is the opposite of an ascent or climb.

title: Ella Baker
paragraph: Ella Josephine Baker (December 13, 1903 – December 13, 1986) was an African-American civil rights and human rights activist born in Virginia, who grew up in North Carolina and graduated from college there, and worked for most of her life based in New York City. [SBD]  She was a largely behind-the-scenes organizer whose career spanned more than five decades. [SBD]  She worked alongside some of the most famous civil rights leaders of the 20th century, including W. E. B. Du Bois, Thurgood Marshall, A. Philip Randolph, and Martin Luther King, Jr. She also mentored many emerging activists, such as Diane Nash, Stokely Carmichael, Rosa Parks, and Bob Moses.

title: Brush-tailed phascogale
paragraph: The brush-tailed phascogale ("Phascogale tapoatafa"), also known by its Australian native name tuan, the common wambenger or the black-tailed phascogale, is a rat-sized arboreal carnivorous marsupial of the family Dasyuridae, characterized by a tuft of black silky hairs on the terminal portion of its tail. [SBD]  Males of this species do not live past the age of one, as they die after reproducing.

title: Frolic Froth
paragraph: Frolic Froth is a psychedelic band formed in Mexico City by members Victor Basurto (bass) and Arturo López (drums) of Loch Ness, and Jorge Beltrán (guitar) from Humus. [SBD]  These three musicians had previously played together in diverse bands along with other musicians during the 1980s and good part of the 1990s, until they finally decided to break away from the sound of previous bands and start Frolic Froth.

title: List of Canadian electoral districts 1882–86
paragraph: This is a list of electoral districts or "ridings" in Canada for the Canadian federal election of 1882. [SBD]  Starting in 1887, the Northwest Territories (acquired by Canada in 1870) was included in representation in the House of Commons. [SBD]  (Representation stopped from 1905 to 1949.)

title: Anthony Geary
paragraph: Anthony Dean Geary (born May 29, 1947) is an American actor. [SBD]  He is known for playing the role of Luke Spencer on the ABC daytime drama "General Hospital". [SBD]  Geary originated the role of Luke in 1978 and has since received a record eight Daytime Emmy Awards for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series. [SBD]  He also had a supporting role in "Weird Al" Yankovic's comedy film "UHF" (1989).

title: Security Armored Express
paragraph: Security Armored Express, Inc. was an armored car and courier provider for the Western United States. [SBD]  Its corporate office was located in Helena, Montana.

title: Genie Francis
paragraph: Eugenie Ann "Genie" Francis Frakes (born May 26, 1962) is an American actress best known for her portrayal of Laura Spencer on the ABC Daytime soap opera "General Hospital".

title: Stephen Nichols
paragraph: Stephen Nichols (born February 19, 1951) is an American actor, most notable for his roles on American daytime soap operas. [SBD]  He played the part of Steve (Patch) Johnson on NBCs "Days of Our Lives" from 1985-1990; after that, he had a stint on ABC's "General Hospital" as Stefan Cassadine from 1996-2003. [SBD]  He returned to the role of Steve (Patch) Johnson on "Days of Our Lives" in June 2006 after 16 years, remaining through February 2009, and returning to the role again in 2015. [SBD]  He played (from December 2009 to January 2013) the role of Tucker McCall on "The Young and the Restless".

title: Helen Duncan
paragraph: Victoria Helen McCrae Duncan (25 November 1897 – 6 December 1956) was a Scottish medium best known as the last person to be imprisoned under the British Witchcraft Act of 1735. [SBD]  She was famous for producing fraudulent ectoplasm made from cheesecloth.

title: JAXA
paragraph: The Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA) (国立研究開発法人宇宙航空研究開発機構 , Kokuritsu-kenkyū-kaihatsu-hōjin Uchū Kōkū Kenkyū Kaihatsu Kikō , literally "National Research and Development Agency on Aerospace Research and Development") is Japan's national aero-space agency. [SBD]  Through the merger of three previously independent organizations, JAXA was formed on 1 October 2003. [SBD]  JAXA is responsible for research, technology development and the launch of satellites into orbit, and is involved in many more advanced missions, such as asteroid exploration and possible manned exploration of the Moon. [SBD]  Its motto is "One JAXA" and its corporate slogan is "Explore to Realize" (formerly "Reaching for the skies, exploring space").

title: Buffalo Bills (quartet)
paragraph: The Buffalo Bills were a barbershop quartet formed in Buffalo, New York, on September 20, 1947. [SBD]  The original members were tenor Vern Reed, an executive for the Tonawanda Boys' Club; lead Al Shea, who was a City of Buffalo policeman; baritone Herschel Smith, a corporate executive; and bass Bill Spangenberg, a truck driver for a steel company. [SBD]  They started out as an unnamed foursome, singing for community groups. [SBD]  During an appearance at the Buffalo Quarterback Club, they were introduced as the "Buffalo Bills", which was meant to be just for that day, but the name stuck from that point on. [SBD]  Coincidentally, a football team known formerly as the Buffalo Bisons also changed its name to the Bills at about the same time; the name proved popular enough that the current Buffalo Bills also picked up the name when they debuted thirteen years later.

title: Treaty of 1818
paragraph: The Convention respecting fisheries, boundary and the restoration of slaves between the United States of America and the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, also known as the London Convention, Anglo-American Convention of 1818, Convention of 1818, or simply the Treaty of 1818, was an international treaty signed in 1818 between those parties. [SBD]  Signed during the presidency of James Monroe, it resolved standing boundary issues between the two nations. [SBD]  The treaty allowed for joint occupation and settlement of the Oregon Country, known to the British and in Canadian history as the Columbia District of the Hudson's Bay Company, and including the southern portion of its sister district New Caledonia.

title: Bouvier
paragraph: Bouvier, a French surname, is the last name of several notable people:

title: Oxalate
paragraph: Oxalate (IUPAC: ethanedioate) is the dianion with the formula C2O42− , also written (COO)22− . [SBD]  Either name is often used for derivatives, such as salts of oxalic acid, for example sodium oxalate NaCO, or dimethyl oxalate ((CH)CO). [SBD]  Oxalate also forms coordination compounds where it is sometimes abbreviated as ox.

title: Kazem al-Haeri
paragraph: Grand Ayatollah Kazem Husseini Haeri (Arabic: كاظم حسيني حائري‎ ‎ ) is a prominent Twelver Shi'a marja. [SBD]  Haeri was born in Iran, but moved to Iraq to lead the Twelver Shi'a community there. [SBD]  He was a top leader of the Al-Da'wa Party in Iraq. [SBD]  His involvement in the party led to his exile in the 1970s, when he moved to Iran, where he remains to this day in the "holy" city of Qom.

title: Lander University
paragraph: Lander University is a public university located in Greenwood, South Carolina. [SBD]  It is the state's second-smallest publicly funded baccalaureate institution.

title: St Peter's School, York
paragraph: St Peter's School is a co-educational independent boarding and day school (also referred to as a public school), in the English City of York, with extensive grounds on the banks of the River Ouse. [SBD]  Founded by St Paulinus of York in AD 627, it is the third oldest school in the UK and the fourth oldest in the world. [SBD]  It is part of the York Boarding Schools Group.

title: Chamber of Deputies of Chile
paragraph: The Honourable Chamber of Deputies of the Republic of Chile (Spanish: "Cámara de Diputados" ) is the lower house of Chile's bicameral Congress. [SBD]  Its organisation and its powers and duties are defined in articles 42 to 59 of Chile's current constitution.

title: National Congress of Chile
paragraph: The National Congress of Chile (Spanish: "Congreso Naciona de Chile" ) is the legislative branch of the government of the Republic of Chile.

title: DLI
paragraph: DLI is a three-letter abbreviation that may refer to:

title: Train of Thought (Dream Theater album)
paragraph: Train of Thought is the seventh studio album by progressive band Dream Theater, released on November 11, 2003 through Elektra Records.

title: Tainan County
paragraph: Tainan County was a county of the Republic of China in southern Taiwan before it merged with the provincial Tainan City to form a new special municipality in 2010. [SBD]  The county capital was Xinying City.

title: Tom Freston
paragraph: Thomas E. Freston (born November 22, 1945) is an American entertainment industry executive.

title: Premises
paragraph: Premises are land and buildings together considered as a property. [SBD]  This usage arose from property owners finding the word in their [title deed]s, where it originally correctly meant "the aforementioned; what this document is about", from [Latin] "prae-missus" = "placed before".

title: Roy Welensky
paragraph: Sir Roland "Roy" Welensky, KCMG ("né" Raphael Welensky; 20 January 1907 – 5 December 1991) was a Northern Rhodesian politician and the second and last prime minister of the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland.

title: Murphy J. Foster
paragraph: Murphy James Foster (January 12, 1849June 12, 1921) was a Louisiana politician who served two terms as the 31st Governor of Louisiana from 1892 to 1900. [SBD]  Foster adopted the Louisiana Constitution of 1898, which effectively disfranchised the black majority, who comprised most of the Republicans, thus leading to Louisiana's becoming essentially a one-party (Democratic) state for several generations and excluding African Americans from the political system.

title: Mis-Teeq
paragraph: Mis-Teeq were a British girl group, consisting of lead singer Sabrina Washington, rapper, singer and songwriter Alesha Dixon and singer Su-Elise Nash. [SBD]  They had three top-ten double-platinum albums and seven consecutive top-ten singles, with chart-topping success on the UK Singles Chart as well as across Europe. [SBD]  The group originally formed as a quartet in 1999, which included Zena McNally; she left in 2001.

title: Thorbräu
paragraph: Thorbräu is one of the oldest breweries in Germany, founded in 1582 in Augsburg, Bavaria.

title: Ken Daneyko
paragraph: Kenneth Stephen Daneyko (born April 17, 1964) is a retired Canadian-American ice hockey defenceman of Ukrainian origin who played his entire career (1983–2003) with the New Jersey Devils of the National Hockey League, winning three Stanley Cup championships with the team. [SBD]  He has been nicknamed "Mr. Devil" by Devils fans, as he currently holds the franchise record for games played as a Devil with 1,283 games. [SBD]  Daneyko now provides colour analysis alongside Steve Cangialosi during broadcasts of Devils games on MSG Plus.

title: Numbered highways in Ohio
paragraph: The Ohio Department of Transportation (ODOT) is responsible for the establishment and classification of a state highway network which includes interstate highways, U.S. highways, and state routes. [SBD]  As with other states, U.S. and Interstate highways are classified as state routes in Ohio. [SBD]  There are no state routes which duplicate an existing U.S. or Interstate highway in Ohio.

title: Nu Virgos
paragraph: Nu Virgos (Ukrainian: ВІА Гра ) was the name used to promote the musical group VIA Gra (ВИА Гра) outside of Ukraine and other nearby countries. [SBD]  The name "VIA Gra" is both a reference to the drug Viagra and a play on words, since the first three letters stand for "vocal-instrumental ensemble" in Ukrainian, and "hra" means "game" in Ukrainian and it is also kind of a signature of the surnames of the two first girls of the group, VI-nnitskay-A and GRA-novskaya, the originally used maiden name of Nadya Meikher. [SBD]  Nu Virgos was a Ukrainian girl group that hit the charts in these countries in September 2000 with their first single ""Popytka No. 5"".

title: Cross-polytope
paragraph: In geometry, a cross-polytope, orthoplex, hyperoctahedron, or cocube is a regular, convex polytope that exists in "n"-dimensions. [SBD]  A 2-orthoplex is a square, a 3-orthoplex is a regular octahedron, and a 4-orthoplex is a 16-cell. [SBD]  Its facets are simplexes of the previous dimension, while the cross-polytope's vertex figure is another cross-polytope from the previous dimension.

title: Gander International Airport
paragraph: Gander International Airport (IATA: YQX, ICAO: CYQX) is located in Gander, Newfoundland and Labrador, Canada, and is operated by the Gander International Airport Authority. [SBD]  Canadian Forces Base Gander shares the airfield but is a separate entity from the airport.

title: 16-cell
paragraph: In four-dimensional geometry, a 16-cell is a regular convex 4-polytope. [SBD]  It is one of the six regular convex 4-polytopes first described by the Swiss mathematician Ludwig Schläfli in the mid-19th century. [SBD]  It is also called C, hexadecachoron, or hexdecahedroid.

title: Sergei Brylin
paragraph: Sergei Vladimirovich Brylin (Russian: Серге́й Влади́мирович Бры́лин ; born January 13, 1974) is a Russian former professional ice hockey center. [SBD]  He currently is an assistant coach with the Albany Devils of the American Hockey League (AHL). [SBD]  Brylin is a three-time Stanley Cup champion with the New Jersey Devils of the National Hockey League (NHL).

title: Copper River (Alaska)
paragraph: The Copper River or Ahtna River ( ), Ahtna Athabascan ‘Atna’tuu (] ), "river of the Ahtnas", Tlingit Eeḵhéeni (] ), "river of copper", is a 290-mile (470 km) river in south-central Alaska in the United States. [SBD]  It drains a large region of the Wrangell Mountains and Chugach Mountains into the Gulf of Alaska. [SBD]  It is known for its extensive delta ecosystem, as well as for its prolific runs of wild salmon, which are among the most highly prized stocks in the world. [SBD]  The river is the tenth largest in the United States, as ranked by average discharge volume at its mouth.

title: Seychelles International Airport
paragraph: Seychelles International Airport (IATA: SEZ, ICAO: FSIA) , or "Aéroport de la Pointe Larue" in French, is the international airport of the Seychelles located on the island of Mahé near the capital city of Victoria. [SBD]  The airport is the home base and the head office of Air Seychelles and features several regional and long-haul routes due to its importance as an international leisure destination.

title: Ohio State Route 21
paragraph: State Route 21 is a relic of an old U.S. Route 21, a major north–south highway that connected greater Cleveland, Ohio, to southern South Carolina. [SBD]  South of Strasburg, Ohio, near the current southern terminus of State Route 21, the designation of U.S. Route 21 was moved to the new Interstate 77 freeway in east-central and southeastern Ohio by the early 1970s and then decommissioned. [SBD]  North of Strasburg, what remained of U.S. Route 21 as a route separate from Interstate 77 became State Route 21.

title: Praslin Island Airport
paragraph: Praslin Island Airport (IATA: PRI, ICAO: FSPP) also known as Iles des Palmes Airport, is an airport at Grand Anse on Praslin Island in the Seychelles.

title: Flags and arms of cantons of Switzerland
paragraph: Each of the 26 modern cantons of Switzerland has an official flag and a coat of arms.

title: Coil stamp
paragraph: A coil stamp is a type of postage stamp sold in strips one stamp wide. [SBD]  The name derives from the usual handling of long strips, which is to coil them into rolls, in a manner reminiscent of adhesive tape rolls. [SBD]  A large percentage of modern stamps are sold in coil form, because they are more amenable to mechanized handling in large quantities than either sheet stamps or booklet stamps.

title: Hurricane Danielle (1998)
paragraph: Hurricane Danielle resulted in minor damage throughout its duration as a tropical cyclone in late August and early September 1998. [SBD]  The fourth named storm and second hurricane of the annual hurricane season, Danielle originated from a tropical wave that emerged off the western coast of Africa on August 21. [SBD]  Tracking generally west-northwestward, the disturbance was initially disorganized; under favorable atmospheric conditions, shower and thunderstorm activity began to consolidate around a low-pressure center. [SBD]  Following a series of satellite intensity estimates, the system was upgraded to Tropical Depression Four during the pre-dawn hours of August 24, and further to Tropical Storm Danielle that afternoon. [SBD]  Moving around the southern periphery of the Azores High located in the northeastern Atlantic, quick intensification to hurricane status occurred early on August 25. [SBD]  By 0600 UTC the following day, Danielle reached an initial peak intensity of 105 mph (165 km/h), a Category 2 hurricane. [SBD]  Increased wind shear from a nearby trough encroached on further development later that day, and subsequently led to slight weakening. [SBD]  By 1200 UTC on August 27, despite continued unfavorable conditions, Danielle reached a second peak intensity equal to the first. [SBD]  Weakening once ensued late on August 27 in addition to the days following, and Danielle was a low-end Category 1 hurricane by August 31 as its forward speed slowed.

title: Vascular congestion
paragraph: Vascular congestion is the engorgement of an entity, such as the blood vessels of the erectile tissues, with blood. [SBD]  It is known to occur with deep venous thrombosis (DVT).

title: Marbles (album)
paragraph: Marbles is the 13th studio album from rock band Marillion, released in 2004. [SBD]  Unlike their previous studio album, "Anoraknophobia" (2001), which was financed largely by a preorder campaign, it was the publicity campaign that fans financed for the album. [SBD]  Those fans who pre-ordered the album received an exclusive 2-CD "Deluxe Campaign Edition" with a booklet containing the names of everyone who pre-ordered before a certain date. [SBD]  The public release date of the retail single-CD version of the album was 3 May 2004 while a plain 2CD version could still be obtained from the band's website. [SBD]  A limited (500 copy) edition was released on white multicoloured vinyl by Racket Records on 13 November 2006.

title: U.S. Route 21
paragraph: U.S. Route 21 (US 21) is a north–south United States Numbered Highway that runs 394 mi from Hunting Island State Park, South Carolina to Wytheville, Virginia.

title: Monstera deliciosa
paragraph: Monstera deliciosa is a species of flowering plant native to tropical rainforests of southern Mexico, south to Panama. [SBD]  It has been introduced to many tropical areas, and has become a mildly invasive species in Hawaii, Seychelles, Ascension Island and the Society Islands.

title: Data Transmission Network
paragraph: DTN, formerly known as Data Transmission Network, is a subscription-based service for the delivery of real-time weather, agricultural and commodity market information. [SBD]  The company is based in Omaha, Nebraska. [SBD]  As of June 2011 Schneider Electric acquired Telvent. [SBD]  Telvent DTN is the name of the service that is owned by its parent company Schneider Electric. [SBD]  DTN’s primary users are agriculture producers, professionals in weather-sensitive industries and commodities and futures traders.

title: Oni (video game)
paragraph: Oni is a third-person action video game developed by Bungie West, a division of Bungie. [SBD]  Released in 2001, it was Bungie West's only game. [SBD]  Gameplay consists of third-person shooting with hand-to-hand combat. [SBD]  A PlayStation 2 port was developed by Rockstar Canada.

title: Entropy (1977 board game)
paragraph: Entropy is an abstract strategy board game for two players designed by Eric Solomon in 1977. [SBD]  The game is "based on the eternal conflict in the universe between order and chaos [...] One player is Order, the other Chaos. [SBD]  Order is trying to make patterns vertically and horizontally. [SBD]  Chaos is trying to prevent this." [SBD]  The game originally employed a 5×5 gameboard, but in 2000 a 7x7 board was introduced to allow deeper strategies.

title: New Zealand general election, 1975
paragraph: The 1975 New Zealand general election was held on 29 November to elect MPs to the 38th session of the New Zealand Parliament. [SBD]  It was the first general election in New Zealand where 18- to 20-year-olds and all permanent residents of New Zealand were eligible to vote, although only citizens were able to be elected.

title: Kobuk River
paragraph: The Kobuk River (also Kooak, Kowak, Kubuk, Kuvuk, or Putnam)

title: Ouagadougou Airport
paragraph: Ouagadougou Airport (IATA: OUA, ICAO: DFFD) is an airport in the center of the city of Ouagadougou in Burkina Faso. [SBD]  It was built in the 1960s, and it is approximately 1.5 km southeast of the main commercial area. [SBD]  The site itself is approximately 4.8 km in length, 0.5 km in width at its narrowest point, and covers an area of approximately 426 hectares. Its runway is 3 000 m long. [SBD]  When the airport was built it was on the southern boundary of the city. [SBD]  Ouagadougou has since experienced rapid urbanization and the airport is now surrounded by urban development.

title: Emblems of the Kalmar Union
paragraph: The Kalmar Union was the personal union of the kingdoms of Denmark, Norway and Sweden during the 15th century. [SBD]  The first king of the Kalmar Union was Eric of Pomerania. [SBD]  His seal combined the coats of arms of Norway (center, as an inescutcheon upon a cross over all), Denmark (in dexter chief), Sweden (the Folkung lion, in dexter base) and Pomerania (a griffin, in sinister base), and in addition the Three Crowns symbol in sinister chief; the latter heraldic design predates the Kalmar Union, and is now mostly associated with the coat of arms of Sweden, but which during the 15th century came to represent the three kingdoms of the union.

title: Sexual arousal disorder
paragraph: Sexual arousal disorder is characterized by a lack or absence of sexual fantasies and desire for sexual activity in a situation that would normally produce sexual arousal, or the inability to attain or maintain typical responses to sexual arousal. [SBD]  The disorder is found in the DSM-IV. [SBD]  The condition should not be confused with a sexual desire disorder.

title: Audubon Ballroom
paragraph: The Audubon Theatre and Ballroom, generally referred to as the Audubon Ballroom, was a theatre and ballroom located at 3940 Broadway at West 165th Street in the Washington Heights neighborhood of Manhattan, New York City. [SBD]  It was built in 1912 and was designed by Thomas W. Lamb. [SBD]  The theatre was known at various times as the William Fox Audubon Theatre, the Beverly Hills Theater, and the San Juan Theater, and the ballroom is noted for being the site of the assassination of Malcolm X on February 21, 1965. [SBD]  It is currently the Audubon Business and Technology Center and the Shabazz Center.

title: M-86 (Michigan highway)
paragraph: M-86 is an east–west state trunkline highway in the US state of Michigan in the southern portion of the Lower Peninsula. [SBD]  The highway starts at Business US Highway 131 (Bus. [SBD]  US 131) and M-60 in Three Rivers and ends at US Highway 12 (US 12) near Coldwater. [SBD]  In between, it crosses farm country and runs along a section of the Prairie River. [SBD]  Following a highway originally numbered M-7, the roadway was renumbered M-86 in 1940. [SBD]  It has been a part of the state highway system at least since 1927. [SBD]  Two other roadways carried the M-86 designation in the 1920s. [SBD]  Two bridges along the road are eligible for inclusion on the National Register of Historic Places (NRHP).

title: City of Port Adelaide Enfield
paragraph: The City of Port Adelaide Enfield, located across inner north and north-western suburbs of Adelaide, is one of the largest metropolitan councils within South Australia. [SBD]  It was established on 26 March 1996 by the amalgamation of the City of Port Adelaide and the City of Enfield.

title: Star of India (gem)
paragraph: The Star of India is a 563.35-carat (112.67 g) star sapphire, one of the largest such gems in the world. [SBD]  It is almost flawless and is unusual in that it has stars on both sides of the stone. [SBD]  The greyish blue gem was mined in Sri Lanka and is housed in the American Museum of Natural History in New York City.

title: The Three Periods
paragraph: The Three Periods is a Quebec sovereigntist strategy. [SBD]  Before the 1993 federal election in Canada, Parti Québécois (PQ) leader Jacques Parizeau evoked a strategy for attainment of Quebec independence called the Three Periods. [SBD]  The strategy is partly inspired by the three periods of play in ice hockey (the most popular sport in Quebec). [SBD]  It is seen as a typical Parizeau concept: dedicated and straightforward, especially compared to some sovereigntist attitudes like a few (not all) of René Lévesque's (specifically in the last years of his government) or to the "étapisme" or "step-by-step" strategy.

title: Kissimmee (disambiguation)
paragraph: Kissimmee is the name of several things in the U.S. state of Florida:

title: Tehran Imam Khomeini International Airport
paragraph: Tehran Imam Khomeini International Airport (Persian: فرودگاه بین‌المللی امام خمینی‎ ‎ ) (IATA: IKA, ICAO: OIIE) , also known as Tehran-IKIA or IKIA, is the main international airport of Iran, located 30 km southwest of the city of Tehran, near the localities of Robat Karim and Eslamshahr, on a 13500 hectare site. [SBD]  Along with Mehrabad International Airport, it is one of the two major commercial airports serving Tehran and the busiest international air passenger gateway to Iran. [SBD]  As of December 2016, it serves international destinations in Asia and Europe. [SBD]  All domestic flights in Tehran are currently served by Mehrabad Airport.

title: Fred Crisman
paragraph: Fred Lee Crisman (July 22, 1919 - Washington December 10, 1975) was an author from Tacoma, Washington known for claims of paranormal events and 20th century conspiracies.

title: Breslow's depth
paragraph: In medicine, Breslow's depth was used as a prognostic factor in melanoma of the skin. [SBD]  It is a description of how deeply tumor cells have invaded. [SBD]  Currently, the standard Breslow's depth has been replaced by the AJCC depth. [SBD]  Originally, Breslow's depth was divided into 5 stages.

title: Interstate 496
paragraph: Interstate 496 (I-496) is an auxiliary Interstate Highway that passes through downtown Lansing in the US state of Michigan. [SBD]  Also a component of the State Trunkline Highway System, the freeway connects I-96 to the downtown area. [SBD]  It has been named the R.E. Olds Freeway (sometimes just Olds Freeway) for Ransom E. Olds, the founder of Oldsmobile and the REO Motor Car Company. [SBD]  I-496 runs east–west from I-96/I-69 near the downtown area and north–south along a section that runs concurrently with US Highway 127 (US 127). [SBD]  The trunkline also passes a former assembly plant used by Oldsmobile and runs along or crosses parts of the Grand and Red Cedar rivers.

title: RRDtool
paragraph: RRDtool ("round-robin database tool") aims to handle time series data such as network bandwidth, temperatures or CPU load. [SBD]  The data is stored in a circular buffer based database, thus the system storage footprint remains constant over time. [SBD]  This is distinct from the computer science concept of round-robin scheduling.

title: Michael Riconosciuto
paragraph: Michael Riconosciuto is an electronics and computer expert who was arrested in early 1991, shortly after providing Inslaw, Inc. with an affidavit in support of their lawsuit against the U.S. Dept. of Justice.

title: Denatonium
paragraph: Denatonium, usually available as denatonium benzoate (under trade names such as BITTERANT-b, BITTER+PLUS, Bitrex or Aversion) and as denatonium saccharide (BITTERANT-s), is the most bitter chemical compound known, with bitterness thresholds of 0.05 ppm for the benzoate and 0.01 ppm for the saccharide.

title: Tagea Brandt Rejselegat
paragraph: The Tagea Brandt "Rejselegat" (Travel Scholarship) is a Danish award to women who have made a significant contribution in science, literature or art. [SBD]  The grant, which is given without application, was created and endowed by Danish industrialist Vilhelm Brandt (1854–1921) in 1905 in honor of his wife, Tagea Brandt.

title: Carl Ludwig Siegel
paragraph: Carl Ludwig Siegel (December 31, 1896 – April 4, 1981) was a German mathematician specialising in number theory and celestial mechanics. [SBD]  He is known for, amongst other things, his contributions to the Thue–Siegel–Roth theorem in Diophantine approximation and the Siegel mass formula for quadratic forms. [SBD]  He was named as one of the most important mathematicians of the 20th century.

title: Burning Love
paragraph: "Burning Love" is a song written by Dennis Linde and originally recorded by country soul artist Arthur Alexander, who included it on his 1972 self-titled album. [SBD]  It was soon covered and brought to fame by Elvis Presley, becoming his biggest hit single in the United States since "Suspicious Minds" in 1969 and his last Top 10 hit in the American Hot 100 or pop charts.

title: Stannary Courts and Parliaments
paragraph: The stannary parliaments and stannary courts were legislative and legal institutions in Cornwall and in Devon (in the Dartmoor area), England. [SBD]  The stannary courts administered equity for the region's tin-miners and tin mining interests, and they were also courts of record for the towns dependent on the mines. [SBD]  Executive authority in stannary areas was exercised by the Lord Warden of the Stannaries.

title: Florida's Turnpike
paragraph: Florida's Turnpike, designated as State Road 91 (SR 91) and the Ronald Reagan Turnpike, is a toll road in Florida, maintained by Florida's Turnpike Enterprise (FTE). [SBD]  Spanning approximately 309 mi along a north–south axis, the turnpike is in two sections. [SBD]  The SR 91 mainline runs roughly 265 mi , from its southern terminus at an interchange with Interstate 95 (I-95) in Miami Gardens to an interchange with I-75 in Wildwood at its northern terminus. [SBD]  The Homestead Extension of Florida's Turnpike (abbreviated HEFT and designated as SR 821) continues from the southern end of the mainline for another 48 mi to US Highway 1 (US 1) in Florida City.

title: Samuel E. Wright
paragraph: Samuel E. Wright is an American film and theatre actor and singer. [SBD]  He is best known as the voice of Sebastian in Disney's "The Little Mermaid", for which he provided the main vocals to "Under the Sea", which won the Academy Award for Best Original Song. [SBD]  Wright also played the part of Mufasa in the original cast of "The Lion King" on Broadway and voiced Kron the Iguanodon in Disney's CGI film "Dinosaur".

title: Treaty of Wedmore
paragraph: The Peace of Wedmore is a term used by historians for an event referred to by the monk Asser in his Life of Alfred, outlining how in 878 the Viking leader Guthrum was baptised and accepted Alfred as his adoptive father. [SBD]  Guthrum agreed to leave Wessex and a "Treaty of Wedmore" (sometimes called the "Treaty of Chippenham") is often assumed by historians to have existed. [SBD]  No such treaty still exists. [SBD]  However, there is a document not specifically linked to Wedmore that is a Treaty of Alfred and Guthrum.

title: John Todd (biologist)
paragraph: John Todd (born 1939) is a biologist working in what is sometimes considered the general field of ecological design, in that his ideas often involve applications that become the basis of alternative technologies. [SBD]  His principal professional interests have included solving problems of food production and waste-water processing. [SBD]  As an author, he has presented the outcome of the work that he and colleagues have undertaken in a series of books, as well as in the requisite scientific papers.

title: Dax, Landes
paragraph: Dax (] ; "Dacs" in Occitan) is a commune in Nouvelle-Aquitaine in southwestern France, sub-prefecture of the Landes department.

title: Melanoma
paragraph: Melanoma, also known as malignant melanoma, is a type of cancer that develops from the pigment-containing cells known as melanocytes. Melanomas typically occur in the skin but may rarely occur in the mouth, intestines, or eye. [SBD]  In women they most commonly occur on the legs, while in men they are most common on the back. [SBD]  Sometimes they develop from a mole with concerning changes including an increase in size, irregular edges, change in color, itchiness, or skin breakdown.

title: Geo-Force
paragraph: Geo-Force (Brion Markov) is a fictional superhero character appearing in comic books published by DC Comics. [SBD]  Markov is Prince of Markovia and the half-brother of Terra. [SBD]  One of the founding members of the superhero group the Outsiders, he first appeared in a special insert in "The Brave and the Bold" #200 (July 1983). [SBD]  The character was created by Mike W. Barr and Jim Aparo.

title: Aqualad
paragraph: Aqualad is the name of two fictional comic book superheroes appearing in books published by DC Comics. [SBD]  The first Aqualad, Garth, debuted in February 1960 in "Adventure Comics" #269 and was created by writer Robert Bernstein and artist Ramona Fradon. [SBD]  This Aqualad also appeared in animated form on television in 1967 and 1968.

title: Modulate (album)
paragraph: Modulate is Bob Mould's fifth solo album, released in 2002. [SBD]  Although a few tracks on his previous release, "The Last Dog and Pony Show", had featured tape loops and samples, Mould shocked his fans with such a dramatic embrace of electronica. " [SBD] Rolling Stone" magazine awarded the album 2 ⁄ stars out of five, declaring: "Ultimately, this is a rock record with electronic effects, not a techno record with guitars, and it falls short of being totally satisfying as either."

title: Evolver (311 album)
paragraph: Evolver is the seventh studio album by 311 and the second recorded in 311's recording studio The Hive in North Hollywood, California. [SBD]  Despite the success of the single "Creatures (For a While)" (which reached #3 on the Billboard Modern Rock Tracks chart) and positive reaction from their fanbase, "Evolver" became the first 311 album to not receive an RIAA certification.

title: Dominic Dale
paragraph: Dominic Dale (born Christopher Dale on 29 December 1971) is a Welsh professional snooker player and occasional snooker commentator and presenter for the BBC. [SBD]  He is often referred to by commentators as the greatest player never to have been in the top 16.

title: Japanese Brazilians
paragraph: Japanese Brazilians (日系ブラジル人 , Nikkei Burajiru-jin ) are Brazilian citizens who are nationals or naturals of Japanese ancestry, or Japanese immigrants living in Brazil.

title: Bob Chaperon
paragraph: Robert "Bob" Chaperon (born 18 May 1958) is a Canadian retired professional snooker and billiards player.

title: Nigrostriatal pathway
paragraph: The nigrostriatal pathway or the nigrostriatal bundle (NSB), is a dopaminergic pathway that connects the substantia nigra pars compacta (SNc) with the dorsal striatum (i.e., the caudate nucleus and putamen). [SBD]  It is one of the four major dopamine pathways in the brain, and is particularly involved in the production of movement, as part of a system called the basal ganglia motor loop. [SBD]  Dopaminergic neurons of this pathway synapse onto GABAergic neurons.

title: Togiola Tulafono
paragraph: Togiola Talalelei A. Tulafono (born February 28, 1947) is an American Samoan politician and lawyer who served as the 56th Governor of American Samoa. [SBD]  He is a member of the Democratic Party. [SBD]  He had previously served as lieutenant governor, taking this position on January 3, 1997.

title: Tauese Sunia
paragraph: Tauese Tuailemafua Pita Fiti Sunia (August 29, 1941 – March 26, 2003) was the Governor of American Samoa from 1997 until his death in 2003. [SBD]  He was the second Governor of American Samoa to die in office.

title: A. P. Lutali
paragraph: Aifili Paulo Lauvao (December 24, 1919 – August 1, 2002), was twice governor of American Samoa (1985–89, 1993–97). [SBD]  The founder of the U.S territory's Democratic Party, he had a long career in the legislature and the judiciary in American Samoa.

title: H. Rex Lee
paragraph: Hyrum Rex Lee (April 8, 1910 – July 26, 2001) was an American government employee and diplomat who was the last non-elected Governor of American Samoa. [SBD]  Lee served as governor from 1961 to 1967, and again briefly from 1977 to 1978.

title: Amanda Sefton
paragraph: Amanda Sefton (real name Jimaine Szardos) (also known as Daytripper and the second Magik) is a fictional character, a witch in the Marvel Universe. [SBD]  She is the foster sister and lover of Kurt Wagner, Nightcrawler of the X-Men.

title: Disco 2
paragraph: Disco 2 is the eighth album by UK electronic music duo Pet Shop Boys. [SBD]  Released in September 1994 by Parlophone Records, it consists of remixes of songs from their 1990 "Behaviour",1993 "Very" and B-sides from the time.

title: Wet Mountain Valley
paragraph: The Wet Mountain Valley is a high elevation mountain valley located in Custer County, in south-central Colorado.

title: Peter Tali Coleman
paragraph: Peter Tali Coleman (December 8, 1919 – April 28, 1997) was the first person of Samoan descent to be appointed Governor of American Samoa and later became the territory's first popularly elected governor. [SBD]  A member of the Republican Party, he is the only U.S. governor whose service spanned five decades (1956–1961, 1978–1985 and 1989–1993) and one of the longest-serving governors of any jurisdiction in American history.

title: Electronic viewfinder
paragraph: An electronic viewfinder (EVF) is a camera viewfinder where the image captured by the lens is projected electronically onto a miniature display. [SBD]  The image on this display is used to assist in aiming the camera at the scene to be photographed. [SBD]  It differs from a live preview screen in being smaller and shaded from ambient light.

title: Sloulin Field International Airport
paragraph: Sloulin Field International Airport (IATA: ISN, ICAO: KISN, FAA LID: ISN) is an airport serving Williston, a city in North Dakota. [SBD]  It is two miles north of downtown and is owned and operated by the City. [SBD]  Built in 1947, the airport faces expansion constraints, design issues, and the need for runway refurbishment. [SBD]  For these reasons, as well as the rise in air traffic amid the North Dakota oil boom, officials have decided to build Williston Basin International Airport. [SBD]  This airport will replace Sloulin Field Airport, which will be decommissioned.

title: Bilingual (album)
paragraph: Bilingual is the sixth studio album by English synthpop duo Pet Shop Boys, released on 2 September 1996 by Parlophone. [SBD]  The album reached number four on the UK Albums Chart, lower than their previous five studio albums which had all reached the top three. [SBD]  It yielded five singles which all reached the UK top 20—all but one of which charted inside the top 10.

title: John Mosier
paragraph: John Mosier is an American academic known for his work in English, film, and history. [SBD]  Mosier is currently a professor of English at Loyola University New Orleans.

title: Etienne Ys
paragraph: Etienne Nestor Ys (born 26 February 1962) is a Netherlands Antilles politician.

title: Jamestown Regional Airport
paragraph: Jamestown Regional Airport (IATA: JMS, ICAO: KJMS, FAA LID: JMS) is a public use airport located two nautical miles (4 km) northeast of the central business district of Jamestown, a city in Stutsman County, North Dakota, United States. [SBD]  It is owned by the Jamestown Regional Airport Authority and was formerly known as Jamestown Municipal Airport. [SBD]  It is mostly used for general aviation but is also served by one commercial airline, with flights twice each weekday and once on Saturdays and Sundays. [SBD]  Scheduled passenger service is subsidized by the Essential Air Service program.

title: Hi-MD
paragraph: In January 2004, Sony announced the Hi-MD media storage format as a further development of the MiniDisc format. [SBD]  With its release in later 2004, came the ability to use newly developed, high-capacity 1 gigabyte Hi-MD discs, sporting the same dimensions as regular MiniDiscs. [SBD]  The Hi-MD format can be considered obsolete as the last recorder/player was discontinued in 2011. [SBD]  The discs themselves were withdrawn from sale in September 2012, though regular MiniDiscs are still available ().

title: Outer Circle railway line
paragraph: The Outer Circle was built in 1891 as a steam-era suburban railway line, in Melbourne, Australia. [SBD]  It covered much of the modern City of Boroondara, including the suburbs of (from north to south) Kew East, Camberwell, Burwood, Ashburton, and Malvern East. [SBD]  At its longest stage, it ran from Fairfield station, on what is today the Hurstbridge line, to Oakleigh station, on the current Pakenham and Cranbourne lines.

title: Alfred Blalock
paragraph: Alfred Blalock (April 5, 1899 – September 15, 1964) was a 20th-century American surgeon most noted for his research on the medical condition of shock as well as Tetralogy of Fallot— commonly known as Blue baby syndrome. [SBD]  He developed the Blalock-Thomas-Taussig Shunt, a surgical procedure he developed together with surgical technician Vivien Thomas and pediatric cardiologist Helen Taussig to relieve the cyanosis from Tetralogy of Fallot. [SBD]  This operation ushered in the modern era of cardiac surgery. [SBD]  Blalock worked at both Vanderbilt University and the Johns Hopkins University, where he studied both as an undergraduate and worked as chief of surgery. [SBD]  He is known as a medical pioneer who won various awards, including Albert Lasker Clinical Medical Research Award. [SBD]  Blalock was also nominated several times for the prestigious Nobel Prize in Medicine.

title: Spirituali
paragraph: The Spirituali were members of a reform movement within the Roman Catholic Church, which existed from the 1530s to the 1560s. [SBD]  The movement is sometimes also called evangelism.

title: Spider-Man and Captain America in Doctor Doom's Revenge
paragraph: Spider-Man and Captain America in Doctor Doom's Revenge

title: Capitol (short story collection)
paragraph: Capitol (1979) was Orson Scott Card's second published book. [SBD]  This collection of eleven short stories set in the Worthing series is no longer in print. [SBD]  However six of the stories have been reprinted in "The Worthing Saga" (1990) and one of them in "Maps in a Mirror" (1990).

title: Archie Meets the Punisher
paragraph: Archie Meets the Punisher, or The Punisher Meets Archie, (August 1994) was a one-shot comic book intercompany crossover published under two separate covers by Marvel Comics and Archie Comics, but with the same interior content.

title: USS John L. Hall (FFG-32)
paragraph: USS "John L. Hall" (FFG-32), twenty-sixth ship of the "Oliver Hazard Perry" class of guided-missile frigates, was named for Admiral John L. Hall, Jr. (1891–1978). [SBD]  Her mission is to provide in-depth protection for military and merchant shipping, amphibious task forces, and underway replenishment groups.

title: Alternative worship
paragraph: Alternative worship is "what happens when people create worship for themselves," according to Steve Collins. [SBD]  As a phenomenon it began mainly in Europe, Australia and New Zealand in the late 1980s and early 1990s. [SBD]  It is practiced by Christians across the age-range, although has a particular following amongst adults in their 20s and 30s.

title: Grand Forks International Airport
paragraph: Grand Forks International Airport (IATA: GFK, ICAO: KGFK, FAA LID: GFK) is a public airport five miles (8 km) northwest of Grand Forks, in Grand Forks County, North Dakota. [SBD]  GFK has no scheduled passenger flights out of the country but has an "international" title (like many other airports) because it has customs service for arrivals from Canada and other countries.

title: Pax Mongolica
paragraph: The Pax Mongolica (Latin for "Mongol Peace"), less often known as Pax Tatarica ("Tatar Peace") is a historiographical term, modelled after the original phrase "Pax Romana", which describes the stabilising effects of the conquests of the Mongol Empire on the social, cultural, and economic life of the inhabitants of the vast Eurasian territory that the Mongols conquered in the 13th and 14th centuries. [SBD]  The term is used to describe the eased communication and commerce the unified administration helped to create, and the period of relative peace that followed the Mongols' vast conquests.

title: Nightlife (Pet Shop Boys album)
paragraph: Nightlife is the seventh studio album by English synthpop duo Pet Shop Boys, released on 8 October 1999 by Parlophone. [SBD]  After the release and promotion of their previous album, "Bilingual", Pet Shop Boys started work with playwright Jonathan Harvey on the stage musical that eventually became "Closer to Heaven" (at one stage during the writing process, the musical was given the name of "Nightlife"). [SBD]  Pet Shop Boys soon had an album's worth of tracks and decided to release the album "Nightlife" as a concept album and in order to showcase some of the songs that would eventually make it into the musical.

title: By-product
paragraph: A by-product is a secondary product derived from a manufacturing process or chemical reaction. [SBD]  It is not the primary product or service being produced. [SBD]  In the context of production, a by-product is the 'output from a joint production process that is minor in quantity and/or net realizable value (NRV) when compared with the main products'. [SBD]  Because they are deemed to have no influence on reported financial results, by-products do not receive allocations of joint costs. By-products also by convention are not inventoried, but the NRV from by-products is typically recognized as 'other income' or as a reduction of joint production processing costs when the by-product is produced. [SBD]  A by-product can be useful and marketable or it can be considered waste.

title: Alan Huckle
paragraph: Alan Edden Huckle (born 15 June 1948) is a senior diplomat in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office of the British Government. [SBD]  He was the commissioner of the British Indian Ocean Territory (BIOT) and the British Antarctic Territory from 23 April 2001 until 12 January 2004, when he left to become the governor of Anguilla in the Caribbean. [SBD]  He was the Governor of Anguilla from 28 May 2004 to July 2006, having been appointed in July 2003.

title: Osbourne Fleming
paragraph: Osbourne Berrington Fleming (born February 18, 1940) is a politician and a former chief minister of Anguilla. [SBD]  He held that post from March 6, 2000, three days after the Anguilla United Front, a conservative coalition which included Fleming's Anguilla National Alliance won parliamentary elections, gaining at least 4 of the 7 seats, until February 15 in which he retired from his seat as the chief minister of Anguilla. [SBD]  Mr. Fleming was a prominent and successful businessman prior to entering politics. [SBD]  He served for many years as Minister of Finance before winning election as Anguilla's Chief Minister.

title: USS Jarrett (FFG-33)
paragraph: USS "Jarrett" (FFG-33), was the twenty-fifth ship of the "Oliver Hazard Perry"-class guided missile frigates, was named for Vice Admiral Harry B. Jarrett (1898–1974).

paragraph: The problem play is a form of drama that emerged during the 19th century as part of the wider movement of realism in the arts, especially following the innovations of Henrik Ibsen. [SBD]  It deals with contentious social issues through debates between the characters on stage, who typically represent conflicting points of view within a realistic social context. [SBD]  Critic Chris Baldick writes that the genre emerged "from the ferment of the 1890s... for the most part inspired by the example of Ibsen's realistic stage representations of serious familial and social conflicts." paragraph: Alkaline batteries (IEC code: L) are a type of primary battery dependent upon the reaction between zinc and manganese dioxide (Zn/MnO).

title: XML Signature
paragraph: XML Signature (also called "XMLDSig", "XML-DSig", "XML-Sig") defines an XML syntax for digital signatures and is defined in the W3C recommendation XML Signature Syntax and Processing. [SBD]  Functionally, it has much in common with PKCS#7 but is more extensible and geared towards signing XML documents. [SBD]  It is used by various Web technologies such as SOAP, SAML, and others.

paragraph: USS "Aubrey Fitch" (FFG-34), the twenty-sixth ship of the "Oliver Hazard Perry"-class of guided-missile frigates, was named for Vice-Admiral Aubrey Fitch (1883–1978), who was noted for his outstanding command work in the South Pacific during World War II.

title: West Indian whistling duck
paragraph: The West Indian whistling duck ("Dendrocygna arborea") is a whistling duck that breeds in the Caribbean. [SBD]  Alternative names are black-billed whistling duck and Cuban whistling duck.

title: Alpha Oumar Konaré
paragraph: Alpha Oumar Konaré (born 2 February 1946) is a former President of Mali for two five-year terms (1992 to 2002), and was Chairperson of the African Union Commission from 2003 to 2008.

title: Qahtan Muhammad al-Shaabi
paragraph: Qahtan Muhammad al-Shaabi (1920–7 July 1981) (Arabic: قحطان محمد الشعبي‎ ‎ ) was the first President of the People's Republic of South Yemen. [SBD]  Al-Shaabi's National Liberation Front (NLF) political organisation wrested control of the country from the British and won political supremacy over the opposition Front for the Liberation of Occupied South Yemen (FLOSY) in 1967. [SBD]  On 30 November 1967, the protectorate of South Arabia was declared independent as the People's Republic of South Yemen with al-Shaabi as President. [SBD]  Al-Shaabi held the presidency until 22 June 1969, when a hard-line Marxist group from within his own NLF seized control. [SBD]  He was replaced by Salim Rubai Ali (Salmin) and jailed, then placed under house arrest until the 1970s, and lived quietly in Aden from his release until his death in 1981.

title: Puppetry of the Penis
paragraph: Puppetry of the Penis is a performance show. [SBD]  The show was initially conceived by Australian Simon Morley as the title of an art calendar, showcasing 12 of his favourite penis installations (known as Dick Tricks). [SBD]  On New Year's Eve in 1997 he had a garage full of calendars to sell, and with requests for live demonstrations mounting he finally decided to create an act with fellow Aussie David "Friendy" Friend.

title: Faysal al-Shaabi
paragraph: Faysal Abd al-Latif al-Shaabi (Arabic: فيصل عبد الطيف الشعبي‎ ‎ ) (1935–2 April 1970) was the Prime Minister of the People's Republic of South Yemen from 6 April 1969 until the political coup that led to Salim Ali Rubai's ascendance to power on 22 June 1969. [SBD]  Al-Shaabi was appointed Prime Minister by President Qahtan Mohammed al-Shaabi.

title: Charles Frederick Worth
paragraph: Charles Frederick Worth ( ; ] ; 13 October 1825 – 10 March 1895) was an English fashion designer who founded the House of Worth, one of the foremost fashion houses of the 19th and early 20th centuries. [SBD]  He is considered by many fashion historians to be the father of haute couture. [SBD]  Worth is also credited with revolutionising the business of fashion.

title: Syrup (novel)
paragraph: Syrup is a novel written by Max Barry under the pseudonym Maxx Barry, which satirizes consumerism and marketing techniques. [SBD]  It is Barry's debut novel, published in 1999, and adapted into a movie in 2013.

title: Closer to Heaven
paragraph: Closer to Heaven is a musical by Jonathan Harvey and Pet Shop Boys. [SBD]  It was premiered in May 2001 at the Arts Theatre in London, opening to mixed reviews, and ran until 13 October 2001. [SBD]  A second production of "Closer to Heaven" was premiered in Australia in 2005.

title: Eon Productions
paragraph: Eon Productions (an abbreviation of Everything or Nothing) is a British film production company that produces the "James Bond" film series. [SBD]  The company is based in London's Piccadilly and also operates from Pinewood Studios in the United Kingdom.

title: Federation of South Arabia
paragraph: The Federation of South Arabia (Arabic: اتحاد الجنوب العربي‎ ‎ "Ittiḥād al-Janūb al-‘Arabī ") was an organization of states under British protection in what would become South Yemen. [SBD]  It was formed on 4 April 1962 from the 15 protected states of the Federation of Arab Emirates of the South. [SBD]  On 18 January 1963 it was merged with the Crown colony of Aden. [SBD]  In June 1964, the Upper Aulaqi Sultanate was added for a total of 17 states. [SBD]  A team was sent to the 1966 Commonwealth Games in Kingston, Jamaica. [SBD]  The Federation was abolished when it gained independence along with the Protectorate of South Arabia as the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen on 30 November 1967.

title: Alternative (album)
paragraph: Alternative is a compilation album by English synthpop duo Pet Shop Boys. [SBD]  It was first released in 1995.

title: Chuwit Kamolvisit
paragraph: Chuwit Kamolvisit (Thai: ชูวิทย์ กมลวิศิษฎ์ ; rtgs: Chuwit Kamonwisit ; 29 August 1961 – ) is a controversial Thai politician who was once the country's biggest massage parlour owner. [SBD]  After an arrest in 2003, he publicly claimed that he paid large bribes to many Thai police officers. [SBD]  He then sold some of his massage parlors, formed his own political party and unsuccessfully ran for Bangkok governor in August 2004. [SBD]  In 2005 he was elected for a four-year term to the Thai House of Representatives, but in 2006 the Constitutional Court removed him from parliament. [SBD]  In October 2008 he again ran for governor of Bangkok as an independent but was not elected. [SBD]  In the July 2011 general election his party won four seats in the House of Representatives. [SBD]  He used the pseudonym Davis Kamol on occasion.

title: Mirador (Tarnation album)
paragraph: Mirador is a 1997 album by the band Tarnation, which was led by Paula Frazer. [SBD]  It was released on 4AD in the UK and Europe, and on Reprise/Warner Bros. [SBD]  Records in the US. [SBD]  The American edition features a different album cover from the European version.

title: Abdullah al-Sallal
paragraph: Abdullah al-Sallal (January 9, 1917 – March 5, 1994) (Arabic: عبد الله السلال‎ ‎ ) was the leader of the North Yemeni Revolution of 1962. [SBD]  He served as the first President of the Yemen Arab Republic from 27 September 1962 to 5 November 1967.

title: Pen spinning
paragraph: Pen spinning is a form of object manipulation that involves the deft manipulation of a writing instrument with one's hands. [SBD]  Although it is often considered a form of self-entertainment (usually in a school or office setting), multinational competitions and meetings are sometimes held. [SBD]  It is sometimes classified as a form of contact juggling; however, some tricks do leave contact with the body. [SBD]  Pen spinning is called pen mawashi or, more rarely and disparagingly, "rōnin mawashi" ("rejected student spinning") in Japan, where the pastime has been popular since at least the 1970s and where the Pen Spinning Association Japan is now dedicated to promoting the aspiring art form. [SBD]  Pen spinning has quickly gained international popularity through online video sharing and forums. [SBD]  According to Masaki Tsukada, chairman of the Japanese pen spinners, pen spinning now has dedicated movements in South Korea and the United States.

title: Hamoud al-Gayifi
paragraph: Hamoud Al-Jaifi (Arabic: حمود الجائفي‎ ‎ ) (born 1918 - died March 22, 1985 ), was a Prime Minister of the Yemen Arab Republic. [SBD]  He served from 29 April 1964 to 6 January 1965, under President Abdullah as-Sallal.

title: Agave vilmoriniana
paragraph: Agave vilmoriniana, sometimes misspelled "vilmoriana", and popularly known as Octopus agave, is a species of agave endemic to Mexico. [SBD]  It is known for its untoothed arching and twisting leaves.

title: End-of-train device
paragraph: The end of train device (ETD), sometimes referred to as an EOT, flashing rear-end device (FRED) or sense and braking unit (SBU) is an electronic device mounted on the end of freight trains in lieu of a caboose. [SBD]  They are divided into three categories: "dumb" units, which only provide a visible indication of the rear of the train with a flashing red taillight; "average intelligence" units with a brake pipe pressure gauge; and "smart" units, which send back data to the crew in the locomotive via radio-based telemetry. [SBD]  They originated in North America, and are also used elsewhere in the world, where they may include complete End of Train Air System (ETAS) or Sense and Brake Unit (SBU) devices.

title: Limited-slip differential
paragraph: A limited-slip differential is a type of differential that allows its two output shafts to rotate at different speeds but limits the maximum difference between the two shafts.

title: Mills Godwin
paragraph: Mills Edwin Godwin Jr. (November 19, 1914January 30, 1999) of Chuckatuck, Virginia, was an American politician who was the 60th and 62nd Governor of Virginia for two non-consecutive terms, from 1966 to 1970 and from 1974 to 1978.

title: Michael Lockwood (guitarist)
paragraph: Michael Dean Lockwood (born May 22, 1961) is an American guitarist and producer, a native of Hawthorne, California, best known for producing and performing with Lisa Marie Presley, Aimee Mann and Fiona Apple among others.

title: Jim Gilmore
paragraph: James Stuart Gilmore III (born October 6, 1949) is an American politician and former attorney who was the 68th Governor of Virginia from 1998 to 2002 and Chairman of the Republican National Committee in 2001.

title: Artemisia annua
paragraph: Artemisia annua, also known as sweet wormwood, sweet annie, sweet sagewort, annual mugwort or annual wormwood (), is a common type of wormwood native to temperate Asia, but naturalized in many countries including scattered parts of North America.

title: Quatro de Fevereiro Airport
paragraph: Quatro de Fevereiro International Airport (Portuguese: "Aeroporto Internacional 4 de Fevereiro" ), (IATA: LAD, ICAO: FNLU) is the main international airport of Angola. [SBD]  It is located in the southern part of the capital Luanda, situated in the Luanda Province. [SBD]  "Quatro de Fevereiro" means 4 February, which is an important national holiday in Angola, marking the start of the armed struggle against the Portuguese colonial regime on 4 February 1961. [SBD]  In 2009, about 1.8 million passengers were counted.

title: Cahul
paragraph: Cahul (] ; also known by other alternative names) is a city and municipality in southern Moldova. [SBD]  The city is the administrative center of Cahul District; it also administers one village, Cotihana. [SBD]  As of 1 January 2009, it has an estimated population of 39,400.

title: Modern Age (periodical)
paragraph: Modern Age is an American conservative academic quarterly journal, founded in 1957 by Russell Kirk in close collaboration with Henry Regnery. [SBD]  Originally published independently in Chicago, in 1976 ownership was transferred to the Intercollegiate Studies Institute.

title: Play (Moby album)
paragraph: Play is the fifth studio album by American electronica musician Moby. [SBD]  It was first released on May 17, 1999 by Mute and V2. [SBD]  Recording of the album began in 1998, following the release of his fourth album, "Animal Rights" (1996), which deviated from Moby's electronica style; his goal for "Play" was to return to this style of music. [SBD]  Originally intended to be his final record, the recording of the album took place at Moby's home studio in Manhattan, New York.

title: Houari Boumediene Airport
paragraph: Houari Boumediene Airport (Arabic: مطار هواري بومدين الدولي‎ ‎ , French: "Aéroport d'Alger Houari Boumediene" ) (IATA: ALG, ICAO: DAAG) , also known as Algiers Airport or Algiers International Airport, is an international airport serving Algiers, the capital of Algeria. [SBD]  It is located 9.1 NM east southeast of the city.

title: Hydrocharitaceae
paragraph: Hydrocharitaceae is a flowering plant family including 16 known genera with a total of ca 135 known species (Christenhusz & Byng 2016 ), that including a number of species of aquatic plant, for instance the tape-grasses, the well known Canadian waterweed and frogbit "Hydrocharis morsus-ranae".

title: Artemisinin
paragraph: Artemisinin, also known as qinghao su (), and its semi-synthetic derivatives are a group of drugs used against "Plasmodium falciparum" malaria. [SBD]  It was discovered by Tu Youyou, a Chinese scientist, who was awarded half of the 2015 Nobel Prize in Medicine for her discovery.
