[SBD]  Treatments containing an artemisinin derivative (artemisinin-combination therapies, ACTs) are now standard treatment worldwide for "P. falciparum" malaria. [SBD]  Artemisinin is isolated from the plant "Artemisia annua", sweet wormwood, a herb employed in Chinese traditional medicine. [SBD]  A precursor compound can be produced using genetically engineered yeast.

title: Teany
paragraph: Teany, sometimes stylized as TeaNY or teany, was a tea café, restaurant and beverage distributor in New York City founded by electronic musician Moby with ex-girlfriend, Kelly Tisdale. [SBD]  The Teany Café opened in 2002 in the Lower East Side of Manhattan, New York at 90 Rivington Street and closed in 2015.

title: Compulsory purchase order
paragraph: A compulsory purchase order (CPO) is a legal function in the United Kingdom and Ireland that allows certain bodies which need to obtain land or property to do so without the consent of the owner. [SBD]  It may be enforced if a proposed development is considered one for public betterment; for example, when building motorways where a land owner does not want to sell. [SBD]  Similarly, if town councils wish to develop a town centre, they may issue compulsory purchase orders.

title: Kircubbin, County Down
paragraph: Kircubbin is a village and townland in County Down, Northern Ireland. [SBD]  It is on the shores of Strangford Lough, between Newtownards and Portaferry, in the Borough of Ards. [SBD]  The village harbour contains leisure craft, yachts, and a sailing club. [SBD]  The main street was remodelled in 2008 with some old houses knocked down and rebuilt as new. [SBD]  the village had a population of 1,153 people in the 2011 Census.

title: Dirty Devil River
paragraph: The Dirty Devil River is an 80 mi tributary of the Colorado River, located in the U.S. state of Utah. [SBD]  It flows through southern Utah from the confluence of Fremont River and Muddy Creek to the Colorado River.

title: Azimuth thruster
paragraph: An azimuth thruster is a configuration of marine propellers placed in pods that can be rotated to any horizontal angle (azimuth), making a rudder unnecessary. [SBD]  These give ships better maneuverability than a fixed propeller and rudder system.

title: Jack Russell (priest)
paragraph: John "Jack" Russell (21 December 1795 – 28 April 1883), known as "The Sporting Parson", vicar of Swimbridge and rector of Black Torrington in North Devon, was an enthusiastic fox-hunter and dog breeder, who developed the Jack Russell Terrier, a variety of the Fox Terrier breed.

title: Patrick Watson (producer)
paragraph: Patrick Watson, CC (born December 23, 1929) has been a prolific and outspoken Canadian broadcaster, television and radio interviewer and host, author, commentator, and television writer, producer, and director for five decades. [SBD]  Born in Toronto, Watson attended the University of Toronto and graduated with an MA. [SBD]  He began working on his doctorate at the University of Michigan, but withdrew in early 1956 to focus on working for CBC Television.

title: Samuel Hunter Christie
paragraph: Samuel Hunter Christie (22 March 1784 – 24 January 1865) was a British scientist, physicist and mathematician.

title: Taylor Institution
paragraph: The Taylor Institution (commonly known as the Taylorian) is the Oxford University library dedicated to the study of the European Languages. [SBD]  Its building also includes lecture rooms used by the Faculty of Medieval and Modern Languages, University of Oxford. [SBD]  Since 1889 a prestigious Annual Lecture on a subject of Foreign Literature has been given at the Taylorian Institution.

title: Helmut Hasse
paragraph: Helmut Hasse (] ; 25 August 1898 – 26 December 1979) was a German mathematician working in algebraic number theory, known for fundamental contributions to class field theory, the application of p-adic numbers to local class field theory and diophantine geometry (Hasse principle), and to local zeta functions.

title: Gilbertese language
paragraph: Taetae ni Kiribati or Gilbertese, also Kiribati (sometimes "Kiribatese"), is a Micronesian language of the Austronesian language family. [SBD]  It has a basic verb–object–subject word order.

title: Hyde (musician)
paragraph: Hideto Takarai (寶井 秀人 , Takarai Hideto , born January 29, 1969 in Wakayama, Japan) , known exclusively by his stage name Hyde, is a Japanese musician, singer, songwriter, producer, and actor. [SBD]  He is best known as the lead vocalist for the rock band L'Arc-en-Ciel, as well as for Vamps. [SBD]  As a member of L'Arc-en-Ciel, his stage name is stylized as hyde, while as a solo artist and a member of Vamps it is stylized as HYDE.

title: Basil Blackwell
paragraph: Sir Basil Henry Blackwell (29 May 18899 April 1984) was born in Oxford, England. [SBD]  He was the son of Benjamin Henry Blackwell (18491924), founder of Blackwell's bookshop in Oxford, which went on to become the Blackwell's family publishing and bookshop empire, located on Broad Street in central Oxford. [SBD]  The publishing arm is now part of Wiley-Blackwell.

title: Mbeki
paragraph: Mbeki is a surname. [SBD]  Notable people with the surname include:

title: Miniature Fox Terrier
paragraph: The Miniature Fox Terrier is a small, fine, lightweight working terrier developed as a hunting dog and vermin router. [SBD]  It is known colloquially in its native Australia as the “Mini Foxie”.

title: Instrumentality of Mankind
paragraph: In the science fiction of Cordwainer Smith, the Instrumentality of Mankind refers both to Smith's personal future history and universe and to the central government of humanity. [SBD]  "The Instrumentality of Mankind" is also the title of a paperback collection of short stories by Cordwainer Smith published in 1979 (now superseded by the later "The Rediscovery of Man", which collects all of Smith's short stories).

title: Operation Sundevil
paragraph: Operation Sundevil was a 1990 nationwide United States Secret Service crackdown on "illegal computer hacking activities." [SBD]  It involved raids in approximately fifteen different cities and resulted in three arrests and the confiscation of computers, the contents of electronic bulletin board systems (BBSes), and floppy disks. [SBD]  It was revealed in a press release on May 9, 1990. [SBD]  The arrests and subsequent court cases resulted in the creation of the Electronic Frontier Foundation. [SBD]  The operation is now seen as largely a public-relations stunt. [SBD]  Operation Sundevil has also been viewed as one of the preliminary attacks on the Legion of Doom and similar hacking groups. [SBD]  The raid on Steve Jackson Games, which led to the court case "Steve Jackson Games, Inc. v. United States Secret Service", is often attributed to Operation Sundevil, but the Electronic Frontier Foundation states that it is unrelated and cites this attribution as a media error.

title: American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee
paragraph: The American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee, also known as the Joint or the JDC, is a Jewish relief organization based in New York City.

title: Competitive examination
paragraph: A competitive examination is an examination where candidates are ranked according to their grades. [SBD]  If the examination is open for "n" positions, then the first "n" candidates in ranks pass, the others are rejected.

title: Tarski monster group
paragraph: In the area of modern algebra known as group theory, a Tarski monster group, named for Alfred Tarski, is an infinite group "G", such that every proper subgroup "H" of "G", other than the identity subgroup, is a cyclic group of order a fixed prime number "p". [SBD]  A Tarski monster group is necessarily simple. [SBD]  It was shown by A. Yu. [SBD]  Olshanskii in 1979 that Tarski groups exist, and that there is a Tarski "p"-group for every prime "p" > 10. [SBD]  They are a source of counterexamples to conjectures in group theory, most importantly to Burnside's problem and the von Neumann conjecture.

title: The Midwich Cuckoos
paragraph: The Midwich Cuckoos is a science fiction novel written by English author John Wyndham, published during 1957. [SBD]  It has been filmed twice as "Village of the Damned", with releases during 1960 and 1995.

title: Foreign exchange spot
paragraph: A foreign exchange spot transaction, also known as FX spot, is an agreement between two parties to buy one currency against selling another currency at an agreed price for settlement on the spot date. [SBD]  The exchange rate at which the transaction is done is called the spot exchange rate. [SBD]  As of 2010, the average daily turnover of global FX spot transactions reached nearly 1.5 trillion USD, counting 37.4% of all foreign exchange transactions. [SBD]  FX spot transactions increased by 38% to 2.0 trillion USD from April 2010 to April 2013.

title: Eburones
paragraph: The Eburones (Greek: Ἐβούρωνες , Strabo), were a Celtic tribe who lived in the northeast of Gaul, in what is now the southern Netherlands, eastern Belgium, and the German Rhineland, in the period immediately before this region was conquered by Rome. [SBD]  Though living in Gaul, they were also described as being both Belgae, and Germani (for a discussion of these terms, see below).

title: Prognosis
paragraph: Prognosis (Greek: πρόγνωσις "fore-knowing, foreseeing") is a medical term for predicting the likelihood of a person's survival. [SBD]  When applied to large statistical populations, prognostic estimates can be very accurate: for example the statement "45% of patients with severe septic shock will die within 28 days" can be made with some confidence, because previous research found that this proportion of patients died. [SBD]  This statistical information does not apply to the prognosis for each individual patient: additional information is needed to determine whether a patient belongs to the 45% who will die, or to the 55% who survive.

title: Raid on the Medway
paragraph: The Raid on the Medway during the Second Anglo-Dutch War in June 1667, sometimes called the Battle of the Medway, Raid on Chatham or the Battle of Chatham, was a successful and daring attack conducted by the Dutch navy deep upriver targeting the largest English naval battleships at a time when most were virtually unmanned and unarmed, laid up due to lack of funding in the fleet anchorages off Chatham Dockyard and Gillingham in the county of Kent. [SBD]  At the time, the fortress of Upnor Castle and a barrier chain called the "Gillingham Line" were supposed to protect the mothballed naval ships anchored off Chatham, the main English naval base in southeastern Stuart England.

title: Sadat
paragraph: Sadat (Arabic: سادات ‎ ‎ ) is a given name and family name. [SBD]  It is common to Middle Easterners, mostly those of Turkish or Persian descent.

title: Nekeme Prod
paragraph: Nekeme Prod is the name of a French free video games development association (law 1901). [SBD]  The aim of this team is to regroup all the skills needed to create a game from A to Z.

title: Adforton
paragraph: Adforton is a small village and civil parish in north Herefordshire, England. [SBD]  It is located north of Wigmore, close to the Wales border, and is surrounded by agricultural fields.

title: Hank Marvin
paragraph: Hank Brian Marvin (born Brian Robson Rankin, 28 October 1941) is an English multi-instrumentalist, vocalist and songwriter. [SBD]  He is best known as the lead guitarist for the Shadows, a group which primarily performed instrumentals and was the backing band for Cliff Richard and subsequently for Marvin, Welch & Farrar. [SBD]  Many leading British and Canadian rock guitarists cite Marvin as an influence.

title: Sodium–sulfur battery
paragraph: A sodium–sulfur battery is a type of molten-salt battery constructed from liquid sodium (Na) and sulfur (S). [SBD]  This type of battery has a high energy density, high efficiency of charge/discharge (89–92%) and long cycle life, and is fabricated from inexpensive materials. [SBD]  The operating temperatures of 300 to 350 °C and the highly corrosive nature of the sodium polysulfides, primarily make them suitable for stationary energy storage applications. [SBD]  The cell becomes more economical with increasing size.

title: Pseudomorph
paragraph: In mineralogy, a pseudomorph is a mineral or mineral compound that appears in an atypical form (crystal system), resulting from a substitution process in which the appearance and dimensions remain constant, but the original mineral is replaced by another. [SBD]  The name literally means "false form".

title: European People's Party
paragraph: The European People's Party (EPP) is a European political party. [SBD]  A transnational organisation, it is composed of other political parties, not individuals. [SBD]  Founded by primarily Christian democratic parties in 1976, it has since broadened its membership to include liberal-conservative parties and parties with other centre-right political perspectives.

title: Sea Pictures
paragraph: Sea Pictures, Op. 37 is a song cycle by Sir Edward Elgar consisting of five songs written by various poets. [SBD]  It was set for contralto and orchestra, though a distinct version for piano was often performed by Elgar. [SBD]  Many mezzo-sopranos have sung the piece.

title: Roland Dorgelès
paragraph: Roland Dorgelès (] ; 15 June 1885 – 18 March 1973) was a French novelist and a member of the Académie Goncourt.

title: Claude Dornier
paragraph: Claude (Claudius) Honoré Désiré Dornier (born in Kempten im Allgäu on May 14, 1884 – December 5, 1969) was a German airplane builder and founder of Dornier GmbH. [SBD]  His legacy remains in the aircraft named after him, including the 12-engine Dornier Do X flying boat, for decades the world's largest and most powerful airplane.

title: Indigo (disambiguation)
paragraph: Indigo is a color between blue and violet.

title: Thomas Wilson Dorr
paragraph: Thomas Wilson Dorr (November 5, 1805December 27, 1854), was an American politician and reformer in Rhode Island, best known for leading the Dorr Rebellion, an effort to broaden the franchise in the state for white males and to change apportionment in the legislature for better representation of urban populations.

title: Pentagonal hexecontahedron
paragraph: In geometry, a pentagonal hexecontahedron is a Catalan solid, dual of the snub dodecahedron. [SBD]  It has two distinct forms, which are mirror images (or "enantiomorphs") of each other. [SBD]  It is also well-known to be the Catalan solid with the most vertices. [SBD]  Among the Catalan and Archimedean solids, it has the second largest number of vertices, after the truncated icosidodecahedron, which has 120 vertices.

title: John Thompson Dorrance
paragraph: John Thompson Dorrance (November 11, 1873 – September 21, 1930) was an American chemist who discovered a method to create condensed soup, and served as president of the Campbell Soup Company from 1914 to 1930.

title: Freestylers
paragraph: The Freestylers are a British electronic music group, consisting of producers Matt Cantor and Aston Harvey. [SBD]  They have released five studio albums and a number of mix compilations for, among others, Fabric and BBC Radio.

title: Osvaldo Dorticós Torrado
paragraph: Osvaldo Dorticós Torrado (April 17, 1919 – June 23, 1983) was a Cuban politician who served as the President of Cuba from 1959 until 1976.

title: The Hacker's Diet
paragraph: The Hacker's Diet (humorously subtitled ""How to lose weight and hair through stress and poor nutrition"") is a diet plan created by the founder of Autodesk, John Walker, outlined in an electronic book of the same name, that attempts to aid the process of weight loss by more accurately modeling how calories consumed and calories expended actually impact weight. [SBD]  Walker notes that much of our fat free mass introduces signal noise when trying to determine how much weight we're actually losing or gaining. [SBD]  With the help of a graphing tool (Excel is used in the book), he addresses these problems. [SBD]  Factoring in exercise, and through counting calories, one can calculate one's own total energy expenditure (basal metabolic rate, thermic effect of food, and day-to-day exercise) and cut back calorie intake or increase exercise to lose weight.

title: Irish local elections, 2004
paragraph: The 2004 Irish local elections were held in all the counties, cities and towns of Ireland on 11 June 2004, on the same day as the European elections and referendum on the twenty-seventh amendment of the constitution. [SBD]  Polling was delayed until 19 June 2004 in County Roscommon, due to the sudden death of Councillor Gerry Donnelly.

title: Frank Nelson Doubleday
paragraph: Frank Nelson Doubleday (January 8, 1862 – January 30, 1934), known to friends and family as “Effendi”, founded the eponymous Doubleday & McClure Company in 1897, which later operated under other names. [SBD]  Starting work at the age of 14 after his father's business failed, Doubleday began with Charles Scribner's Sons in New York.

title: Eburonian
paragraph: The Eburonian (German: "Eburon" or "Eburonium"), or, much less commonly, the Eburonian Stage, is a glacial complex in the Calabrian stage of the Pleistocene epoch and lies between the Tegelen and the Waalian interglacial. [SBD]  The transition from the Tegelen to the Eburonian started about 1.78 million years ago, lasted 480,000 years (to 1.3 million years ago), its base marking the boundary between the Neogene and Quaternary deposits of the Netherlands.

title: Ramsgate tug
paragraph: The Ramsgate tugs were a series of tugboats used at Ramsgate harbour since the 19th century. [SBD]  The harbour's development coincided with the growing use of the steam tugs that were then being built for the shipping industry.

title: Charles Montagu Doughty
paragraph: Charles Montagu Doughty (19 August 1843 – 20 January 1926) was an English poet, writer, explorer, adventurer and traveller born in Theberton Hall near Saxmundham, Suffolk and educated at private schools in Laleham and Elstree, and at a school for the Royal Navy, Portsmouth. [SBD]  He was a student at King's College London, eventually graduating from Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge in 1864.

title: Aaron Douglas
paragraph: Aaron Douglas (May 26, 1899 – February 3, 1979) was an African-American painter, illustrator and visual arts educator. [SBD]  He was a major figure in the Harlem Renaissance. [SBD]  He developed his art career painting murals and creating illustrations that addressed social issues around race and segregation in the United States by utilizing African-centric imagery. [SBD]  Douglas set the stage for young, African-American artists to enter public arts realm through his involvement with the Harlem Artists Guild. [SBD]  In 1944, he concluded his art career by founding the Art Department at Fisk University in Nashville, Tennessee. [SBD]  He taught visual art classes at Fisk until his retirement in 1966. [SBD]  Douglas is known as a prominent leader in modern African-American art whose work influenced artists for years to come.

title: Donald Wills Douglas Sr.
paragraph: Donald Wills Douglas Sr. (6 April 1892 – 1 February 1981) was an American aircraft industrialist and engineer.

title: Kahramanmaraş Province
paragraph: Kahramanmaraş Province (Turkish: "Kahramanmaraş ili" ) is a province of Turkey. [SBD]  Its provincial capital is the city of Kahramanmaraş, the traffic code is 46.

title: Fernando Belaúnde Terry
paragraph: Fernando Belaúnde Terry (October 7, 1912 – June 4, 2002) served as the 57th and 60th President of Peru (1963–1968 and 1980–1985). [SBD]  Deposed by a military coup in 1968, he was re-elected in 1980 after eleven years of military rule. [SBD]  He was recognized for his personal integrity and his commitment to the democratic process.

title: William Lewis Douglas
paragraph: William Lewis Douglas (August 22, 1845 – September 17, 1924) was a U.S. businessman and politician from Massachusetts. [SBD]  He served as the 42nd Governor of Massachusetts from 1905 until 1906. [SBD]  He also founded and oversaw the growth of the W. L. Douglas Shoe Company, a highly successful Brockton, Massachusetts business that became one of the world's largest shoe manufacturers. [SBD]  He also opened the first nationwide chain of shoe stores devoted to selling the company's products.

title: MARC standards
paragraph: MARC (MAchine-Readable Cataloging) standards are a set of digital formats for the description of items catalogued by libraries, such as books. [SBD]  Working with the Library of Congress, American computer scientist Henriette Avram developed MARC in the 1960s to create records that could be read by computers and shared among libraries. [SBD]  By 1971, MARC formats had become the US national standard for dissemination of bibliographic data. [SBD]  Two years later, they became the international standard.

title: Inner Circle railway line
paragraph: The Inner Circle was a steam era suburban railway line (later electrified) in Melbourne, Australia. [SBD]  It served the inner-northern suburbs of Parkville, Carlton North, Fitzroy North, and Fitzroy. [SBD]  At its closure, it ran from Royal Park station on the Upfield line (Melway map ref: 29 F11) in the west, to a triangular junction with Rushall and Merri stations on today's South Morang line in the east. [SBD]  (Melway map ref: 30 D11) There was also a branch line to Fitzroy that opened at the same time.

title: Conditions races
paragraph: Conditions races are horse races in which the weights carried by the runners are laid down by the conditions attached to the race. [SBD]  Weights are allocated according to the sex of the runners, with female runners carrying less weight than males; the age of the runners, with younger horses receiving weight from older runners to allow for relative maturity, referred to as weight for age; and the quality of the runners, with horses that have won certain values of races giving weight to less successful entrants.

title: Damwâld
paragraph: Damwâld (Dutch: "Damwoude" ) is a village in the Dantumadiel municipality of Friesland, in the Netherlands and has around 5600 citizens (2014). [SBD]  This number of citizens makes Damwâld the largest village in the municipality of Dantumadiel.

title: Brownie points
paragraph: Brownie points in modern usage are a hypothetical social currency, which can be acquired by doing good deeds or earning favor in the eyes of another, often one's superior.

title: Herbert Henry Dow
paragraph: Herbert Henry Dow (February 26, 1866 – October 15, 1930) was an American chemical industrialist, best known as the founder of the American multinational conglomerate Dow Chemical. [SBD]  He was a graduate of Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio. [SBD]  He was a prolific inventor of chemical processes, compounds, and products, and was a successful businessman.

title: Anthony Comstock
paragraph: Anthony Comstock (March 7, 1844 – September 21, 1915) was a United States Postal Inspector and politician dedicated to ideas of Victorian morality. [SBD]  The terms "comstockery" and "Comstockism" were used for his extensive campaign to censor materials he considered indecent and obscene, such as birth control information.

title: Nocturama (album)
paragraph: Nocturama is the twelfth studio album by Nick Cave and the Bad Seeds, released in 2003. [SBD]  It so far has a Metacritic score of 73 out of 100 based on "generally favorable reviews". [SBD]  To date, it is the last Bad Seeds album to feature founding member Blixa Bargeld. [SBD]  This album reunited Nick Cave with Nick Launay, who had produced "Junkyard" by The Birthday Party 21 years earlier. [SBD]  It was recorded in one week during an Australian tour in March 2002.

title: John Alexander Dowie
paragraph: John Alexander Dowie (25 May 1847 – 9 March 1907) was a Scottish evangelist and faith healer who ministered in Australia and the United States. [SBD]  He founded the city of Zion, Illinois, and the Christian Catholic Apostolic Church. [SBD]  He was an eloquent speaker.

title: Olin Downes
paragraph: Edwin Olin Downes, better known as Olin Downes (January 27, 1886 – August 22, 1955), was an American music critic, known as "Sibelius's Apostle" for his championship of the music of Jean Sibelius. [SBD]  As critic of "The New York Times", he exercised considerable influence on musical opinion, although many of his judgments have not stood the test of time.

title: Constantinos Apostolou Doxiadis
paragraph: Constantinos Apostolou Doxiadis (also Konstantinos; Greek: Κωνσταντίνος (Αποστόλου) Δοξιάδης , ] ; often quoted as C. A. Doxiadis) (14 May 1913 – 28 June 1975), was a Greek architect and town planner. [SBD]  He became known as the lead architect of Islamabad, the new capital of Pakistan, and later as the father of Ekistics.

title: Robert Lees
paragraph: Robert Lees (July 10, 1912 – June 13, 2004) was an American television and film screenwriter. [SBD]  Lees was best known for writing comedy, including several Abbott and Costello films.

title: List of monastic houses on the Isle of Man
paragraph: List of monastic houses on the Isle of Man is a catalogue of abbeys, priories, friaries or other monastic house on the Isle of Man.

title: Erik Gustaf Boström
paragraph: Erik Gustaf Bernhard Boström (11 February 1842 – 21 February 1907) was a Swedish landowner and politician who was a member of the Swedish Parliament (1876–1907) and the longest-serving Prime Minister of Sweden of the 19th century. [SBD]  He served twice, first from 1891 to 1900 and then again from 1902 to 1905. [SBD]  He was also known as E.G. Boström or E. Gust. [SBD]  Boström.

title: Manuel Ruiz Zorrilla
paragraph: Manuel Ruiz Zorrilla (22 March 183313 June 1895) was a Spanish politician. [SBD]  He served as the 39th Prime Minister of Spain for a little over ten weeks, in the summer of 1871, and again for eight months, between June 1872 and February 1873.

title: Juan Zorrilla de San Martín
paragraph: Juan Zorrilla de San Martín (December 28, 1855 – November 3, 1931) was a Catholic Uruguayan epic poet – he is referred to as the "National Poet of Uruguay" – and political figure.

title: Hardware register
paragraph: In digital electronics, especially computing, hardware registers are circuits typically composed of flip flops, often with many characteristics similar to memory, such as:

title: Sergei Zubatov
paragraph: Sergei Vasilyevich Zubatov (Russian: Серге́й Васи́льевич Зуба́тов ) (March 2 (O.S.), 1864, Moscow - March 15 (N.S.), 1917, Moscow) was a famous Russian police administrator. [SBD]  Despite rumors, he was never a Colonel (Polkovnik) in the Special Corps of Gendarmes. [SBD]  He was a director of the Moscow security (Okhrana) Bureau between 1896 and 1902 and Director of the Special Section of the Interior Ministry's (MVD's) Department of Police in 1902-1903.

title: David Zucker (filmmaker)
paragraph: David S. Zucker (born October 16, 1947) is an American film director, producer, and screenwriter. [SBD]  Associated mostly with parody comedies, Zucker is recognized as the director and writer of the critically successful 1980 film "Airplane! [SBD] " as well as being the creator of "The Naked Gun" franchise and for directing "Scary Movie 3" and "Scary Movie 4".

title: Riggs Bank
paragraph: Riggs Bank was a Washington, D.C.-based commercial bank with branches located in the surrounding metropolitan area and offices around the world. [SBD]  For most of its history, it was the largest bank in the U.S. capital. [SBD]  Riggs had been controlled by the Allbritton family since the 1980s, but they lost control after corporate scandals and management problems. [SBD]  On May 13, 2005, the bank merged with PNC Financial Services.

title: Jerry Zucker
paragraph: Jerry G. Zucker (born March 11, 1950) is an American film producer, director, and writer known for his role in directing comedy spoof films such as "Airplane! [SBD] " and "Top Secret! [SBD] ", and the Best Picture-nominated supernatural drama film "Ghost".

title: Mortimer Zuckerman
paragraph: Mortimer Benjamin "Mort" Zuckerman (born June 4, 1937) is a Canadian-born American media proprietor, magazine editor, and investor. [SBD]  He is the co-founder, executive chairman and former CEO of Boston Properties, one of the largest real estate investment trusts in the United States. [SBD]  Zuckerman is also the owner and publisher of "U.S. News & World Report", where he serves as editor-in-chief. [SBD]  He formerly owned the "New York Daily News" "The Atlantic" and "Fast Company". [SBD]  On the "Forbes" 2016 list of the world's billionaires, he was ranked No. 688 with a net worth of US$2.5 billion.

title: Weihenstephan
paragraph: Weihenstephan is a part of Freising north of Munich, Germany.

title: Vodka Red Bull
paragraph: Vodka Red Bull is a caffeinated alcoholic beverage consisting of energy drink Red Bull and varying amounts of vodka. [SBD]  It is popular among 25- to 50-year-olds in bars and nightclubs around the world. [SBD]  Red Bull has been used as a general mixer in alcoholic beverages in Europe since the 1980s, though not specifically with vodka. [SBD]  However the drink became especially popular in North America when it began being served at San Francisco's Legendary Butter Bar, which is attributed to being its home in North America, and one of the many places you will still receive RedBull's "Perfect Serve" of 2oz's of Vodka with a full 8.4Oz can of Red Bull.

title: New Roman Times
paragraph: New Roman Times is an album by musical group Camper Van Beethoven, released October 12, 2004 on Pitch-A-Tent Records. [SBD]  It is the band's first studio album of new material since they released "Key Lime Pie" in 1989 before dissolving in 1990.

title: Barbara Whiting Smith
paragraph: Barbara Whiting Smith (May 19, 1931 – June 9, 2004) was an actress in movies and on radio and television, primarily in the 1940s and 1950s. [SBD]  She received a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.

title: Lockinge Stakes
paragraph: The Lockinge Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged four years or older. [SBD]  It is run over a distance of 1 mile at Newbury in May.

title: Alexander Sergeyevich Yakovlev
paragraph: Alexander Sergeyevich Yakovlev (Russian: Алекса́ндр Серге́евич Я́ковлев ; 1 April [O.S. 19 March] 1906 22 August 1989) was a Soviet aeronautical engineer. [SBD]  He designed the Yakovlev military aircraft and founded the Yakovlev Design Bureau. [SBD]  Yakovlev was a member of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union from 1938.

title: Coronation Cup
paragraph: The Coronation Cup is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged four years or older. [SBD]  It is run at Epsom Downs over a distance of 1 mile, 4 furlongs and 6 yards , and it is scheduled to take place each year in June.

title: Chopper (motorcycle)
paragraph: A chopper is a type of custom motorcycle which emerged in California in the late 1950s. [SBD]  The chopper is perhaps the most extreme of all custom styles, often using radically modified steering angles and lengthened forks for a stretched-out appearance. [SBD]  They can be built from an original motorcycle which is modified ("chopped") or built from scratch. [SBD]  Some of the characteristic features of choppers are long front ends with extended forks often coupled with an increased rake angle, hardtail frames (frames without rear suspension), very tall "ape hanger" or very short "drag" handlebars, lengthened or stretched frames, and larger than stock front wheels. [SBD]  The "sissy bar", a set of tubes that connect the rear fender with the frame, and which are often extended several feet high, is a signature feature on many choppers.

title: Johann Anton Güldenstädt
paragraph: Johann Anton Güldenstädt (26 April 1745 in Riga, Latvia – 23 March 1781 in St. Petersburg, Russia) was a Baltic German naturalist and explorer in Russian service.

title: 1000 Guineas Stakes
paragraph: The 1000 Guineas Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to three-year-old fillies. [SBD]  It is run on the Rowley Mile at Newmarket over a distance of 1 mile (1,609 metres), and it is scheduled to take place each year in late April or early May on the Sunday following the 2000 Guineas Stakes.

title: Ivan Yakubovsky
paragraph: Ivan Ignatyevich Yakubovsky (Russian: Ива́н Игна́тьевич Якубо́вский ; 7 January 1912 – 30 November 1976) was a Marshal of the Soviet Union, twice made a Hero of the Soviet Union and serving as commander-in-chief of the Warsaw Pact from 1967 to 1976.

title: Rosalyn Sussman Yalow
paragraph: Rosalyn Sussman Yalow (July 19, 1921 – May 30, 2011) was an American medical physicist, and a co-winner of the 1977 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine (together with Roger Guillemin and Andrew Schally) for development of the radioimmunoassay (RIA) technique. [SBD]  She was the second American woman to be awarded the Nobel Prize Physiology or Medicine after Gerty Cori.

title: Epsom Oaks
paragraph: The Oaks Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to three-year-old fillies. [SBD]  It is run at Epsom Downs over a distance of 1 mile, 4 furlongs and 6 yards , and it is scheduled to take place each year in early June. [SBD]  It is the second-oldest of the five Classic races, after the St Leger. [SBD]  Officially the Investec Oaks, it is also popularly known as simply The Oaks. [SBD]  (Increasingly it is coming to be referred to as the Epsom Oaks in both the UK and overseas countries, although 'Epsom' is not part of the official title of the race.)

title: Otozō Yamada
paragraph: Otozō Yamada (山田 乙三 , Yamada Otozō , 6 November 1881 – 18 July 1965) was a general in the Imperial Japanese Army during World War II.

title: Rose (mathematics)
paragraph: In mathematics, a rose or rhodonea curve is a sinusoid plotted in polar coordinates.

title: Yamamoto Tatsuo (politician)
paragraph: Yamamoto Tatsuo (山本 達雄 , April 7, 1856 – November 2, 1947) was a Japanese politician and Governor of the Bank of Japan from 1898 to 1903. [SBD]  He was also a member of the House of Peers and served as a cabinet minister in the pre-war government of the Empire of Japan.

title: Page replacement algorithm
paragraph: In a computer operating system that uses paging for virtual memory management, page replacement algorithms decide which memory pages to page out, sometimes called swap out, or write to disk, when a page of memory needs to be allocated. [SBD]  Page replacement happens when a requested page is not in memory (page fault) and a free page cannot be used to satisfy the allocation, either because there are none, or because the number of free pages is lower than some threshold.

title: Yamanashi Hanzō
paragraph: Yamanashi Hanzō (山梨 半造 , 6 April 1864 – 2 July 1944) was a general in the Imperial Japanese Army, Minister of War and Governor-General of Korea from 1927 to 1929.

title: Ten Thousand Villages
paragraph: Ten Thousand Villages is a nonprofit fair trade organization that markets handcrafted products made by disadvantaged artisans from more than 120 artisan groups in more than 35 countries.

title: Yang Zhu
paragraph: Yang Zhu (; 440–360 BC), also known as Yang Zi or Yangzi (Master Yang), was a Chinese philosopher during the Warring States period. [SBD]  An early ethical egoist alternative to Mohist and Confucian thought, Yang Zhu's surviving ideas appear primarily in the Chinese texts "Huainanzi", "Lüshi Chunqiu", "Mengzi", and possibly the "Liezi" and "Zhuangzi".

title: Salpa Line
paragraph: The Salpa Line (Finnish: "Salpalinja" , literally "Bolt-line"; Swedish: "Salpalinjen" ), or its official name, Suomen Salpa ("Finland's Bolt"), is a bunker line on the eastern border of Finland. [SBD]  It was built during the Interim Peace between the Winter War and the Continuation War to defend Finland against a possible Soviet invasion. [SBD]  The line is 1,200 km long, stretching from the Gulf of Finland to Petsamo in northern Finland (now Pechenga, Russia). [SBD]  It never saw military action because the Soviet offensive in 1944 was stopped at the VKT-line on the Karelian Isthmus. [SBD]  The fortifications of the Salpa Line were much stronger than those of the Mannerheim Line.

title: St. James's Palace Stakes
paragraph: The St. James's Palace Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to three-year-old colts. [SBD]  It is run at Ascot over a distance of 7 furlongs and 213 yards , and it is scheduled to take place each year in June.

title: Queen Anne Stakes
paragraph: The Queen Anne Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged four years or older. [SBD]  It is run at Ascot over a distance of 1 mile (1,609 metres), and is an annual event scheduled to take place each year in June.

title: Yaqut al-Hamawi
paragraph: Yāqūt ibn-'Abdullah al-Rūmī al-Hamawī (1179–1229) (Arabic: ياقوت الحموي الرومي‎ ‎ ) was an Arab biographer and geographer of Greek origin, renowned for his encyclopedic writings on the Muslim world. [SBD]  The "nisba" "al-Rumi" ("from Rûm") refers to his Greek (Byzantine) descent; "al-Hamawi" is taken after his master's name; and ibn-Abdullah is a reference to his father's name, Abdullah. [SBD]  The word "yāqūt" means "ruby" or "hyacinth".

title: Prince of Wales's Stakes
paragraph: The Prince of Wales's Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged four years or older. [SBD]  It is run at Ascot over a distance of 1 mile 1 furlong and 212 yards , and it is scheduled to take place each year in June.

title: Yaropolk Rostislavich
paragraph: Yaropolk Rostislavich (11XX - 1182?) [SBD]  was a Russian grand prince of Vladimir between 1174 and 1175. [SBD]  He was a nephew of Andrei I Bogolyubsky.

title: Gaius Antonius (brother of Mark Antony)
paragraph: Gaius Antonius (died 42 BC) was the second son of Marcus Antonius Creticus and Julia Antonia, and thus, younger brother of Mark Antony, who was one of the members of the second triumvirate.

title: Neurogastroenterology
paragraph: Neurogastroenterology encompasses the study of the brain, the gut, and their interactions with relevance to the understanding and management of gastrointestinal motility and functional gastrointestinal disorders. [SBD]  Specifically, neurogastroenterology focuses on the functions, malfunctions, and the malformations of the sympathetic, parasympathetic, and enteric divisions of the digestive tract.

title: Mary Ann Yates
paragraph: Mary Ann Yates (1728–1787) was an English tragic actress. [SBD]  The daughter of William Graham, a ship's steward and his wife, Mary, she married Richard Yates (c. 1706-1796), a well-known comedian of the time.

title: Frye Art Museum
paragraph: The Frye Art Museum is an art museum located in the First Hill neighborhood of Seattle, Washington, USA. [SBD]  The museum emphasizes painting and sculpture from the nineteenth century to the present. [SBD]  Its holdings originate in the private collection of Charles (1858–1940) and Emma (d. 1934) Frye. [SBD]  Charles, owner of a local meatpacking plant, set aside money in his will for a museum to house the Fryes' collection of over 230 paintings. [SBD]  The Frye Art Museum opened to the public in 1952, and was Seattle's first free art museum. [SBD]  The museum building was originally designed by Paul Thiry, although it has since been considerably altered.

title: Tigernmas
paragraph: Tigernmas, son of Follach, son of Ethriel, a descendant of Érimón, was, according to medieval Irish legend and historical traditions, an early High King of Ireland. [SBD]  His name means either "Lord of Death" or "Beautiful Lord" in Old Irish.

title: Bounty (chocolate bar)
paragraph: Bounty is a chocolate bar manufactured by Mars, Incorporated and sold internationally. [SBD]  It was introduced in 1951 in the United Kingdom and Canada, initially only with a milk chocolate coating.

title: Nang yai
paragraph: Nang yai (Thai: หนังใหญ่ ) is a form of shadow play found in Thailand. [SBD]  Puppets are made of painted buffalo hide, while the story is narrated by songs, chants and music.

title: Lake View Cemetery (Seattle)
paragraph: Lake View Cemetery is a private cemetery located in Seattle, Washington, in the Capitol Hill neighborhood, just north of Volunteer Park. [SBD]  Known as "Seattle's Pioneer Cemetery," it is run by an independent, non-profit association. [SBD]  It was founded in 1872 as the Seattle Masonic Cemetery and later renamed for its view of Lake Washington to the east.

title: Volunteer Park (Seattle)
paragraph: Volunteer Park is a 48.3 acre park in the Capitol Hill neighborhood of Seattle, Washington, USA.

title: Parathion
paragraph: Parathion, also called parathion-ethyl or diethyl parathion and locally known as "Folidol", is an organophosphate compound possessing a organothiophosphate group. [SBD]  It is a potent insecticide and acaricide. [SBD]  It was originally developed by IG Farben in the 1940s. [SBD]  It is highly toxic to non-target organisms, including humans. [SBD]  Its use is banned or restricted in many countries, and there are proposals to ban it from all use. [SBD]  The basic structure is shared by parathion methyl.

title: List coloring
paragraph: In graph theory, a branch of mathematics, list coloring is a type of graph coloring where each vertex can be restricted to a list of allowed colors. [SBD]  It was first studied in the 1976 Vizing.

title: Yugoslav First League
paragraph: The Yugoslav First League (: "Prva savezna liga u fudbalu", Serbian Cyrillic: Пpвa Лигa; ] , : "Prva savezna liga u nogometu") was the premier football league in the Kingdom of Yugoslavia (1918–1941) and Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (1945–1992).

title: Football Association of Bosnia and Herzegovina
paragraph: The Football Association of Bosnia and Herzegovina (Nogometni/Fudbalski Savez Bosne i Hercegovine (N/FSBiH); Ногометни/Фудбалски Савез Босне и Херцеговине (Н/ФСБиХ), (FSBiH); unified abbreviation N/FSBiH), based in Sarajevo, is the chief officiating body of football in Bosnia and Herzegovina. [SBD]  The Bosnian football association was founded as the Sarajevo football sub-association of former Yugoslavia in 1920. [SBD]  In 1992 the association was re-founded as the football association of Bosnia and Herzegovina.

title: Lee Arenberg
paragraph: Lee Arenberg (born July 18, 1962) is an American actor, best known for his role as Pintel, one of Captain Barbossa's crew, in the "Pirates of the Caribbean" film series. [SBD]  He currently has a recurring role as the dwarf Grumpy in the television series "Once Upon a Time".

title: Asim Ferhatović Hase Stadium
paragraph: Asim Ferhatović Hase Stadium, also known as City Stadium Koševo, Olympic Stadium Koševo and Asim Ferhatović - Hase Bosnian: 'Gradski stadion Koševo" / "Olimpijski stadion Koševo" / "Asim Ferhatović - Hase' ; Градски стадион Кошево / Олимпијски стадион Кошево / Асим Ферхатовић - Хасе) is a multi-purpose stadium located in the Koševo neighborhood of Sarajevo, Bosnia and Herzegovina. [SBD]  Koševo Stadium (Кошево) or Olympic Stadium is owned by the city, and leased on longterm basis by FK Sarajevo. [SBD]  The club proposed the new name for its sporting and football events, in honor to its former footballer and club's legend, Asim Ferhatović - Hase. [SBD]  It hosted the opening ceremony of the 1984 Winter Olympics. [SBD]  Currently, it is home to football club FK Sarajevo and the Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team.

title: Seattle Art Museum
paragraph: The Seattle Art Museum (commonly known as "SAM") is an art museum located in Seattle, Washington, USA. [SBD]  It maintains three major facilities: its main museum in downtown Seattle; the Seattle Asian Art Museum (SAAM) in Volunteer Park on Capitol Hill, and the open Olympic Sculpture Park on the central Seattle waterfront, which opened on January 20, 2007.

title: Mirsad Fazlagić
paragraph: Mirsad Fazlagić (born 4 April 1943 in Čapljina) is a retired Bosnian professional footballer and manager, considered one of the best full-backs of his generation.

title: List edge-coloring
paragraph: In mathematics, list edge-coloring is a type of graph coloring that combines list coloring and edge coloring.

title: Cable & Deadpool
paragraph: Cable & Deadpool was a comic book series published by Marvel Comics beginning in 2004. [SBD]  The title characters, Cable and Deadpool, shared the focus of the book. [SBD]  The series was launched following the cancellation of the characters' previous ongoing solo series. [SBD]  The book's mix of humor, action, and intricate plotting have won it a devoted fanbase. [SBD]  Marvel Comics canceled the series with issue #50 to make way for a new "Deadpool" ongoing series that began on September 10, 2008, and a new Cable ongoing series that was launched in March 2008. [SBD]  Cable & Deadpool were ranked #7 on Marvel.com's list of "The 10 Greatest Buddy Teams" of all time.

title: Seattle Preparatory School
paragraph: Seattle Preparatory School, popularly known as Seattle Prep, is a private, Jesuit high school located on Capitol Hill in Seattle, Washington.

title: Zig-Zag (company)
paragraph: Zig-Zag is a brand of rolling papers that originated in France. [SBD]  It is marketed in the USA by National Tobacco, in Europe by Republic Technologies, and in Japan by Tsuge Pipes. [SBD]  The Zig-Zag brand produces primarily hand-rolled tobacco related products such as cigarette rolling papers, cigarette tubes and rolling accessories.

title: Rose Marie
paragraph: Rose Marie Mazetta (born August 15, 1923), known professionally as Rose Marie, is an American actress. [SBD]  As a child performer she had a successful singing career as Baby Rose Marie. [SBD]  A veteran of vaudeville and one of its last surviving stars, her career includes film, radio, records, theater, night clubs and television. [SBD]  Her most famous role was television comedy writer Sally Rogers on the CBS situation comedy "The Dick Van Dyke Show". [SBD]  She later portrayed Myrna Gibbons on "The Doris Day Show" and was also a frequent panelist on the game show "Hollywood Squares". [SBD]  She was the first major star to be known simply by her first names and is the subject of a documentary film "Wait for Your Laugh" (2017) which features interviews from numerous co-stars, including Carl Reiner, Dick Van Dyke, Peter Marshall and Tim Conway.

title: Pousse-café
paragraph: Pousse-café (French, literally "coffee-pusher") may refer to:

title: Asim Ferhatović
paragraph: Asim "Hase" Ferhatović (] ; 24 January 1933 – 25 January 1987) was a Bosnian footballer. [SBD]  He started his football career in 1948 with FK Sarajevo, for whom he made his first-team debut in 1952. [SBD]  Ferhatović remained with the club until his retirement in 1967, although he represented Fenerbahçe in the 1962–63 season. [SBD]  He won a solitary cap for the Yugoslavia national football team in 1961.

title: Total coloring
paragraph: In graph theory, total coloring is a type of graph coloring on the vertices and edges of a graph.

title: Soldier X
paragraph: Soldier X is a young adult war drama book written by Don Wulffson about a half-German and half-Russian boy named Erik Brandt who joins the Wehrmacht, Hitler's army, during World War II. [SBD]  The book tells about the war from the perspective of Erik Brandt as he leads a life as both a German and a Russian, as well as the ways in which war can affect a person.

title: Comic opera
paragraph: Comic opera denotes a sung dramatic work of a light or comic nature, usually with a happy ending.

title: Safet Sušić
paragraph: Safet Sušić (born 13 April 1955) is a Bosnian football manager and former player. [SBD]  He is currently managing Aytemiz Alanyaspor. [SBD]  Sušić was a gifted midfielder known for his dribbling skills and technical ability, and is strongly reputed to have been one of the finest European players of his generation. [SBD]  Sušić played for Yugoslavia in two FIFA World Cups, 1982 and 1990, and at UEFA Euro 1984. [SBD]  As manager he took the Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team to the 2014 FIFA World Cup.

title: Operation Desert Lion
paragraph: Operation Desert Lion began on 27 March 2003. [SBD]  Soldiers from the U.S. 505th Parachute Infantry Regiment and 82nd Airborne Division launched the operation in the Kohe Safi Mountains and surrounding areas in the Kandahar province of Afghanistan, near Bagram Air Base. [SBD]  Their mission was to hunt for supplies and members of the Taliban and Al-Qaida. [SBD]  The action began with soldiers debouching from Chinook and Black Hawk helicopters. [SBD]  The soldiers found two caches of weapons that included 107mm rockets, mortar rounds, recoilless rocket rounds and cases of machine-gun ammunition just five kilometers from the air base. [SBD]  Disposal experts blew up the caches in place.

title: Zabranjeno Pušenje
paragraph: Zabranjeno Pušenje (Bosnian for "No Smoking") is a Bosnian rock band from Sarajevo.

title: Sergej Barbarez
paragraph: Sergej Barbarez (born 17 September 1971) is a Bosnian former professional footballer who played for several clubs in the German Bundesliga and the Bosnia and Herzegovina national team. [SBD]  He is considered as one of the all-time great players of Hamburger SV where he scored 65 goals in 174 Bundesliga games. [SBD]  Mainly used as a second striker, he has also played as an attacking midfielder or left winger.

title: Harmonious coloring
paragraph: In graph theory, a harmonious coloring is a (proper) vertex coloring in which every pair of colors appears on at most one pair of adjacent vertices. [SBD]  The harmonious chromatic number χ("G") of a graph "G" is the minimum number of colors needed for any harmonious coloring of "G".

title: Gbadolite
paragraph: Gbadolite or Gbado-Lite (pronounced ) is the capital of Nord-Ubangi Province in the Democratic Republic of the Congo. [SBD]  The town is located 12 km south of the Ubangi River at the border to the Central African Republic and 1150 km northeast of the national capital Kinshasa. [SBD]  Gbadolite was the ancestral home and residence of Joseph-Désiré Mobutu, lafter self-styled as Mobutu Sese Seko, the President of Zaire from 1965 to 1997.

title: Amy Acker
paragraph: Amy Louise Acker (born December 5, 1976) is an American actress. [SBD]  She played Winifred Burkle and Illyria on the TV series "Angel" and Kelly Peyton on "Alias". [SBD]  Between 2012 and 2016, she played Root on "Person of Interest", having become a series regular during the third season.

title: Complete coloring
paragraph: In graph theory, complete coloring is the opposite of harmonious coloring in the sense that it is a vertex coloring in which every pair of colors appears on at least one pair of adjacent vertices. [SBD]  Equivalently, a complete coloring is minimal in the sense that it cannot be transformed into a proper coloring with fewer colors by merging pairs of color classes. [SBD]  The achromatic number ψ(G) of a graph G is the maximum number of colors possible in any complete coloring of G.

title: Exact coloring
paragraph: In graph theory, an exact coloring is a (proper) vertex coloring in which every pair of colors appears on exactly one pair of adjacent vertices.

title: Thabana Ntlenyana
paragraph: Thabana Ntlenyana, which literally means "Beautiful little mountain" in Sesotho, is the highest point in Lesotho and the highest mountain in southern Africa. [SBD]  It is situated on the Mohlesi ridge of the Drakensberg/Maloti Mountains, north of Sani Pass. [SBD]  It stands at 3482 m high.

title: Pedro Arias Dávila
paragraph: Pedrarias Dávila (Pedro Arias de Ávila) y Ortiz de Cota (Segovia, Castile, c. 1440 –

title: Differential analyser
paragraph: The differential analyser is a mechanical analogue computer designed to solve differential equations by integration, using wheel-and-disc mechanisms to perform the integration. [SBD]  It was one of the first advanced computing devices to be used operationally.

title: Champagne Castle
paragraph: Champagne Castle is a mountain in the central Drakensberg range, and is the second highest peak in South Africa. [SBD]  It contains a series of subsidiary peaks, amongst them, Cathkin Peak (3149 m), Sterkhorn (previously called Mount Memory), Monk's Cowl and Dragon's Back.

title: Sultanate of Sulu
paragraph: The Sultanate of Sulu (Jawi: کسلطانن سولو دار الإسلام, Malay: "Kesultanan Sulu" , Filipino: "Kasultanan ng Sulu" , Arabic: سلطنة سولك‎ ‎ ) was a Muslim state that ruled the islands in the Sulu Archipelago, parts of Mindanao, certain portions of Palawan and north-eastern Borneo (present-day the certain parts of Sabah and North Kalimantan).

title: Grænalón
paragraph: Grænalón loosely translated as "Green-lagoon" was one of the glacial lakes of the Icelandic glacier Vatnajökull. [SBD]  It was situated in the south of Iceland. [SBD]  Its surface measured 18 km² during the 20th Century.

title: Francisco Oller
paragraph: Francisco Oller (June 17, 1833 – May 17, 1917) was a Puerto Rican visual artist. [SBD]  Oller is the only Latin American painter to have played a role in the development of Impressionism.

title: Acyclic coloring
paragraph: In graph theory, an acyclic coloring is a (proper) vertex coloring in which every 2-chromatic subgraph is acyclic.

title: Giant's Castle
paragraph: Giant's Castle is a mountain peak in the southern African Drakensberg in KwaZulu Natal. [SBD]  Giants Castle offers visitors to the regions hiking opportunities with panoramic views. [SBD]  The Nature Reserve offers secluded accommodation, bushman rock art with easy access for everyone and about the best base to start a Drakensberg hiking experience. [SBD]  The area is one of many of South Africa's adventure areas, and plays host to the Giants Challenge MTB marathon in April each year.

title: Strong coloring
paragraph: In graph theory, a strong coloring, with respect to a partition of the vertices into (disjoint) subsets of equal sizes, is a (proper) vertex coloring in which every color appears exactly once in every partition.

title: Grímsvötn
paragraph: Grímsvötn (] ; "vötn" = "waters", singular: "vatn" ) is a volcano in South-East Iceland. [SBD]  It is in the highlands of Iceland at the northwestern side of the Vatnajökull ice-cap. [SBD]  The caldera is at , at an elevation of 1725 m . [SBD]  Beneath the caldera is the magma chamber of the Grímsvötn volcano.

title: Artocarpus integer
paragraph: Artocarpus integer, commonly known as cempedak (pronounced "chem-pe-dak"), is a species of tree in the family Moraceae, and in the same genus as breadfruit and jackfruit. [SBD]  It is native to southeast Asia, from Indonesia and the Malay Peninsula to the island of New Guinea. [SBD]  Furthermore, the tree has also been introduced to Queensland.

title: Garfield Barwick
paragraph: Sir Garfield Edward John Barwick, {'1': ", '2': ", '3': ", '4': "} (22 June 190313 July 1997) was an Australian lawyer, politician, and judge who was the seventh and longest serving Chief Justice of Australia, in office from 1964 to 1981. [SBD]  He previously served as a minister in the Menzies Government from 1958 to 1964.

title: Ben Macdhui
paragraph: Ben Macdhui (or Ben Macdui) is the name of two mountains:

title: 2C-C
paragraph: 2C-C is a psychedelic drug of the 2C family. [SBD]  It was first synthesized by Alexander Shulgin, sometimes used as an entheogen. [SBD]  In his book "PiHKAL (Phenethylamines i Have Known And Loved)", Shulgin lists the dosage range as 20–40 mg. [SBD]  2C-C is usually taken orally, but may also be insufflated. [SBD]  2C-C is schedule I of section 202(c) of the Controlled Substances Act in the United States, signed into law as of July, 2012 under the Food and Drug Administration Safety and Innovation Act.

title: Hvítavatn
paragraph: Hvítavatn is a small lake in the southern Highlands of Iceland. [SBD]  It is situated between "Sídujökull" and Skeiðarájökull, two of the southern arms of the big glacier Vatnajökull, and lies 15 km to the north of the infamous Skeiðará sander.

title: Terry Funk
paragraph: Terrence Funk (born June 30, 1944) is an American professional wrestler and actor. [SBD]  Funk is known for the longevity of his career – which spanned 50 years and included multiple short-lived retirements – and the influential hardcore wrestling style he pioneered in the latter part of his career.

title: Þingvallavatn
paragraph: Þingvallavatn, anglicised as Thingvallavatn, is a rift valley lake in southwestern Iceland. [SBD]  With a surface of 84 km² it is the largest natural lake in Iceland. [SBD]  Its greatest depth is 114 m. [SBD]  At the northern shore of the lake, at Þingvellir (after which the lake is named), the Alþingi, the national parliament, was founded in the year 930, and held its sessions there until 1799 and still as of today the name Alþingi Íslendinga is carried by the parliament of Iceland.

title: Lincoln Memorial Bridge
paragraph: Lincoln Memorial Bridge is a deck arch bridge carrying U.S. Route 50 Business over the Wabash River between Vincennes, Indiana and Lawrence County, Illinois. [SBD]  It is said to mark the point where Abraham Lincoln crossed the Wabash River on his way to Illinois in 1830, and a sculptural installation, the Lincoln Trail State Memorial, marks the western end of the bridge.

title: Winifred Burkle
paragraph: Winifred "Fred" Burkle is a fictional character created by Joss Whedon and introduced by Shawn Ryan and Mere Smith on the television series "Angel". [SBD]  The character is portrayed by Amy Acker.

title: Þórisvatn
paragraph: Þórisvatn, is the largest lake of Iceland, situated at the south end of Sprengisandur highland road within the highlands of Iceland.

title: Bat (disambiguation)
paragraph: A bat is a flying mammal of the order Chiroptera.

title: Arlington Memorial Bridge
paragraph: The Arlington Memorial Bridge is a Neoclassical masonry, steel, and stone arch bridge with a central bascule (or drawbridge) that crosses the Potomac River at Washington, D.C., the capital of the United States. [SBD]  First proposed in 1886, the bridge went unbuilt for decades thanks to political quarrels over whether the bridge should be a memorial, and to whom or what. [SBD]  Traffic problems associated with the dedication of the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier in November 1921 and the desire to build a bridge in time for the bicentennial of the birth of George Washington led to its construction in 1932.

title: Parliament railway station
paragraph: Parliament railway station is an underground station on the metro network in Melbourne, Australia. [SBD]  It is one of five stations (and one of three underground) on the City Loop, which encircles the Melbourne CBD. [SBD]  In 2011/12 it was the 4th busiest station on Melbourne's metropolitan network, with 10.7 million passenger movements.

title: 2C-D
paragraph: 2C-D (2,5-dimethoxy-4-methylphenethylamine, also known as 2C-M) is a psychedelic drug of the 2C family that is sometimes used as an entheogen. [SBD]  It was first synthesized in 1970 by a team from the Texas Research Institute of Mental Sciences, and its activity was subsequently investigated in humans by Alexander Shulgin. [SBD]  The full name of the chemical is 2,5-dimethoxy-4-methylphenethylamine. [SBD]  In his book "PiHKAL (Phenethylamines i Have Known And Loved)", Shulgin lists the dosage range as being from 20 to 60 mg and many people recommend higher doses. [SBD]  Lower doses (generally 10 mg or less) of 2C-D have been explored as a potential nootropic, albeit with mixed results. [SBD]  2C-D is generally taken orally, though may be insufflated (i.e. taken nasally). [SBD]  Insufflating tends to cause intense pain, however, and the dosage level is usually much lower, typically in the region of 1 to 15 mg.

title: Seward Park (Seattle)
paragraph: Seward Park is a municipal park which covers 300 acre . [SBD]  It is located in southeast Seattle, Washington, U.S.A in the neighborhood of the same name. [SBD]  The park occupies all of Bailey Peninsula, a forested peninsula that juts into Lake Washington. [SBD]  It contains one of the last surviving tracts of old-growth forest within the city of Seattle. [SBD]  The park is named for U.S. Secretary of State William Seward.

title: Ryan Atwood
paragraph: Ryan Francis Atwood is a fictional character on the FOX television series "The O.C.", portrayed by Benjamin McKenzie. [SBD]  A troubled teenager from Chino, California, he is the main protagonist of the show, an outcast who is given a second chance when the wealthy Cohen family takes him in.

title: 2C-T-21
paragraph: 2C-T-21 is a psychedelic phenethylamine of the 2C family. [SBD]  It was first synthesized by Alexander Shulgin, sometimes used as an entheogen. [SBD]  It was the first psychedelic drug known to contain six different chemical elements in the structure.

title: Marissa Cooper
paragraph: Marissa Cooper is a fictional character on the FOX television series "The O.C.", portrayed by Mischa Barton. [SBD]  Marissa was among the original "core four" characters on "The O.C." She is a privileged California native born into a wealthy family, residing next to the Cohen family's house. [SBD]  Throughout The O.C.'s storyline, Marissa is introduced to new characters who influence her perspective on life and her personality.

title: Rappahannock River
paragraph: The Rappahannock River is a river in eastern Virginia, in the United States, approximately 195 mi in length. [SBD]  It traverses the entire northern part of the state, from the Blue Ridge Mountains in the west, across the Piedmont, to the Chesapeake Bay, south of the Potomac River.

title: Age of Discovery
paragraph: The Age of Discovery or the Age of Exploration from the end of the 15th century to the 18th century, was an informal and loosely defined European historical period marking the time period in which extensive overseas exploration emerged as a powerful factor in European culture and the beginning of globalization. [SBD]  It also marks the rise of the period of widespread adoption in Europe of colonialism and mercantilism. [SBD]  Many lands previously unknown to Europeans were discovered during this period, though most were already inhabited. [SBD]  From the perspective of many non-Europeans, the Age of Discovery marked the arrival of invaders from previously unknown continents.

title: Suling
paragraph: A suling or Seruling is a Southeast Asian bamboo ring flute especially in Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines and Singapore. [SBD]  It is used in gamelan ensembles.

title: John Hopps
paragraph: John H. Hopps (1939 – May 14, 2004) was an African-American physicist and politician. [SBD]  A native of Dallas, Texas, Hopps was a Ford Scholar to Morehouse College, also receiving degrees from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (where he was a member of Omega Psi Phi fraternity) and Brandeis University. [SBD]  After his graduation in 1971, Hopps joined the faculty at Ohio State University, and later accepted a research position in nuclear engineering at MIT, and was a member of leadership at the Charles Stark Draper Laboratory.

title: Cunning folk in Britain
paragraph: The cunning folk in Britain were professional or semi-professional practitioners of magic in Britain, active from the Medieval period through to the early twentieth century. [SBD]  As cunning folk, they practised folk magic – also known as "low magic" – although often combined with elements of "high" or ceremonial magic, which they learned through the study of grimoires. Primarily using spells and charms as a part of their profession, they were most commonly employed to use their magic in order to combat malevolent witchcraft, to locate criminals, missing persons or stolen property, for fortune telling, for healing, for treasure hunting and to influence people to fall in love. [SBD]  Belonging "to the world of popular belief and custom", the cunning folk's magic has been defined as being "concerned not with the mysteries of the universe and the empowerment of the magus [as ceremonial magic usually is], so much as with practical remedies for specific problems." [SBD]  However, other historians have noted that in some cases, there was apparently an "experimental or 'spiritual' dimension" to their magical practices, something which was possibly shamanic in nature.

title: Skjálfandafljót
paragraph: The Skjálfandafljót River is situated in the north of Iceland. [SBD]  Skjálfandafljót is 178 km long, and is the fourth longest river of Iceland.

title: Kamala Markandaya
paragraph: Kamala Markandaya (1924 – 16 May 2004) was a pseudonym used by Kamala Purnaiya Taylor, an Indian novelist and journalist.

title: Flash freezing
paragraph: In physics and chemistry, flash freezing is a naturally occurring phenomenon, but also used by people in everyday life in the food industry and forecasting in the field of meteorology.

title: Billy Graham
paragraph: William Franklin "Billy" Graham Jr. [SBD]  KBE (born November 7, 1918) is an American evangelical Christian evangelist, ordained as a Southern Baptist minister, who rose to celebrity status in 1949 reaching a core constituency of middle-class, moderately conservative Protestants. [SBD]  He is widely regarded as the most influential preacher of the 20th century. [SBD]  He held large indoor and outdoor rallies; sermons were broadcast on radio and television, some still being re-broadcast into the 21st century. [SBD]  In his six decades of television, Graham is principally known for hosting the annual "Billy Graham Crusades", which he began in 1947, until he concluded in 2005, at the time of his retirement. [SBD]  He also hosted the popular radio show "Hour of Decision" from 1950 to 1954. [SBD]  He repudiated segregation and, in addition to his religious aims, helped shape the worldview of fundamentalists and evangelicals, leading them to appreciate the relationship between the Bible and contemporary secular viewpoints. [SBD]  Graham has preached to live audiences of nearly 215 million people in more than 185 countries and territories through various meetings, including BMS World Mission and Global Mission. [SBD]  He has also reached hundreds of millions more through television, video, film, and webcasts.

title: Rio Grande (film)
paragraph: Rio Grande is a 1950 Western film directed by John Ford and starring John Wayne and Maureen O'Hara. [SBD]  The picture is the third installment of Ford's "cavalry trilogy," following two RKO Pictures releases: "Fort Apache" (1948) and "She Wore a Yellow Ribbon" (1949).

title: Progressive Federal Party
paragraph: The Progressive Federal Party (PFP) (Afrikaans: "Progressiewe Federale Party" ) was a South African political party formed in 1977. [SBD]  It advocated power-sharing in South Africa through a federal constitution, in place of apartheid.

title: List of ancient Egyptians
paragraph: This is a list of ancient Egyptian people who have articles on Wikipedia. [SBD]  The list covers key ancient Egyptian individuals from the start of the first dynasty until the end of the ancient Egyptian nation when the Ptolemaic Dynasty ended and Egypt became a province of Rome in 30 BC.

title: Matrix decoder
paragraph: Matrix decoding is an audio technology where a finite number of discrete audio channels (e.g., 2) are decoded into a larger number of channels on play back (e.g., 5). [SBD]  The channels are generally, but not always, arranged for transmission or recording by an encoder, and decoded for playback by a decoder.

title: Avant-garde metal
paragraph: Avant-garde metal, also known as avant-metal or experimental metal, is a subgenre of heavy metal music loosely defined by use of experimentation and innovative, avant-garde elements, including non-standard and unconventional sounds, instruments, song structures, playing styles, and vocal techniques. [SBD]  Avant-garde metal is influenced by progressive rock and extreme metal, particularly death metal, and is closely related to progressive metal. [SBD]  Some local scenes include Los Angeles, the San Francisco Bay Area, Boston, and Seattle in the United States, Oslo in Norway, and Tokyo in Japan.

title: 2,5-Dimethoxy-4-methylamphetamine
paragraph: 2,5-Dimethoxy-4-methylamphetamine (DOM; known on the street as STP, standing for "Serenity, Tranquility and Peace") is a psychedelic and a substituted amphetamine. [SBD]  It was first synthesized by Alexander Shulgin, and later reported in his book "PiHKAL: A Chemical Love Story". [SBD]  DOM is classified as a Schedule I substance in the United States, and is similarly controlled in other parts of the world. [SBD]  Internationally, it is a Schedule I drug under the Convention on Psychotropic Substances. [SBD]  It is generally taken orally.

title: Precedence effect
paragraph: The precedence effect or law of the first wavefront is a binaural psychoacoustic effect. [SBD]  When a sound is followed by another sound separated by a sufficiently short time delay (below the listener's echo threshold), listeners perceive a single fused auditory image; its perceived spatial location is dominated by the location of the first-arriving sound (the first wave front). [SBD]  The lagging sound also affects the perceived location. [SBD]  However, its effect is suppressed by the first-arriving sound.

title: County of Hainaut
paragraph: The County of Hainaut (French: "Comté de Hainaut" , Dutch: "Graafschap Henegouwen" ; German: "Grafschaft Hennegau" ), sometimes given the archaic spellings Hainault and Heynowes, was a historical lordship within the medieval Holy Roman Empire, with its capital at Mons (Dutch: "Bergen" ). [SBD]  The name comes from the river Haine (Dutch: "Hene", German: "Henne"). [SBD]  Besides Mons, it included the cities of Cambrai ("Kamerijk") and Charleroi. [SBD]  It consisted of what is now the Belgian province of Hainaut and the southern part of the French "département" of Nord.

title: Richard Diebenkorn
paragraph: Richard Diebenkorn (April 22, 1922 – March 30, 1993) was an American painter. [SBD]  His early work is associated with abstract expressionism and the Bay Area Figurative Movement of the 1950s and 1960s. [SBD]  His later work (best known as the "Ocean Park" paintings) were instrumental to his achievement of worldwide acclaim.

title: Pilgrim's Pride
paragraph: Pilgrim's Pride Corporation, also known as Pilgrim's, is a Brazilian-owned, American food company, currently the largest chicken producer in the United States and Puerto Rico and the second-largest chicken producer in Mexico. [SBD]  It exited bankruptcy in December 2009 and relocated its U.S. headquarters to Greeley, Colorado, in 2011. [SBD]  It is majority-owned by JBS S.A.. [SBD]  Pilgrim Pride purchased Gold N'Plump for $350 million in late November 2016.

title: Minnie Pearl
paragraph: Sarah Ophelia Colley Cannon (October 25, 1912 – March 4, 1996), known professionally as Minnie Pearl, was an American country comedian who appeared at the Grand Ole Opry for more than 50 years (from 1940 to 1991) and on the television show "Hee Haw" from 1969 to 1991.

title: Joel Stransky
paragraph: Joel Theodore Stransky (born 16 July 1967) is a former South African rugby union rugby player, most notable for scoring all of South Africa's points, including the famous dramatic winning drop goal, against New Zealand in the 1995 Rugby World Cup final. [SBD]  He played as a fly-half.

title: Arnulf III, Count of Flanders
paragraph: Arnulf III (died 22 February 1071) was Count of Flanders from 1070 until his death at the Battle of Cassel in 1071.

title: Virtual airline (hobby)
paragraph: A virtual airline (VA) is a dedicated hobby organization that uses flight simulation to model the operations of an airline. [SBD]  Virtual airlines generally have a presence on the Internet, similar to a real airline. [SBD]  Many hundreds of virtual airlines of significance are currently active, with tens of thousands of participants involved at any one time.

title: Roquepertuse
paragraph: Acropolis Roquepertuse is a historical religious center for the Celts. [SBD]  It is located near the city of Velaux, north of Marseille and west of Aix-en-Provence, in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur région of southern France. [SBD]  Roquepertuse had no domiciles available for worshippers and has been used as a sanctuary where only priests may have lived permanently. [SBD]  It was destroyed by the Romans in 124 BC and was discovered in 1860. [SBD]  Most of the excavations were done in 1923 by Henri de Gérin-Ricard.

title: World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)
paragraph: The World Heavyweight Championship was a professional wrestling world heavyweight championship owned by WWE. [SBD]  It was one of two top championships in WWE from 2002 to 2006 and from 2010 to 2013, complementing the WWE Championship, and one of three top championships from 2006 to 2010 with the addition of the ECW World Heavyweight Championship.

title: The Entity
paragraph: The Entity is a 1982 American horror film directed by Sidney J. Furie and written by Frank De Felitta, who adapted his 1978 novel of the same name. [SBD]  It stars Barbara Hershey as a woman who is raped and tormented by an invisible assailant. [SBD]  Despite being filmed and planned for a release in 1981, the movie was not released in worldwide theaters until September 1982 and February 1983 in the United States. [SBD]  Like the novel, the film is based on the 1974 Doris Bither case.

title: Baldwin II, Count of Hainaut
paragraph: Baldwin II of Mons (1056–1098?) [SBD]  was count of Hainaut from 1071 to his death. [SBD]  He was the younger son of Baldwin VI, Count of Flanders and Richilde, Countess of Mons and Hainaut.

title: Baldwin III, Count of Hainaut
paragraph: Baldwin III (1088–1120) was count of Hainaut from 1098 to his death. [SBD]  He was son of Baldwin II, Count of Hainaut and Ida of Louvain.

title: Baldwin IV, Count of Hainaut
paragraph: Baldwin IV (1108 – 8 November 1171) was count of Hainaut from 1120 to his death. [SBD]  He was the son of Baldwin III, Count of Hainaut, and Yolande de Wassenberg.

title: Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut
paragraph: Baldwin V of Hainaut (1150 – 17 December 1195) was count of Hainaut (1171–1195), margrave of Namur as Baldwin I (1189–1195) and count of Flanders as Baldwin VIII (1191–1195).

title: Isabella of Hainault
paragraph: Isabella of Hainaut (5 April 1170 in Valenciennes – 15 March 1190 in Paris) was Queen of France as the first spouse of King Philip II.

title: Marcus Rose
paragraph: Marcus Rose (born 12 January 1957) is a former England rugby union international full back who gained ten caps between 1981 and 1987.

title: 2,5-Dimethoxy-4-bromoamphetamine
paragraph: Dimethoxybromoamphetamine (DOB), also known as brolamfetamine (INN) and bromo-DMA, is a psychedelic drug and substituted amphetamine of the phenethylamine class of compounds. [SBD]  DOB was first synthesized by Alexander Shulgin in 1967. [SBD]  Its synthesis and effects are documented in Shulgin's book "PiHKAL: A Chemical Love Story".

title: District of Alyn and Deeside
paragraph: Alyn and Deeside (Welsh: "Alun a Glannau Dyfrdwy" ) was one of six districts of the county of Clwyd, north-east Wales from 1974 to 1996. [SBD]  There is still a parliamentary constituency of the same name.

title: John I, Count of Hainaut
paragraph: John of Avesnes (1 May 1218 – 24 December 1257) was the count of Hainaut from 1246 to his death.

title: Adelaide of Holland
paragraph: Adelaide of Holland, Countess of Hainaut (Dutch: "Aleide (Aleidis) van Holland" ;  1230 – buried 9 April 1284) was a Dutch regent. [SBD]  She was a daughter of Floris IV, Count of Holland and Matilda of Brabant. [SBD]  She was also a sister of William II, Count of Holland and King of Germany. [SBD]  She acted as regent for her nephew Count Floris V during his minority.

title: John I, Count of Holland
paragraph: John I (1284 – 10 November 1299) was Count of Holland and son of Count Floris V. [SBD]  John inherited the county in 1296 after the murder of his father.

title: Battle of the Ebro
paragraph: The Battle of the Ebro (Spanish: "Batalla del Ebro" , Catalan: "Batalla de l'Ebre" ) was the longest and largest battle of the Spanish Civil War. [SBD]  It took place between July and November 1938, with fighting mainly concentrated in two areas on the lower course of the Ebro River, the Terra Alta comarca of Catalonia, and the Auts area close to Fayón "(Faió)" in the lower Matarranya, Eastern Lower Aragon. [SBD]  These sparsely populated areas saw the largest array of armies in the war. [SBD]  The results of the battle were disastrous for the Second Spanish Republic, with tens of thousands of dead and wounded and little effect on the advance of the Nationalists.

title: John II, Count of Holland
paragraph: John II of Avesnes (1247 – 22 August 1304) was Count of Hainaut, Holland, and Zeeland.

title: J. P. Donleavy
paragraph: James Patrick Donleavy (23 April 1926 – 11 September 2017) was an Irish-American novelist and playwright. [SBD]  His best-known work is the novel "The Ginger Man", which was initially banned for obscenity.

title: William I, Count of Hainaut
paragraph: William I, Count of Hainaut (  1286 – 7 June 1337), was Count William III of Avesnes, Count William III of Holland and Count William II of Zeeland from 1304 to his death.

title: Tatar alphabet
paragraph: Three scripts are currently used for the Tatar language: Arabic (in China), Cyrillic (in Tatarstan and Kazakhstan) and Latin (unofficially).

title: William II, Count of Hainaut
paragraph: William II, Count of Hainaut (1307 – 26 September 1345) was William IV of Avesnes, William IV of Holland and William III of Zeeland from 1337 to his death, succeeding his father, William I. [SBD]  He married Joanna, Duchess of Brabant and Limburg in 1334, but had no issue.

title: Shortcake
paragraph: Shortcake is a sweet cake or biscuit (in the American sense: that is, a crumbly bread that has been leavened with baking powder or baking soda).

title: Wrexham Maelor
paragraph: Wrexham Maelor (Welsh: "Wrecsam Maelor" ) was one of six local government districts of the county of Clwyd, north-east Wales, from 1974 to 1996.

title: Alone in the Dark (2005 film)
paragraph: Alone in the Dark is a 2005 Canadian-German-American action horror film loosely based on the of Infogrames' video game series of the same name. [SBD]  Directed by Uwe Boll, the film stars Christian Slater as supernatural detective Edward Carnby (the main character in the games), and also features a cast of Tara Reid, Stephen Dorff, Frank C. Turner, Matthew Walker, Will Sanderson, Mike Dopud, Mark Acheson, Darren Shahlavi, Karin Konoval and Ed Anders.

title: Jacqueline, Countess of Hainaut
paragraph: Jacqueline (Dutch: "Jacoba van Beieren" ; French: "Jacqueline de Bavière" ; 15 July 1401 – 8 October 1436), was a Duchess of Bavaria-Straubing, Countess of Holland and Zeeland and Countess of Hainaut from 1417 to 1433. [SBD]  She was also Dauphine of France for a short time between 1415 and 1417 and Duchess of Gloucester in the 1420s, if her marriage to Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester, is accepted as valid.

title: Jerry Bock
paragraph: Jerrold Lewis "Jerry" Bock (November 23, 1928November 3, 2010) was an American musical theater composer. [SBD]  He received the Tony Award for Best Musical and the Pulitzer Prize for Drama with Sheldon Harnick for their 1959 musical "Fiorello! [SBD] " and the Tony Award for Best Composer and Lyricist for the 1964 musical "Fiddler on the Roof" with Sheldon Harnick.

title: Cáceres, Mato Grosso
paragraph: Cáceres is a municipality in the Brazilian state of Mato Grosso. [SBD]  It covers an area of 24,000km2 and as of 2014 had an estimated population of 90,000.

title: Aldtsjerk
