paragraph: Aldtsjerk (Dutch: "Oudkerk" ) is a small village on the highway from Leeuwarden to Dokkum. [SBD]  It is part of Tytsjerksteradiel, Friesland, the Netherlands and had 693 inhabitants as of 2008.

title: Shuangyashan
paragraph: Shuangyashan () is a coal mining prefecture-level city located in the eastern part Heilongjiang province, People's Republic of China, bordering Russia's Khabarovsk and Primorsky krais to the east. [SBD]  The city's name means a pair-of-ducks mountains and refers to two peaks northeast of the city. [SBD]  In 2007 it had a GDP of RMB 20.6 billion with a 14.2% growth rate.

title: England national rugby union team
paragraph: The England national rugby union team competes in the annual Six Nations Championship with France, Ireland, Scotland, Italy, and Wales. [SBD]  They have won this championship outright on a total of 28 occasions (with the addition of 10 shared victories), 13 times winning the Grand Slam and 25 times winning the Triple Crown, making them the most successful team in the tournament's history. [SBD]  They are ranked second in the world by the International Rugby Board as of 26 June 2017. [SBD]  England are to date the only team from the northern hemisphere to win the Rugby World Cup, when they won the tournament back in 2003. [SBD]  They were also runners-up in 1991 and 2007.

title: Stephen Dorff
paragraph: Stephen Dorff Jr. (born July 29, 1973) is an American actor, known for portraying PK in "The Power of One", Stuart Sutcliffe in "Backbeat", Johnny Marco in Sofia Coppola's "Somewhere", and for his roles in "Blade" (as self-styled vampire-overlord Deacon Frost), "Cecil B. DeMented", "The Motel Life", "S.F.W." and "Space Truckers".

title: International School of Geneva
paragraph: The International School of Geneva (in French: "Ecole Internationale de Genève"), also known as "Ecolint", is a private international school based in Geneva, Switzerland. [SBD]  It is the oldest and largest operating international school in the world. [SBD]  In the mid-1960s, a group of teachers from the International School of Geneva, La Grande Boissière campus created the International Schools Examinations Syndicate (ISES), which would later become the International Baccalaureate Organization (IBO) and then the International Baccalaureate (IB).

title: Landon Curt Noll
paragraph: Landon Curt Noll (born October 28, 1960) is an American computer scientist, co-discoverer of the 25th Mersenne prime and discoverer of the 26th, which he found while still enrolled at Hayward High School and concurrently at California State University, Hayward.

title: Charles Anderson (governor)
paragraph: Charles Anderson (June 1, 1814 – September 2, 1895) was first a Whig and later a Republican politician from Ohio. [SBD]  He served briefly as the 27th Governor of Ohio.

title: Briquette
paragraph: A briquette (or briquet) is a compressed block of coal dust or other combustible biomass material such as charcoal, sawdust, wood chips, peat, or paper used for fuel and kindling to start a fire. [SBD]  The term comes from the French language and is related to "brick".

title: The Women's College, University of Sydney
paragraph: The Women's College is a residential college within the University of Sydney, in the suburb of Camperdown, New South Wales. [SBD]  It was opened in 1892.

title: John Brough
paragraph: John Brough (rhymes with "huff") (September 17, 1811 – August 29, 1865) was a War Democrat politician from Ohio. [SBD]  He served as the 26th Governor of Ohio during the final years of the American Civil War, dying in office of gangrene shortly after the war concluded.

title: Mario Silva (politician)
paragraph: Mário Silva (born June 11, 1966) is a Canadian legal scholar and former politician. [SBD]  Silva served as a Canadian Member of Parliament from 2004 to 2011. [SBD]  He began his political career as a Toronto City Councillor from 1994–2003. [SBD]  He then moved to federal politics, being elected for the Liberal Party of Canada in the 2004 election in the Toronto riding of Davenport. [SBD]  He served as the Official Opposition Critic for Foreign Affairs (Americas) after having served as Critic for the Treasury Board and Labour. [SBD]  In 2007, the President of the French Republic bestowed him the title of Knight of the Order of the Legion of Honour (Ordre national de la Légion d'honneur). [SBD]  He has also been awarded the Order of Merit of Portugal. [SBD]  and the Order of Rio Branco from Brazil.

title: Annie Montague Alexander
paragraph: Annie Montague Alexander (1867–1950) was an American philanthropist and paleontological collector. [SBD]  She established the University of California Museum of Paleontology (UCMP), Museum of Vertebrate Zoology (MVZ), and financed their collections as well as a series of paleontological expeditions to the western United States at the turn of the 20th century. [SBD]  She took part in many of these expeditions, gathering a significant collection of fossils and exotic game animals in her own right.

title: DirectInput
paragraph: In computing, DirectInput is a legacy Microsoft API for collecting input from a computer user, via input devices such as the mouse, keyboard, joystick or other game controllers. [SBD]  It also provides a system for "action mapping," which allows the user to assign specific actions within a game to the buttons and axes of the input devices. [SBD]  Additionally it handles "haptic feedback" (input/output) devices. [SBD]  Microsoft introduced a new input library called XInput specifically for the Xbox 360 controller.

title: DirectSound
paragraph: DirectSound is a deprecated software component of the Microsoft DirectX library for the Windows operating system. [SBD]  DirectSound provides a low-latency interface to sound card drivers written for Windows 95 through Windows XP and can handle the mixing and recording of multiple audio streams.

title: DirectMusic
paragraph: DirectMusic is a deprecated component of the Microsoft DirectX API that allows music and sound effects to be composed and played and provides flexible interactive control over the way they are played. [SBD]  Architecturally, DirectMusic is a high-level set of objects, built on top of DirectSound, that allow the programmer to play sound and music without needing to get quite as low-level as DirectSound. [SBD]  DirectSound allows for the capture and playback of digital sound samples, whereas DirectMusic works with message-based musical data. [SBD]  Music can be synthesized either in hardware, in the Microsoft GS Wavetable SW Synth, or in a custom synthesizer.

title: DirectShow
paragraph: DirectShow (sometimes abbreviated as DS or DShow), codename Quartz, is a multimedia framework and API produced by Microsoft for software developers to perform various operations with media files or streams. [SBD]  It is the replacement for Microsoft's earlier Video for Windows technology. [SBD]  Based on the Microsoft Windows Component Object Model (COM) framework, DirectShow provides a common interface for media across various programming languages, and is an extensible, filter-based framework that can render or record media files on demand at the request of the user or developer. [SBD]  The DirectShow development tools and documentation were originally distributed as part of the DirectX SDK. [SBD]  Currently, they are distributed as part of the Windows SDK (formerly known as the Platform SDK).

title: DirectSetup
paragraph: DirectSetup is an extremely simple library of functions for installing DirectX on a machine. [SBD]  It also provides a way to check the version of DirectX that is present.

title: David Tod
paragraph: David Tod (February 21, 1805 – November 13, 1868) was a politician and industrialist from the U.S. state of Ohio. [SBD]  As the 25th Governor of Ohio, Tod gained recognition for his forceful and energetic leadership during the American Civil War.

title: Saurian Expedition of 1905
paragraph: The Saurian Expedition of 1905 was a noted paleontological research mission in northern Nevada in the United States. [SBD]  The expedition recovered many of the finest specimens of ichthyosaur ever found.

title: Joseph Weber Award for Astronomical Instrumentation
paragraph: Joseph Weber Award for Astronomical Instrumentation

title: Acura CL
paragraph: The Acura CL is a midsize coupé manufactured by Honda's Acura brand from February 19, 1996 to 1999, and from 2000 to 2003. [SBD]  The CL is often thought to have been a replacement for the Acura Legend coupé, but with the advent of the TL in 1996, which directly replaced the Vigor, the CL is more precisely a TL coupé. [SBD]  All Acura CLs were built at Honda's plant in Marysville, Ohio, alongside the TL and the Honda Accord upon which the Acura CLs were based. [SBD]  The CL was the first Acura to be built in the United States.

title: National Statuary Hall Collection
paragraph: The National Statuary Hall Collection in the United States Capitol is composed of statues donated by individual states to honor persons notable in their history. [SBD]  Limited to two statues per-state, the collection was originally set up in the old Hall of the House of Representatives, which was then renamed National Statuary Hall. [SBD]  The expanding collection has since been spread throughout the Capitol.

title: Safe Havens
paragraph: Safe Havens is a comic strip drawn by cartoonist Bill Holbrook. [SBD]  It was originally syndicated by Washington Post Writers Group before switching to King Features Syndicate in 1993. [SBD]  Started in 1988, the strip is currently published in more than 50 newspapers. [SBD]  The strip originally concerned the group of pre-schoolers at Safe Havens Day Care, but has focused on Samantha and followed her as she has grown up (approximately in real-time) and gone through elementary school, high school, college, and (currently) marriage. [SBD]  The comic then went online in 2010.

title: William Dennison Jr.
paragraph: William Dennison Jr. (November 23, 1815 – June 15, 1882) was a Whig and Republican politician from Ohio. [SBD]  He served as the 24th Governor of Ohio and as U.S. Postmaster General in the Cabinet of President Abraham Lincoln during the American Civil War.

title: Barret Oliver
paragraph: Barret Spencer Oliver (born August 24, 1973) is an American photographer and former child actor. [SBD]  He is known for his role as Bastian Balthazar Bux in the film adaptation of Michael Ende's novel "The NeverEnding Story", followed by roles in "D.A.R.Y.L.", "Cocoon" and "".

title: Video game development
paragraph: Video game development is the process of creating a video game. [SBD]  The effort is undertaken by a game developer, which may range from a single person to an international team strewn across the globe. [SBD]  Traditional commercial PC and console games are normally funded by a publisher, and can take several years to reach completion. [SBD]  Indie games can take less time and can be produced at a lower cost by individuals and smaller developers. [SBD]  The independent game industry has seen a substantial rise in recent years with the growth of new online distribution systems, such as Steam and Uplay, as well as the mobile game market, such as for Android and iOS devices.

title: Steve Dallas
paragraph: Steve Dallas is a fictional character in the American comic strips of Berke Breathed, most famously "Bloom County" in the 1980s.

title: Pro Cricket
paragraph: Pro Cricket was a professional cricket league in the United States. [SBD]  It was operated by American Pro Cricket LLC (APC), a private company independent of the ICC and the USACA.

title: Luca Cordero di Montezemolo
paragraph: Luca Cordero di Montezemolo (] ; born 31 August 1947) is an Italian businessman, former Chairman of Ferrari, and formerly Chairman of Fiat S.p.A. and President of Confindustria and FIEG. [SBD]  He comes from an aristocratic family from the region of Piedmont in Italy. [SBD]  He graduated with a degree in law from La Sapienza University in 1971. [SBD]  Afterward, he studied for a masters degree in international commercial law at Columbia University. [SBD]  He is one of the founders and former president of NTV, an Italian company which is Europe's first private open access operator of 300 km/h (186 mph) high-speed trains.

title: Jeremiah P. Ostriker
paragraph: Jeremiah Paul "Jerry" Ostriker (born April 13, 1937) is an astrophysicist and a professor of astronomy at Columbia University and is the Charles A. Young Professor "Emeritus" at Princeton where he also continues as a Senior Research Scholar. [SBD]  Ostriker has also served as a University administrator as Provost of Princeton University.

title: Nationale Handelsbank
paragraph: The Nationale Handelsbank was a Dutch bank that was established to financing trade between the Netherlands and the Dutch East Indies. [SBD]  After operating independently for nearly a hundred years, the parts in Indonesia, were nationalized by the Indonesian government and the remainder was acquired by the "Rotterdamsche Bank" in 1960 and would be absorbed into AMRO Bank.

title: Weehawken Cove
paragraph: Weehawken Cove is a cove on the west bank of the Hudson River between the New Jersey municipalities of Hoboken to the south and Weehawken to the north. [SBD]  At the perimeter of the cove are completed sections the Hudson River Waterfront Walkway, offering views of Manhattan and the Palisades. [SBD]  The name Weehawken comes from the Lenape, and can translate as ""at the end of"", either the Hudson Palisades or the stream which flowed from them into the cove, later the site of the nearby Lincoln Tunnel.

title: William Medill
paragraph: William Medill (February 1802September 2, 1865) was a Democratic politician from Ohio. [SBD]  He served as the 22nd Governor of Ohio from 1853 to 1856.

title: The Academia Waltz
paragraph: The Academia Waltz was Berkeley Breathed's first cartoon, published daily from 1978 to 1979 in "The Daily Texan" at The University of Texas at Austin, where he was a student. [SBD]  The strip focused primarily on college life, although it sometimes made references to big news stories of the time (such as the Three Mile Island accident in 1979).

title: Arctic Circle Restaurants
paragraph: Arctic Circle Restaurants is a chain of burger and shake restaurants based in Midvale, Utah, United States. [SBD]  There were 87 restaurants as of April 2016, about a third are company owned and two-thirds by franchisees, in Utah, Idaho, Montana, Nevada, Oregon, Washington, and Wyoming. [SBD]  About 50% of the restaurants are located in Utah.

title: Ashlee Simpson
paragraph: Ashley Nicolle Ross (née Simpson; born October 3, 1984), known by the stage name Ashlee Simpson, is an American singer-songwriter and actress. [SBD]  The younger sister of pop singer and actress Jessica Simpson, Ashlee began appearing in television commercials at the age of 15. [SBD]  She later pursued a career as an actress, and had a recurring role on the family drama "7th Heaven". [SBD]  Her breakout came following her appearance on the reality show "" (2003–05), which focused on her sister Jessica and her then-husband Nick Lachey. [SBD]  While working on her debut studio album, Simpson became the star of her own spin-off reality series, "The Ashlee Simpson Show" (2004–05). [SBD]  The show became a ratings hit, and earned Simpson widespread recognition. [SBD]  Like her sister before her, Simpson became the center of considerable media attention, much of which focused on her relationship with musician Ryan Cabrera.

title: Tatsumi Hijikata
paragraph: Tatsumi Hijikata (土方 巽 , Hijikata Tatsumi , March 9, 1928 - January 21, 1986) was a Japanese choreographer, and the founder of a genre of dance performance art called Butoh. [SBD]  By the late 1960s, he had begun to develop this dance form, which is highly choreographed with stylized gestures drawn from his childhood memories of his northern Japan home. [SBD]  It is this style which is most often associated with Butoh by Westerners.

title: Disinflation
paragraph: Disinflation is a decrease in the rate of inflation – a slowdown in the rate of increase of the general price level of goods and services in a nation's gross domestic product over time. [SBD]  It is the opposite of reflation. [SBD]  Disinflation occurs when the increase in the “consumer price level” slows down from the previous period when the prices were rising.

title: David Christopherson
paragraph: David Christopherson (born October 5, 1954) is a Canadian politician. [SBD]  Since 2004, he has represented the riding of Hamilton Centre in the Canadian House of Commons. [SBD]  He previously served in the Legislative Assembly of Ontario from 1990 to 2003, and was a cabinet minister in the provincial government of Bob Rae. [SBD]  Christopherson is a member of the New Democratic Party.

title: Reuben Wood
paragraph: Reuben Wood (1792/1793October 1, 1864) was a Democratic politician from the U.S. state of Ohio. [SBD]  He served as the 21st Governor of Ohio.

title: Ars antiqua
paragraph: Ars antiqua, also called ars veterum or ars vetus, is a term used by modern scholars to refer to the Medieval music of Europe during the high Middle Ages, between approximately 1170 and 1310. [SBD]  This covers the period of the Notre Dame school of polyphony (the use of multiple, simultaneous, independent melodic lines), and the subsequent years which saw the early development of the motet, a highly varied choral musical composition. [SBD]  Usually the term "ars antiqua" is restricted to sacred (church) or polyphonic music, excluding the secular (non-religious) monophonic songs of the troubadours, and trouvères. [SBD]  However, sometimes the term "ars antiqua" is used more loosely to mean all European music of the thirteenth century, and from slightly before. [SBD]  The term "ars antiqua" is used in opposition to "ars nova" (meaning "new art", "new technique" or "new style"), which refers to the period of musical activity between approximately 1310 and 1375.

title: Ars nova
paragraph: Ars nova (Latin for new art) refers to a musical style which flourished in France and the Burgundian Low Countries in the Late Middle Ages: more particularly, in the period between the preparation of the "Roman de Fauvel" (1310s) and the death of the composer Guillaume de Machaut in 1377. [SBD]  The term is sometimes used more generally to refer to all European polyphonic music of the 14th century. [SBD]  For instance, "Italian ars nova" is sometimes used to denote the music of Francesco Landini and his compatriots (although Trecento music is the more common term for music in Italy). [SBD]  The "ars" in "ars nova" can be read as "technique", or "style". [SBD]  The term was first used in two musical treatises, titled "Ars novae musicae" (New Technique of Music) (c. 1320) by Johannes de Muris, and a collection of writings (c. 1322) attributed to Philippe de Vitry often simply called "Ars nova" today. [SBD]  However, the term was only first used to describe an historical era by Johannes Wolf in 1904.

title: List of Allied convoy codes during World War II
paragraph: This is a list of convoy codes used by the Allies during World War II There were over 300 convoy routes organized, in all areas of the world; each was designated by a two- or three letter code. [SBD]  List of Allied convoys during World War II by region provides additional information.

title: John Campbell Merriam
paragraph: John Campbell Merriam (October 20, 1869 – October 30, 1945) was an American paleontologist, educator, and conservationist. [SBD]  The first vertebrate paleontologist on the West Coast of the United States, he is best known for his taxonomy of vertebrate fossils at the La Brea Tar Pits in Los Angeles, particularly with the genus "Smilodon", more commonly known as the sabertooth cat. [SBD]  He is also known for his work to extend the reach of the National Park Service.

title: Interference (chess)
paragraph: In the game of chess, interference occurs when the line between an attacked piece and its defender is interrupted by sacrificially interposing a piece. [SBD]  It is a chess tactic which seldom arises, and is therefore often overlooked. [SBD]  Opportunities for interference are rare because the defended object must be more valuable than the sacrificed piece, and the interposition must itself represent a threat.

title: Richard Speck
paragraph: Richard Benjamin Speck (December 6, 1941 – December 5, 1991) was an American mass murderer who systematically tortured, raped, and murdered eight student nurses from South Chicago Community Hospital on the night of July 13-14, 1966.

title: Saci (Brazilian folklore)
paragraph: Saci (] ] ) is a character in Brazilian folklore. [SBD]  He is a one-legged black or mulatto youngster with holes in the palms of his hands, who smokes a pipe and wears a magical red cap that enables him to disappear and reappear wherever he wishes (usually in the middle of a dust devil). [SBD]  Considered an annoying prankster in most parts of Brazil, and a potentially dangerous and malicious creature in others, he nevertheless grants wishes to anyone who manages to trap him or steal his magic cap. [SBD]  However, his cap is often depicted as having a bad smell. [SBD]  Most people who claimed to have stolen this cap say they can never wash the smell away.

title: Ohio Company
paragraph: The Ohio Company, formally known as the Ohio Company of Virginia, was a land speculation company organized for the settlement by Virginians of the Ohio Country (approximately the present state of Ohio) and to trade with the Native Americans. [SBD]  The company had a land grant from Britain and a treaty with Indians, but France also claimed the area, and the conflict helped provoke the 'outbreak' of the French and Indian War.

title: Mud Islands
paragraph: The Mud Islands reserve is located within Port Phillip, about 90 km south-west of Melbourne, Australia, lying 10 km inside Port Phillip Heads, 7 km north of Portsea and 9 km east of Queenscliff. [SBD]  The land area of about 50 ha is made up of three low-lying islands surrounding a shallow tidal 35 ha lagoon connected to the sea by three narrow channels. [SBD]  The shapes and configuration of the islands change over the years due to movement of sand by tidal currents.

title: Ohio Company of Associates
paragraph: The Ohio Company of Associates, also known as the Ohio Company, was a land company whose members are today credited with becoming the first non-Native American group to settle in the present-day state of Ohio. [SBD]  In 1788 they established Marietta, Ohio as the first permanent settlement of the new United States in the newly organized Northwest Territory.

title: Ramón Emeterio Betances
paragraph: Ramón Emeterio Betances y Alacán (April 8, 1827 – September 16, 1898) was a Puerto Rican nationalist. [SBD]  He was the primary instigator of the Grito de Lares revolution and is considered to be the father of the Puerto Rican independence movement. [SBD]  Since the "Grito" galvanized a burgeoning nationalist movement among Puerto Ricans, Betances is also considered ""El Padre de la Patria"" (Father of the [Puerto Rican] Nation). [SBD]  Because of his charitable deeds for people in need, he also became known as "El Padre de los Pobres" ("The Father of the Poor").

title: Tim Hagans
paragraph: Tim Hagans (born August 19, 1954) is a jazz trumpeter, arranger, and composer. [SBD]  He has been nominated for three Grammy Awards: Best Instrumental Composition for "Box of Cannoli" on "The Avatar Sessions" (Fuzzy Music, 2010); Best Contemporary Jazz Album for "Animation*Imagination" (Blue Note, 1999); and Best Contemporary Jazz Album for "Re-Animation" (Blue Note, 2000).

title: Tupac: Resurrection (soundtrack)
paragraph: Tupac: Resurrection was released by Amaru Entertainment as the soundtrack for the 2003 documentary, Academy Award nominated "". [SBD]  It includes several previously released 2Pac recordings, including "Death Around the Corner" from "Me Against the World", "Secretz of War" from "Still I Rise", Holler If Ya Hear Me from "Strictly 4 My N.I.G.G.A.Z." and "Rebel of the Underground" from "2Pacalypse Now"; and unreleased 2Pac verses re-constructed into new tracks such as "Ghost", "One Day at a Time", and "Runnin (Dying to Live)". [SBD]  Eminem produced major parts of this album. [SBD]  The song "Runnin (Dying to Live)" won the Top Soundtrack Song of the Year award at the 2005 ASCAP Rhythm & Soul Music Awards. [SBD]  The Album Features The Notorious B.I.G., Eminem, 50 Cent, Outlawz, & Digital Underground. [SBD]  "Intro", "Ghost", "Death Around The Corner", "Bury Me A G" and "Str8 Ballin'" do not actually feature in the movie, but appear on the album.

title: Scioto Company
paragraph: The Scioto Company was a French institution which granted worthless deeds in the Northwest Territory, later Ohio, to French colonists.

title: Test target
paragraph: A test target is a common feature on interplanetary landing craft such as the Viking Lander and Mars Exploration Rovers.

title: Delisle scale
paragraph: The Delisle scale (°D) is a temperature scale invented in 1732 by the French astronomer Joseph-Nicolas Delisle (1688–1768). [SBD]  Delisle was the author of "Mémoires pour servir à l'histoire et aux progrès de l'Astronomie, de la Géographie et de la Physique" (1738).

title: Peruvilai
paragraph: Peruvilai is called also as Keezha Peruvilai(Peruvilai)

title: University of the Pacific (United States)
paragraph: The University of the Pacific (also referred to as Pacific or UOP) is a private university in the western United States, located in Stockton, California. [SBD]  It is the oldest chartered university in California, the first independent co-educational campus in California, and both the first conservatory of music and first medical school on the West Coast.

title: French Grant
paragraph: The French Grant (also known as the French-Grant Estates) was a land tract in the Northwest Territory, present day Scioto County, Ohio, that was paid out by the U.S. Congress on March 31, 1795. [SBD]  This was after a group of French colonists were defrauded by the Scioto Company of purchased land grants which rightly were controlled by the Ohio Company of Associates. [SBD]  Not all of the settlers took the grant, some preferring to stay on the East Coast others preferring stay in Gallipolis, Ohio in Gallia County. [SBD]  (Gallia and Gallipolis were named for Gaul, the ancient Latin name of France.)

title: Terry Kath
paragraph: Terry Alan Kath (January 31, 1946 – January 23, 1978) was an American musician and songwriter, best known as the original guitarist, one of the lead singers and founding members of the rock band Chicago. [SBD]  He has been praised by the band for his guitar skills and Ray Charles-influenced vocal style.

title: Tomorrow Never Dies (video game)
paragraph: Tomorrow Never Dies (also known as 007: Tomorrow Never Dies) is a third-person shooter stealth video game based on the James Bond film of the same name. [SBD]  Developed by Black Ops Entertainment and published by Electronic Arts, it was released exclusively for the Sony PlayStation in November 1999. [SBD]  It is the first 007 game of many that was published by Electronic Arts since acquiring the James Bond licence. [SBD]  This game marks the second appearance of Pierce Brosnan's James Bond, although the voice of Bond is provided by actor Adam Blackwood in the game.

title: Rift (album)
paragraph: Rift is the fourth official studio album by the American rock band Phish. [SBD]  It is the band's second concept album, the first being "The Man Who Stepped into Yesterday" in 1987, which has never been officially released. [SBD]  "Rift"'s songs convey the experience of a man dreaming about the rift in his relationship with his girlfriend. [SBD]  Recorded in September and October 1992 and produced by Muscle Shoals music veteran Barry Beckett, the album was released by Elektra Records on February 2, 1993.

title: Ohio Lands
paragraph: The Ohio Lands were the several grants, tracts, districts and cessions which make up what is now the U.S. state of Ohio. [SBD]  The Ohio Country was one of the first settled parts of the Midwest, and indeed one of the first settled parts of the United States beyond the original 13 colonies. [SBD]  The land that became first the anchor of the Northwest Territory and later Ohio was cobbled together from a variety of sources and owners.

title: A Live One
paragraph: A Live One is a live album by the American rock band Phish, released on June 27, 1995, by Elektra Records. [SBD]  The album was the band's first official live release, and their second two-cd album (after "Junta").

title: Village indigobird
paragraph: The village indigobird or steelblue widowfinch ("Vidua chalybeata") is a small songbird belonging to the family Viduidae. [SBD]  It is distinguishable from other indigobird species by bill and leg colours, the colour tinge of the male's breeding plumage, song, and to lesser extent, the nestling's plumage and mouth pattern. [SBD]  The bill colour can be red or white depending on the population, and there is some regional variation in the colour tone of the male's plumage.

title: Mercedes-Benz GLK-Class
paragraph: The Mercedes-Benz GLK (codename X204) is a compact luxury crossover SUV that went on sale from the autumn of 2008 after its public debut at the 2008 Beijing Auto Show alongside the competing Audi Q5.

title: Slip Stitch and Pass
paragraph: Slip Stitch and Pass is the second official live album by the American rock band Phish. [SBD]  It was released on October 28, 1997, by Elektra Records and has nine tracks from the band's March 1, 1997, show at the Markthalle Hamburg in Hamburg, Germany, which was part of Phish's 1997 European Tour.

title: The Story of the Ghost
paragraph: The Story of the Ghost is the seventh official studio album by American rock band Phish. [SBD]  It was released by Elektra Records on October 27, 1998.

title: Netherlands Trading Society
paragraph: The Netherlands Trading Society (Dutch: "Nederlandsche Handel-Maatschappij" or NHM) was a Dutch trading company established in 1824 by King Willem I of the Netherlands to promote and develop trade, shipping and agriculture. [SBD]  For the next 140 years the NHM developed a large international branch network and increasingly engaged in banking operations, and subsequently would become one of the primary ancestors of ABN AMRO.

title: Farmhouse (album)
paragraph: Farmhouse is the eighth official studio album by the American rock band Phish. [SBD]  The tracks were recorded at The Barn, frontman Trey Anastasio's studio in Chittenden County, Vermont. [SBD]  The album was released on May 16, 2000, by Elektra Records. [SBD]  "Farmhouse" was the last Phish studio album before their temporary split in October 2000 (the band subsequently returned in late 2002).

title: Qi Baishi
paragraph: Qi Baishi (1 January 1864 – 16 September 1957) was an influential Chinese painter, noted for the whimsical, often playful style of his watercolor works.

title: Páll Guðmundsson
paragraph: Páll Guðmundsson (] ; born 1959 in Húsafell in the west of Iceland, where he still lives) is a sculptor and artist.

title: The Siket Disc
paragraph: The Siket Disc is a 1999/2000 release from the American band Phish. [SBD]  (It was released in 1999 through the Phish web site and mailordering system, but did not reach stores until November 7, 2000, from Elektra Records.)

title: List of defunct banks of the Netherlands
paragraph: This page exists to list banks from the Netherlands about which we have only the barest information.

title: Hoist (album)
paragraph: Hoist (stylized as (Hoist)) is the fifth official studio album by American rock band Phish, released on March 29, 1994, by Elektra Records. [SBD]  At the time of its release, "Hoist" was Phish's best selling album to date, peaking at #34 on the Billboard 200 albums chart.

title: Pin-tailed whydah
paragraph: The pin-tailed whydah ("Vidua macroura") is a small songbird with a conspicuous pennant-like tail in breeding males. [SBD]  It is a resident breeding bird in most of Africa south of the Sahara Desert.

title: Timeline of Ahmedabad
paragraph: This page provides a Historical timeline of Ahmedabad, the sixth largest city in India.

title: Round Room
paragraph: Round Room is the ninth official studio album by the American rock band Phish, released on December 10, 2002, by Elektra Records. [SBD]  The album was recorded and released in the lead up to Phish's reunion concert on New Year's Eve 2002 at Madison Square Garden, which marked the end of the band's two-and-a-half year break.

title: Procalcitonin
paragraph: Procalcitonin (PCT) is a peptide precursor of the hormone calcitonin, the latter being involved with calcium homeostasis. [SBD]  It was first identified by Leonard J. Deftos and Bernard A. Roos in the 1970s. [SBD]  It is composed of 116 amino acids and is produced by parafollicular cells (C cells) of the thyroid and by the neuroendocrine cells of the lung and the intestine.

title: Lepidosireniformes
paragraph: Lepidosireniformes are an order of lungfish containing the families Lepidosirenidae (the South American lungfish) and Protopteridae (the African lungfish). [SBD]  Both of the two families are monogeneric, and the sole genus of the family Lepidosirenidae is also monospecific.

title: Smithsonian Institution Building
paragraph: The Smithsonian Institution Building, located near the National Mall in Washington, D.C. behind the National Museum of African Art and the Sackler Gallery, houses the Smithsonian Institution's administrative offices and information center. [SBD]  The building is constructed of Seneca red sandstone in the faux Norman style (a 12th-century combination of late Romanesque and early Gothic motifs; built in the Gothic and Romanesque revival styles) and is nicknamed The Castle. [SBD]  It was completed in 1855 and designated a National Historic Landmark in 1965.

title: Comte
paragraph: Comte is the French, Catalan and Occitan form of the word 'count' (Latin: "comes"); comté is the Gallo-Romance form of the word 'county' (Latin: "comitatus").

title: Answers in Genesis
paragraph: Answers in Genesis (AiG) is a fundamentalist Christian apologetics parachurch organization. [SBD]  It advocates a literal or historical-grammatical interpretation of the Book of Genesis, with a particular focus on a pseudoscientific promotion of young Earth creationism, rejecting any results of scientific investigation which do not conform to their literal interpretation of the Genesis creation narrative. [SBD]  The organization sees evolution as incompatible with scripture and believes anything other than the young earth view is a compromise on biblical inerrancy.

title: Garrincha
paragraph: Manuel Francisco dos Santos (28 October 1933 – 20 January 1983), known by the nickname Garrincha (] , "little bird"), was a Brazilian footballer who played right winger and forward. [SBD]  He is regarded by many in the sport to be one of the best dribblers in football history.

title: José Jiménez (character)
paragraph: José Jiménez was a fictional character created and performed by comedian Bill Dana on "The Steve Allen Show" in 1959 and who became increasingly popular during the 1960s. [SBD]  This character introduced himself with the catch phrase: "My name... José Jiménez". [SBD]  Dana played José in three non-variety shows: "Make Room For Daddy", which spun off "The Bill Dana Show", and a cameo in an episode of "Batman" ("The Yegg Foes in Gotham", October 20, 1966).

title: Exercise Tiger
paragraph: Exercise Tiger, or Operation Tiger, was the code name for one in a series of large-scale rehearsals for the D-Day invasion of Normandy, which took place in April 1944 on Slapton Sands in Devon. [SBD]  Coordination and communication problems resulted in friendly fire deaths during the exercise, and an Allied convoy positioning itself for the landing was attacked by E-boats of Nazi Germany's "Kriegsmarine", resulting in the deaths of at least 749 American servicemen. [SBD]  Because of the impending invasion of Normandy, the incident was under the strictest secrecy at the time and was only nominally reported afterwards.

title: North Jersey
paragraph: North Jersey comprises the northern portions of the U.S. state of New Jersey between the upper Delaware River and the Atlantic Ocean. [SBD]  The designation of northern New Jersey with a distinct toponym is a colloquial one rather than an administrative one, reflecting not only geographical but also perceived cultural differences from the southern part of the state, with no official definition.

title: Saag
paragraph: Saag (] ) (Nepali: साग ) (Sindhi: ساڳ‎ ) or sag is a leaf-based (spinach, mustard leaf, collard greens, basella, etc.) dish eaten in the Indian subcontinent with bread such as roti or naan, or rice (in Nepal, Odisha and West Bengal). [SBD]  Saag can be made from spinach, mustard leaves, finely chopped broccoli, or other greens, along with added spices and sometimes other ingredients such as paneer. [SBD]  On some menus, it is called saagwala.

title: Uta Barth
paragraph: Uta Barth (born 1958 in Berlin, Germany) is a contemporary photographer who lives and works in Los Angeles, California. [SBD]  Barth is a 2012 MacArthur Fellow and a recipient of the John Simon Guggenheim Fellowship in 2004‑05.

title: Shemot
paragraph: Shemot is a Hebrew word, which is the second word of the Book of Exodus, the second book of the Torah (the first five books of the Tanakh, or Hebrew Bible). [SBD]  It means "Names".

title: National Museum of American History
paragraph: The National Museum of American History: Kenneth E. Behring Center collects, preserves, and displays the heritage of the United States in the areas of social, political, cultural, scientific, and military history. [SBD]  Among the items on display is the original Star-Spangled Banner. [SBD]  The museum is part of the Smithsonian Institution and located on the National Mall at 14th Street and Constitution Avenue NW in Washington, D.C.

title: The Raccoons
paragraph: The Raccoons is a Canadian animated series which was originally broadcast from 1985 to 1992, with three preceding television specials from its inception in 1980, and one direct to video special in 1984. [SBD]  The franchise was created by Kevin Gillis with the co-operation of the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (French: "Société Radio-Canada").

title: Rainbow Brite
paragraph: Rainbow Brite, also known in Japan as Magical Girl Rainbow Brite (魔法少女レインボーブライト , Mahō Shōjo Reinbō Buraito ) , is a media franchise by Hallmark Cards, introduced in 1983. [SBD]  The animated television series of the same name first aired in 1984, the same year Hallmark licensed Rainbow Brite to Mattel for a range of dolls and other merchandise. [SBD]  A theatrical feature-length film, "Rainbow Brite and the Star Stealer" was released by Warner Bros. in 1985. [SBD]  The franchise was rebooted in 1996, 2003, 2009, and then again in 2014 through Hallmark's online on-demand streaming video service, Feeln. [SBD]  2015 also saw with it a line of new merchandise sold only by Hallmark online and in its shops.

title: Robert Jungk
paragraph: Robert Jungk (] ; born "Robert Baum", also known as "Robert Baum-Jungk"; May 11, 1913 – July 14, 1994) was an Austrian writer and journalist who wrote mostly on issues relating to nuclear weapons.

title: Yuzhnoye Design Office
paragraph: Yuzhnoye Design Office (Ukrainian: Державне конструкторське бюро «Південне» ім. [SBD]  М. [SBD]  К. [SBD]  Янгеля ; Russian: Констру́кторское бюро́ «Ю́жное» ), located in Dnipro, Ukraine, is a designer of satellites and rockets, and formerly of Soviet intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs) established by Mikhail Yangel. [SBD]  Yuzhnoye's OKB designation was OKB-586.

title: National Museum of Natural History
paragraph: The National Museum of Natural History is a natural history museum administered by the Smithsonian Institution, located on the National Mall in Washington, D.C., United States. [SBD]  It has free admission and is open 364 days a year. [SBD]  In 2016, with 7.1 million visitors, it was the fourth most visited museum in the world, and the most visited natural history museum in the world . [SBD]  Opened in 1910, the museum on the National Mall was one of the first Smithsonian buildings constructed exclusively to hold the national collections and research facilities. [SBD]  The main building has an overall area of 1,500,000 ft2 with 325,000 ft2 of exhibition and public space and houses over 1,000 employees.

title: Mayors for Peace
paragraph: Mayors for Peace is an international organization of cities dedicated to the promotion of peace that was established in 1982 at the initiative of then Mayor of Hiroshima Takeshi Araki, in response to the deaths of around 140,000 people due to the atomic bombing of the city on August 6, 1945.

title: Takeshi Araki
paragraph: Takeshi Araki (荒木 武 , Araki Takeshi , March 4, 1916 – June 17, 1994) was the mayor of Hiroshima from 1975 to 1991.

title: Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden
paragraph: The Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden is an art museum beside the National Mall, in Washington, D.C., the United States. [SBD]  The museum was initially endowed during the 1960s with the permanent art collection of Joseph H. Hirshhorn. [SBD]  It was designed by architect Gordon Bunshaft and is part of the Smithsonian Institution. [SBD]  It was conceived as the United States' museum of contemporary and modern art and currently focuses its collection-building and exhibition-planning mainly on the post–World War II period, with particular emphasis on art made during the last 50 years.

title: Zenit (rocket family)
paragraph: Zenit (Ukrainian: Зеніт , Russian: Зени́т ; meaning "Zenith") is a family of space launch vehicles designed by the Yuzhnoye Design Bureau in Dnipro, Ukraine, which was then part of the Soviet Union. [SBD]  Zenit was originally built in the 1980s for two purposes: as a liquid rocket booster for the Energia rocket and, equipped with a second stage, as a stand-alone middle-weight launcher with a payload greater than the 7 tonnes of the Soyuz but smaller than the 20 tonnes payload of the Proton. [SBD]  The last rocket family developed in the USSR, the Zenit was intended as an eventual replacement for the dated R-7 and Proton families, and it would employ propellants which were safer and less toxic than the Proton's nitrogen tetroxide/UDMH mix. [SBD]  Zenit was planned to take over manned spaceship launches from Soyuz, but these plans were abandoned after the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.

title: Remastering
paragraph: Remaster refers to quality enhancement of sound and/or picture of a previously existing recording.

title: Zenit
paragraph: Zenit, meaning zenith, may refer to:

title: Nell's
paragraph: Nell's (or Nells) was a nightclub located on 246 West 14th Street in downtown Manhattan. [SBD]  It opened in the fall of 1986 in the space of a former electronics store and closed May 30, 2004. [SBD]  Actress-singer Nell Campbell was its namesake and longtime proprietress. [SBD]  Initially, she co-owned the club with Lynn Wagenknecht and Keith McNally. [SBD]  McNally gave up ownership when he and Wagenknecht divorced.

title: Dram (unit)
paragraph: The dram (alternative British spelling drachm; apothecary symbol ʒ or ℨ; abbreviated dr) is a unit of mass in the avoirdupois system, and both a unit of mass and a unit of volume in the apothecaries' system. [SBD]  It was originally both a coin and a weight in ancient Greece. [SBD]  The unit of volume is more correctly called a fluid dram, fluid drachm, fluidram or fluidrachm (abbreviated fl dr, ƒ 3, or fʒ).

title: Armenian dram
paragraph: The dram (Armenian: Դրամ ; sign: ֏; code: AMD) is the monetary unit of Armenia. [SBD]  It is subdivided into 100 luma (Armenian: լումա ). [SBD]  The word "dram" translates into English as "money" and is cognate with the Greek drachma and the Arabic dirham. [SBD]  The first instance of a dram currency was in the period from 1199 to 1375, when silver coins called dram were issued.

title: Raven (DC Comics)
paragraph: Raven is a fictional superheroine appearing in American comic books published by DC Comics. [SBD]  The character first appeared in a special insert in "DC Comics Presents" #26 (October 1980), and was created by writer Marv Wolfman and artist George Pérez. [SBD]  The daughter of a demon father (Trigon) and human mother (Arella), Raven is an empath who can teleport and control her "soul-self", which can fight physically, as well as act as Raven's eyes and ears away from her physical body. [SBD]  She is a prominent member of the superhero team Teen Titans. [SBD]  The character also goes by the alias Rachel Roth.

title: Kane Hodder
paragraph: Kane Warren Hodder (born April 8, 1955) is an American actor, stuntman, and author.

title: Amin al-Majaj
paragraph: Dr Amin Saleh Majaj (Arabic: أمين المجاج‎ ‎ , Āmeen Majjaj ) (born Ramallah March 21, 1921 – died East Jerusalem January 2, 1999) was a titular mayor of Jerusalem, formerly the neighborhoods of East Jerusalem that were occupied and annexed by Jordan during the years 1949–1967, and later occupied and annexed by Israel in the Six-Day War.

title: 1937 in sports
paragraph: 1937 in sports describes the year's events in world sport.

title: Hawkgirl
paragraph: Hawkgirl is the name of several fictional superheroines appearing in American comic books published by DC Comics. [SBD]  The original Hawkgirl, Shiera Sanders Hall, was created by writer Gardner Fox and artist Dennis Neville, and first appeared in "Flash Comics" #1 (January 1940). [SBD]  Shayera Hol was created by writer Gardner Fox and artist Joe Kubert, and first appeared in "The Brave and the Bold" #34 (March 1961). [SBD]  Kendra Saunders was created by writer David S. Goyer, writer James Robinson, and artist Stephen Sadowski, and first appeared in "JSA Secret Files and Origins" #1 (August 1999). [SBD]  One of DC's earliest super-heroines, Hawkgirl has appeared in many of the company's flagship team-up titles including Justice Society of America and Justice League of America.

title: Iron Gates
paragraph: The Iron Gates (Romanian: "Porțile de Fier" , Serbian: "Đerdapska klisura" , German: "Eisernes Tor" ) is a gorge on the Danube River. [SBD]  It forms part of the boundary between Serbia and Romania. [SBD]  In the broad sense it encompasses a route of 134 km ; in the narrow sense it only encompasses the last barrier on this route, just beyond the Romanian city of Orșova, that contains two hydroelectric dams, with two power stations, Iron Gate I Hydroelectric Power Station and Iron Gate II Hydroelectric Power Station.

title: Tr (Unix)
paragraph: tr is a command in Unix-like operating systems. [SBD]  It is an abbreviation of "translate" or "transliterate", indicating its operation of replacing or removing specific characters in its input data set.

title: Confessionalization
paragraph: In Protestant Reformation history, confessionalization is the parallel processes of "confession-building" taking place in Europe between the Peace of Augsburg (1555) and the Thirty Years' War (1618-1649). [SBD]  During this time prior to the Thirty Years' War, there was a nominal peace between the Protestant and Catholic confessions as both competed to establish their faith more firmly with the population of their respective area. [SBD]  This confession-building occurred through "social-disciplining," as there was a stricter enforcement by the churches of their particular rules for all aspects of life in both Protestant and Catholic areas. [SBD]  This had the consequence of creating distinctive confessional identities.

title: Zaza language
paragraph: Zaza language, also called Zazaki, Kirmanjki and Dimli, is an Indo-European language spoken primarily in eastern Turkey by the Zazas. [SBD]  The language is a part of the northwestern group of the Iranian section of the Indo-European family, and belongs to the Zaza–Gorani and Caspian dialect group. [SBD]  Zaza shares many features, structures, and vocabulary with Gorani. [SBD]  Zaza also has some similarities with Talyshi and other Caspian languages. [SBD]  According to Ethnologue (which cites [Paul 1998]), the number of speakers is between 1.5 and 2.5 million (including all dialects). [SBD]  According to Nevins, the number of Zaza speakers is between 2 and 4 million.

title: Meir Nitzan
paragraph: Meir Nitzan (Hebrew: מאיר ניצן‎ ‎ ; born 1932) is an Israeli politician. [SBD]  He was mayor of Rishon Lezion for five consecutive terms.

title: Moussaka
paragraph: Moussaka ( , or ) is an eggplant- (aubergine) or potato-based dish, often including ground meat, in the Levant, Middle East, and Balkans, with many local and regional variations.

title: Prime Minister of Afghanistan
paragraph: The Prime Minister of Afghanistan is a currently defunct post in the Afghan Government.

title: The Butterfly Effect (band)
paragraph: The Butterfly Effect is an alternative metal band from Brisbane, Australia, formed in 1999. [SBD]  The band released a self-titled debut EP in 2001, and then three full-length album afterwards; "Begins Here" in 2003, "Imago" in 2006, and "Final Conversation of Kings" in 2008. [SBD]  During this time, the band consisted of Clint Boge on lead vocals, Kurt Goedhart on guitar, Glenn Esmond on bass, and Ben Hall on drums. [SBD]  After struggling for years to work on a fourth studio album, Boge left the band in 2012 due to personal and creative differences. [SBD]  The remaining members recruited Brisbane-based singer Paul Galagher for a final single and tour before announcing their breakup in 2016. [SBD]  In July 2017, the band announced their reunion as well as a headlining tour scheduled to take place in March 2018.

title: International Watch Company
paragraph: International Watch Co., also known as IWC, is a luxury Swiss watch manufacturer located in Schaffhausen, Switzerland, and founded by American watchmaker Florentine Ariosto Jones in 1868.

title: Usher (album)
paragraph: Usher is the eponymous debut studio album by American singer Usher. [SBD]  It was released on August 30, 1994, by LaFace Records. [SBD]  As executive producer, Sean "Puffy" Combs mostly did the production work on this album, as well as the additional production that were provided by Chucky Thompson, DeVante Swing and Al B. Sure! [SBD] , among others. [SBD]  The album debuted at number 167 on the US "Billboard" 200. [SBD]  The release of the album was accompanied by the supported of three singles: "Can U Get wit It", "Think of You" and "The Many Ways".

title: Abdelkarim Hussein Mohamed Al-Nasser
paragraph: The Saudi Abdelkarim Hussein Mohamed Al-Nasser (Arabic: عبد الكريم حسين محمد الناصر‎ ‎ ) is an alleged member and suspected leader of the terrorist organization Saudi Hizballah, wanted in the United States in connection with 1996 Khobar Towers bombing.

title: Stamford Bridge, East Riding of Yorkshire
paragraph: Stamford Bridge is a village and civil parish on the River Derwent in the East Riding of Yorkshire, England, approximately 7 mi east of York and 22 mi west of Driffield. [SBD]  The village lies on the border with the Ryedale district of North Yorkshire.

title: Live (Usher album)
paragraph: Live is a live album by American singer Usher. [SBD]  It was recorded on October 15 and 16, 1998 in the singer's hometown of Chattanooga, Tennessee, and released by LaFace Records on March 23, 1999. [SBD]  Both audio-only and video longform versions were released; it was distributed to break up the gap between Usher's second and third studio albums, "My Way" (1997) and "8701" (2001).

title: Law dictionary
paragraph: A law dictionary is a dictionary that is designed and compiled to give information about terms used in the field of law.

8701 is the third studio album by American singer Usher; it was first released on August 7, 2001, by Arista Records. [SBD]  Recording was handled by several producers including The Neptunes, Jermaine Dupri, Babyface, Kevin "She'kspere" Briggs, Mike City, Bryan Michael Cox, Jimmy Jam & Terry Lewis. [SBD]  Although intended for an October 31, 2000, release under the title "All About U", the album was delayed numerous times, following the leak of several tracks onto the online music store Napster. [SBD]  Usher subsequently recorded new tracks and released the album under the new title, "8701", which is derived from Usher singing for the first time in his local church in 1987 and the album's release date of 2001.

title: Chișinău International Airport
paragraph: Chișinău International Airport (IATA: KIV, ICAO: LUKK) is Moldova's main international airport, located 13 km southeast of the centre of Chișinău, the capital city. [SBD]  It serves as headquarters for Air Moldova, the country's national airline. [SBD]  The IATA airport code KIV is derived from Kishinev (the Russified name of the city).

title: Masters Qualifying Event
paragraph: The Masters Qualifying Event was a professional snooker tournament, which ran from 1990 to 2009. [SBD]  Each season, the winner of the event was awarded a wild-card to play at the Masters.

title: Under My Skin (Avril Lavigne album)
paragraph: Under My Skin is the second studio album by Canadian singer-songwriter Avril Lavigne that was released through the RCA Records Label internationally throughout May 2004. [SBD]  Lavigne wrote most of the album with singer-songwriter Chantal Kreviazuk, who invited her to a Malibu in-house recording studio shared by Kreviazuk and her husband Raine Maida, where Lavigne recorded many of the songs. [SBD]  The album was produced by Maida, Don Gilmore, and Butch Walker.

title: Olof Salmén
paragraph: Olof Salmén (born 1927) is a politician in the Åland Islands, an autonomous and Swedish-speaking territory of Finland.

title: Earl Blumenauer
paragraph: Earl Blumenauer (born August 16, 1948) is the U.S. Representative for Oregon 's 3 congressional district , serving since 1996. [SBD]  He is a member of the Democratic Party. [SBD]  The district includes most of Portland east of the Willamette River. [SBD]  He previously spent over 20 years as a public official in Portland, including serving on the Portland City Council from 1987 to 1996.

title: Tim Collins (politician)
paragraph: Timothy William George Collins, CBE, (born 7 May 1964) is a British politician, once a prominent member of the Conservative Party. [SBD]  Collins was active in the 1990s and was later the Member of Parliament (MP) for Westmorland and Lonsdale in north-west England from 1997 until his defeat at the 2005 general election by Tim Farron, later leader of the Liberal Democrats.

title: Col (game)
paragraph: Col is a pencil and paper game, specifically a map-coloring game, involving the shading of areas in a line drawing according to the rules of Graph coloring. [SBD]  With each move, the graph must remain proper (no two areas of the same colour may touch), and a player who cannot make a legal move loses. [SBD]  The game was described and analysed by John Conway, who attributed it to Colin Vout, in On Numbers and Games.

title: Tim Collins (British Army officer)
paragraph: Colonel Timothy Thomas Cyril "Tim" Collins, OBE (born April 1960) is a retired Northern Irish military officer in the British Army. [SBD]  He is best known for his role in the Iraq War in 2003, and his inspirational eve-of-battle speech, a copy of which apparently hung in the White House's Oval Office. [SBD]  He is currently Chairman (and co-founder) of intelligence-based security services company New Century.

title: Honolulu Stadium
paragraph: Honolulu Stadium was a stadium located in the Moʻ iliʻ ili district of Honolulu, Hawai'i, at the corner of King and Isenberg Streets. [SBD]  It was opened in 1926 and demolished in 1976. [SBD]  It was the primary sports venue in Hawaiʻ i preceding Aloha Stadium. [SBD]  Famous athletes who competed in Honolulu Stadium include Babe Ruth, Joe DiMaggio, who hit a home run out of the park in 1944, and Jesse Owens.

title: Greg Walden
paragraph: Gregory Paul Walden (born January 10, 1957) is an American politician, the U.S. Representative for Oregon 's 2 congressional district , first elected to that office in 1998. [SBD]  He is a member of the Republican Party, and the only Republican member of the congressional delegation from Oregon. [SBD]  The 2nd district covers more than two-thirds of the state (generally, east of the Cascades). [SBD]  He is the son of Paul E. Walden, three-term Oregon state representative.

title: Geneva Public Transport
paragraph: Geneva Public Transport (French: Transports publics genevois , TPG) operates most of the public transportation system in Geneva Canton, Switzerland, including the city of Geneva. [SBD]  The agency's head office is in Grand-Lancy, Lancy.

title: Frank B. Willis
paragraph: Frank Bartlett Willis (December 28, 1871March 30, 1928) was a Republican politician from Ohio. [SBD]  He served as the 47th Governor of Ohio from 1915 to 1917, then served as a U.S. Senator from Ohio from 1921 until his death in 1928.

title: Fried Green Tomatoes at the Whistle Stop Cafe
paragraph: Fried Green Tomatoes at the Whistle Stop Cafe is a 1987 novel by Fannie Flagg. [SBD]  It weaves together the past and the present through the blossoming friendship between Evelyn Couch, a middle-aged housewife, and Ninny Threadgoode, an elderly woman who lives in a nursing home. [SBD]  Every week Evelyn visits Ninny, who tells her stories about her youth in Whistle Stop, Alabama where her sister-in-law, Idgie, and her friend, Ruth, ran a café. [SBD]  These stories, along with Ninny's friendship, enable Evelyn to begin a new, satisfying life while allowing the people and stories of Ninny's youth to live on. [SBD]  The book was also made into a movie, and explores themes of family, aging, lesbianism, and the dehumanizing effects of racism on both blacks and whites.

title: Judson Harmon
paragraph: Judson Harmon (February 3, 1846February 22, 1927) was a Democratic politician from Ohio. [SBD]  He served as United States Attorney General under President Grover Cleveland and later served as the 45th Governor of Ohio.

title: Zohar Manna
paragraph: Zohar Manna (born 1939) is a professor of computer science at Stanford University. [SBD]  He is the author of "The Mathematical Theory of Computation" (McGraw Hill, 1974; reprinted Dover, 2003), one of the first texts to provide extensive coverage of the mathematical concepts behind computer programming.

title: Fried green tomatoes (disambiguation)
paragraph: Fried green tomatoes are a traditional side dish in the Southern United States.

title: Stanley Cohen (sociologist)
paragraph: Stanley Cohen, FBA (23 February 1942 – 7 January 2013) was a sociologist and criminologist, Professor of Sociology at the London School of Economics, known for breaking academic ground on "emotional management", including the mismanagement of emotions in the form of sentimentality, overreaction, and emotional denial. [SBD]  He had a lifelong concern with human rights violations, first growing up in South Africa, later studying imprisonment in England and finally in Palestine. [SBD]  He founded the Centre for the Study of Human Rights at the London School of Economics.

title: Stanley Cohen (biochemist)
paragraph: Stanley Cohen (born November 17, 1922) is an American biochemist who, along with Rita Levi-Montalcini, was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1986 for the isolation of nerve growth factor and the discovery of epidermal growth factor.

title: Saimin
paragraph: Saimin is a noodle soup dish developed by different immigrant groups in Hawaii. [SBD]  Inspired by Japanese ramen, Chinese mein, and Filipino pancit, saimin was developed during Hawaii's plantation era. [SBD]  It is a soup dish of that consists of soft wheat egg noodles served in hot "dashi" garnished with green onions. " [SBD] Kamaboko", "char siu", sliced Spam, "linguiça", and "nori" , among other additions.

title: Willard Brown
paragraph: Willard Jessie Brown (26 June 1915 – 4 August 1996), nicknamed "Home Run" Brown, was an American baseball player who played outfielder in the Negro leagues and in Major League Baseball (MLB). [SBD]  He is a member of the Baseball Hall of Fame.

title: Quavers
paragraph: Quavers are a British snack food, originally made by Smiths, and now produced by Walkers. [SBD]  Walkers, part of the PepsiCo family, purchased the Quavers brand in 1997 where it became one of the Frito Lay International brand names.

title: Nineteenth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland
paragraph: Nineteenth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland

title: New Charter University
paragraph: New Charter University is a for-profit, accredited distance learning university headquartered in Salt Lake City, Utah.

title: Thavory Meas Bong
paragraph: Thavory Meas Bong (ថាវរីមាសបង)is a Cambodian melodramatic film of the late 1960s directed by Uon Kon Thuok of Korng Chak Pheap Yun. [SBD]  The film stars Kong Som Oeurn, Saom Vansodany, Vichara Dany and So Hean.

title: Correlation ratio
paragraph: In statistics, the correlation ratio is a measure of the relationship between the statistical dispersion within individual categories and the dispersion across the whole population or sample. [SBD]  The measure is defined as the "ratio" of two standard deviations representing these types of variation. [SBD]  The context here is the same as that of the intraclass correlation coefficient, whose value is the square of the correlation ratio.

title: Chad Varah
paragraph: Edward Chad Varah, {'1': ", '2': ", '3': ", '4': "} (12 November 1911 – 8 November 2007) was a British Anglican priest. [SBD]  He is best remembered as the founder of the Samaritans, established in 1953 as the world's first crisis hotline telephone support to those contemplating suicide.

title: John M. Pattison
paragraph: John M. Pattison (June 13, 1847 – June 18, 1906) was a Democratic politician from Ohio. [SBD]  Pattison was the 43rd Governor of Ohio, serving for a shorter period than any other person elected to the office before his death.

title: American Topical Association
paragraph: The American Topical Association (ATA) is a US-based philatelic society and the largest organization devoted to topical stamp collecting. [SBD]  It was established in 1949, and currently serves members in over 60 countries. [SBD]  ATA publishes "Topical Time", its bimonthly journal. [SBD]  It also publishes numerous handbooks and maintains checklists of philatelic material organized by topics. [SBD]  The organization runs the National Topical Stamp Show as well as supporting 50+ study units on various topics and 40+ local chapters.

title: Bras d'Or Lake
paragraph: Bras d'Or Lake is an inland sea, or large body of partially fresh/salt water in the centre of Cape Breton Island in the province of Nova Scotia, Canada. [SBD]  Bras d'Or Lake is sometimes referred to as the "Bras d'Or Lakes" or the "Bras d'Or Lakes system"; however, its official geographic name is "Bras d'Or Lake" as it is a singular entity. [SBD]  Canadian author and yachtsman Silver Donald Cameron describes Bras d'Or Lake as "A basin ringed by indigo hills laced with marble. [SBD]  Islands within a sea inside an island." [SBD]  The lake is connected to the North Atlantic by natural channels, the Great Bras d'Or Channel north of Boularderie Island and the Little Bras d'Or Channel to south of Boularderie Island, connect the northeastern arm of the lake to the Cabot Strait. [SBD]  The Bras d'Or is also connected to Atlantic Ocean via the Strait of Canso by means of a lock canal completed in 1869—the St. Peters Canal, at the southern tip of the lake.

title: San Diego Convention Center
paragraph: The San Diego Convention Center is the primary convention center in San Diego, California. [SBD]  It is located in the Marina district of downtown San Diego near the Gaslamp Quarter, at 111 West Harbor Drive. [SBD]  The center is managed by the San Diego Convention Center Corporation, a non-profit public benefit corporation created by the City of San Diego. [SBD]  The corporation also manages the San Diego Civic Theatre through a subsidiary called San Diego Theatres Inc.

title: Myron T. Herrick
paragraph: Myron Timothy Herrick (October 9, 1854March 31, 1929) was a Republican politician from Ohio. [SBD]  He served as the 42nd Governor of Ohio.

title: Holy Piby
paragraph: The Holy Piby is a proto-Rastafari text written by an Anguillan, Robert Athlyi Rogers (d. 1931), for the use of an Afrocentric religion in the West Indies founded by Rogers in the 1920s, known as the Afro-Athlican Constructive Gaathly. [SBD]  The theology outlined in this work saw Ethiopians (in the classical sense of all Africans) as the chosen people of God. [SBD]  The church preached self-reliance and self-determination for Africans, using the Piby as its guiding document.

title: Bellinzona
paragraph: Bellinzona (] ; French: "Bellinzone" ] , German: "Bellenz" ] , Romansh: "Blizuna" ] ) is the capital of the canton Ticino in Switzerland. [SBD]  The city is famous for its three castles (Castelgrande, Montebello, Sasso Corbaro) that have been UNESCO World Heritage Sites since 2000.

title: George K. Nash
paragraph: George Kilbon Nash (August 14, 1842October 28, 1904) was a Republican politician from Ohio. [SBD]  He served as the 41st Governor of Ohio.

title: Escape from L.A.
paragraph: Escape from L.A. (also known as John Carpenter's Escape from L.A. or Escape from Los Angeles) is a 1996 American science fiction action film co-written, co-scored, and directed by John Carpenter, co-written and produced by Debra Hill and Kurt Russell, with Russell also starring as Snake Plissken. [SBD]  A sequel to "Escape from New York", "Escape from L.A." co-stars Steve Buscemi, Stacy Keach, Bruce Campbell, and Pam Grier.

title: Asa S. Bushnell (governor)
paragraph: Asa Smith Bushnell I (September 16, 1834 – January 15, 1904) was a Republican politician from Ohio. [SBD]  He served as the 40th Governor of Ohio. [SBD]  Prior to becoming governor, he served as the president of the Warder, Bushnell and Glessner Company, which became one of four companies that merged to form International Harvester. [SBD]  Other roles in business included serving as president of the Springfield Gas Company and the First National Bank of Springfield.

title: Bristol Airport
paragraph: Bristol Airport (IATA: BRS, ICAO: EGGD) , located at Lulsgate Bottom in North Somerset, is the commercial airport serving the city of Bristol, England, and the surrounding area. [SBD]  It is 7 NM southwest of Bristol city centre. [SBD]  Built on the site of a former RAF airfield, it opened in 1957 as Bristol (Lulsgate) Airport, replacing Bristol (Whitchurch) Airport as Bristol's municipal airport. [SBD]  From 1997 to 2010 it was known as Bristol International Airport. [SBD]  In 1997 a majority shareholding in the airport was sold to FirstGroup, and then in 2001 the airport was sold to a joint venture of Macquarie Group and others. [SBD]  In September 2014, Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan bought out Macquarie to become the sole owner.

title: Harriet Boyd Hawes
paragraph: Harriet Boyd Hawes (October 11, 1871 – March 31, 1945) was a pioneering American archaeologist, nurse, and relief worker. [SBD]  She is best known as the discoverer and first director of Gournia, one of the first archaeological excavations to uncover a Minoan settlement and palace on the Aegean island of Crete.

title: Antonín Novotný
paragraph: Antonín Josef Novotný (10 December 1904 – 28 January 1975) was General Secretary of the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia from 1953 to 1968, and also held the post of President of Czechoslovakia from 1957 to 1968. [SBD]  An ardent hardliner, Novotný was forced to yield the reins of power to Alexander Dubček during the short-lived reform movement of 1968.

title: Operation Buccaneer
paragraph: Operation Buccaneer is an "ongoing international copyright piracy investigation and prosecution" undertaken by the United States federal government.

title: Sailor Art Thomas
paragraph: Arthur Thomas (January 30, 1924 – March 20, 2003), better known as Sailor Art Thomas, was an American Merchant Mariner, bodybuilder and professional wrestler.

title: Punchbowl Crater
paragraph: Punchbowl Crater (546 ft) is an extinct volcanic tuff cone located in Honolulu, Hawaii. [SBD]  It is the location of the National Memorial Cemetery of the Pacific.

title: James E. Campbell
paragraph: James Edwin Campbell (July 7, 1843 – December 18, 1924) was a Democratic politician from Ohio. [SBD]  He served as the 38th Governor of Ohio.

title: Jay Hammond
paragraph: Jay Sterner Hammond (July 21, 1922 – August 2, 2005) was an American politician of the Republican Party, who served as the fourth Governor of Alaska from 1974 to 1982. [SBD]  Hammond was born in Troy, New York and served as a Marine Corps fighter pilot in World War II with the Black Sheep Squadron. [SBD]  In 1946, he moved to Alaska where he worked as a bush pilot. [SBD]  Hammond served as a state representative from 1959 to 1965 and as a state senator from 1967 to 1973. [SBD]  From 1972 until 1974 he was the mayor of the Bristol Bay Borough. [SBD]  Then, in 1974, he was elected governor of Alaska. [SBD]  He oversaw the creation of the Alaska Permanent Fund in 1976, which, since the early 1980s, has paid annual dividends to Alaska residents. [SBD]  He advocated for fiscal responsibility. [SBD]  When his tenure as governor was over, he continued to be active in public life. [SBD]  He advocated for environmentally and fiscally responsible government and individual civic responsibility. [SBD]  From 1985 to 1992 he hosted a television series called Jay Hammond’s Alaska. [SBD]  He wrote three autobiographies.

title: North American Christian Convention
paragraph: The North American Christian Convention is an annual summer convention supported by churches, colleges, institutions, and missions programs associated with the Christian churches and churches of Christ, mainly across the United States, but also in other parts of the world. [SBD]  First started in 1927, it has gradually grown over the years in both attendance and location. [SBD]  The NACC was held annually after 1927 until the end of that decade; the deprivations brought about by the Great Depression and the dislocations caused by World War II contributed to its being held only three times in the 1930s and four times in the 1940s; since 1950 it has again become an annual event. [SBD]  Ministers from churches across the United States have come and spoken at the event, as well as other well-known speakers and authors of the Christian community. [SBD]  The NACC Mission statement is "the connecting place providing ideas, inspiration, and identity to New Testament Christian Churches and their leaders." [SBD]  Philosophically this organization gives all their credit to Jesus Christ.

title: Joseph B. Foraker
paragraph: Joseph Benson Foraker (July 5, 1846 – May 10, 1917) was the 37th Governor of Ohio from 1886 to 1890 and a Republican United States Senator from 1897 until 1909.

title: Benjamin Cleveland
paragraph: Benjamin Cleveland (May 28, 1738 – October 1806) was an American pioneer and soldier in North Carolina. [SBD]  He is best remembered for his service as a colonel in the North Carolina militia during the War of Independence, and in particular for his role in the American victory at the Battle of Kings Mountain .

title: George Hoadly
paragraph: George Hoadly (July 31, 1826August 26, 1902) was a Democratic politician. [SBD]  He served as the 36th Governor of Ohio.

title: Dara Ó Briain
paragraph: Dara Ó Briain ( ; ] ; born 4 February 1972) is an Irish comedian and television presenter in the United Kingdom and Ireland. [SBD]  He is noted for hosting topical panel shows such as "Mock the Week", "The Panel", and "". [SBD]  His TV work also includes starring in and writing of television comedy and documentary series. [SBD]  Ó Briain has also been a newspaper columnist, with pieces published in national papers in both Britain and Ireland.

title: Huang Chengyan
paragraph: Huang Chengyan (birth and death dates unknown) was a scholar who lived in the Eastern Han dynasty. [SBD]  He was from Miannan (沔南), Jing Province, which is around present-day Honghu, Jingzhou, Hubei. [SBD]  He was known for being carefree and open-minded.

title: Belgium (disambiguation)
paragraph: Belgium is a country in Europe.

title: Yakovlev Yak-38
paragraph: The Yakovlev Yak-38 (Russian: Яковлев Як-38 ; NATO reporting name: "Forger") was the Soviet Naval Aviation's only operational VTOL strike fighter aircraft, in addition to being its first operational carrier-based fixed-wing aircraft. [SBD]  It was developed specifically for, and served almost exclusively, on the Kiev-class aircraft carriers.

title: Angiodysplasia
paragraph: In medicine (gastroenterology), angiodysplasia is a small vascular malformation of the gut. [SBD]  It is a common cause of otherwise unexplained gastrointestinal bleeding and anemia. [SBD]  Lesions are often multiple, and frequently involve the cecum or ascending colon, although they can occur at other places. [SBD]  Treatment may be with colonoscopic interventions, angiography and embolization, medication, or occasionally surgery.

title: Cantrip
paragraph: Cantrip is a word of Scots origin to mean a magical spell of any kind, or one which reads the same forwards and backwards. [SBD]  It can also be a witch's trick, or a sham. [SBD]  It is possibly derived from the Gaelic "canntaireachd", a piper's mnemonic chant.

title: Polaron
paragraph: A polaron is a quasiparticle used in condensed matter physics to understand the interactions between electrons and atoms in a solid material. [SBD]  The polaron concept was first proposed by Lev Landau in 1933 to describe an electron moving in a dielectric crystal where the atoms move from their equilibrium positions to effectively screen the charge of an electron, known as a phonon cloud. [SBD]  This lowers the electron mobility and increases the electron's effective mass.

title: Platform shoe
paragraph: Platform shoes are shoes, boots, or sandals with an obvious thick sole, usually in the range of 3 - . [SBD]  Platform shoes may also be high heels, in which case the heel is raised significantly higher than the ball of the foot. [SBD]  Extreme heights, of both the sole and heel, can be found in fetish footwear such as ballet boots, where the sole may be up to 20 cm high, and the heels up to 40 cm and more. [SBD]  The sole of a platform shoe can have a continuous uniform thickness, have a wedge, a separate block or a stiletto heel. [SBD]  Apart from the extreme forms of fetish shoes (which are first and foremost not intended for walking in), walking in platform shoes can be cumbersome and clumsy. [SBD]  Raising the ankle increases the risk of a sprained ankle.

title: Matt Barlow
paragraph: Matthew Barlow (born March 10, 1970 in Biloxi, Mississippi, US) is an American heavy metal singer and police officer. [SBD]  He is the lead singer for Ashes of Ares and former of Iced Earth and Pyramaze. [SBD]  He is Jon Schaffer's brother-in-law.

title: Edwards Pierrepont
paragraph: Edwards Pierrepont (March 4, 1817 – March 6, 1892) was a popular American attorney, reformer, jurist, traveler, New York U.S. Attorney, U.S. Attorney General, U.S. Minister to England, and orator. [SBD]  Having graduated from Yale in 1837, Pierrepont studied law and was admitted to the bar in 1840. [SBD]  During the American Civil War, Pierrepont was a Democrat, although he supported President Abraham Lincoln. [SBD]  Pierrepont initially supported President Andrew Johnson's conservative Reconstruction efforts having opposed the Radical Republicans. [SBD]  In both 1868 and 1872, Pierrepont supported Ulysses S. Grant for President. [SBD]  For his support, President Grant appointed Pierrepont United States Attorney in 1869. [SBD]  In 1871, Pierrepont gained the reputation as a solid reformer, having joined New York's "Committee of Seventy" that shut down Boss Tweed's corrupt Tammany Hall. [SBD]  In 1872, Pierrepont modified his views on Reconstruction and stated that African American freedman's rights needed to be protected.

title: Ghost Rider
paragraph: Ghost Rider is the name of many fictional supernatural antiheroes appearing in American comic books published by Marvel Comics. [SBD]  Marvel had previously used the name for a Western character whose name was later changed to Phantom Rider.

title: Steinefrenz
paragraph: Steinefrenz is an "Ortsgemeinde" – a community belonging to a "Verbandsgemeinde" – in the Westerwaldkreis in Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany.

title: Julia Hartley-Brewer
paragraph: Julia Hartley-Brewer (born 2 May 1968) is an English broadcaster and columnist. [SBD]  She has been presenting the weekday morning radio show from 10:00 am to 1:00 pm on talk radio station talkRADIO since 21 March 2016.

title: Sierpiński curve
paragraph: Sierpiński curves are a recursively defined sequence of continuous closed plane fractal curves discovered by Wacław Sierpiński, which in the limit formula_1 completely fill the unit square: thus their limit curve, also called the Sierpiński curve, is an example of a space-filling curve.

title: Introduction to Objectivist Epistemology
paragraph: Introduction to Objectivist Epistemology is a work of philosophy by Ayn Rand (with an additional article by Leonard Peikoff). [SBD]  Rand considered it her most important philosophical writing. [SBD]  First published in installments in Rand's Journal, The Objectivist, July 1966 through its February 1967, the work's opening chapters present Rand's proposed solution to the historic problem of universals. [SBD]  Chapters 3 through 8 present the extension of the theory to complex cases and outline how the theory applies to other issues in the theory of knowledge.

title: Software verification and validation
paragraph: In software project management, software testing, and software engineering, verification and validation (V&V) is the process of checking that a software system meets specifications and that it fulfills its intended purpose. [SBD]  It may also be referred to as software quality control. [SBD]  It is normally the responsibility of software testers as part of the software development lifecycle. [SBD]  In simple terms, software verification is: "Assuming we should build X, does our software achieve its goals without any bugs or gaps?" [SBD]  On the other hand, software validation is: "Was X what we should have built? [SBD]  Does X meet the high level requirements?"

title: Rømer scale
paragraph: The Rømer scale (] ; also Roemer) is a temperature scale named after the Danish astronomer Ole Christensen Rømer, who proposed it in 1701. [SBD]  It is based on the freezing point of pure water being 7.5 degrees and the boiling point of water as 60 degrees.

title: Opium (KMFDM album)
paragraph: Opium is the debut album by KMFDM released in 1984. [SBD]  There were only a handful of cassette copies made. [SBD]  The album was re-released in 2002 by KMFDM Records. [SBD]  It was originally recorded in Hamburg, Germany.

title: Biomedical Primate Research Centre
paragraph: The Biomedical Primate Research Centre (BPRC) is Europe's largest primate animal testing research centre. [SBD]  It is a scientific research institute that performs research that contributes to the identification and development of new medicines against deadly diseases. [SBD]  It is located in Rijswijk, (Zuid-Holland) and employs about 110 people.

title: Thrill Kill
