paragraph: Thrill Kill is an unreleased 1998 fighting video game for the Sony PlayStation. [SBD]  While the technical feat of allowing four players to fight simultaneously in the same room was to be a major selling point, this was overshadowed by the controversy surrounding the game's depictions of violence and sexual content. [SBD]  Examples of this content include BDSM and fetishistic costumes and acts, limb dismemberment, and violent special moves with suggestive names such as "Bitch Slap" and "Swallow This".

title: East Humboldt Range
paragraph: The East Humboldt Range is a mountain range in Elko County, Nevada, United States. [SBD]  It is located along the eastern edge of the upper watershed of the Humboldt River, which flows to the southwest from its source just north of the range. [SBD]  The range reaches a maximum elevation of 11306 ft atop Hole in the Mountain Peak. [SBD]  Most of the range is included within the Ruby Mountains Ranger District of the Humboldt-Toiyabe National Forest. [SBD]  In 1989, the United States Congress passed the Nevada Wilderness Protection Act establishing over 36000 acre of the range as the East Humboldt Wilderness. [SBD]  The range was named by the explorer John C. Frémont for the German naturalist Alexander von Humboldt.

title: Syntactic methods
paragraph: In software engineering, syntactic methods are techniques for developing correct software programs. [SBD]  The techniques attempt to detect, and thus prevent, certain kinds of defects (bugs) by examining the structure of the code being produced at its syntactic rather than semantic level.

title: Hitman (DC Comics)
paragraph: Hitman (Tommy Monaghan) is a fictional character, a superpowered hitman in the DC Comics Universe. [SBD]  The character was created by Garth Ennis and John McCrea and first appeared in "The Demon Annual" #2 and then received his own series by Ennis and McCrea lasting 61 issues.

title: Hugh Fearnley-Whittingstall
paragraph: Hugh Christopher Edmund Fearnley-Whittingstall (born 14 January 1965) is an English celebrity chef, television personality, journalist, food writer and campaigner on food and environmental issues, known for his back-to-basics philosophy.

title: Star number
paragraph: A star number is a centered figurate number that represents a centered hexagram (six-pointed star), such as the one that Chinese checkers is played on.

title: Arc System Works
paragraph: Arc System Works Co., Ltd. (株式会社アークシステムワークス , Kabushiki gaisha Āku Shisutemu Wākusu ) is a video game developer and publisher based in Yokohama, Japan. [SBD]  Founded by Minoru Kidooka in 1988, Arc System Works is best known for its arcade 2D fighting game franchises, "Guilty Gear" and "BlazBlue".

title: Ukrainian Orthodox Church of Canada
paragraph: The Ukrainian Orthodox Church of Canada (UOCC) is an Eastern Orthodox Church in Canada, primarily consisting of Orthodox Ukrainian Canadians. Its former name was the Ukrainian Greek Orthodox Church of Canada (UGOCC). [SBD]  The Church, currently a Metropolis of the Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople, is part of the wider Eastern Orthodox communion, however was created independently in 1918.

title: MGM Grand Las Vegas
paragraph: The MGM Grand Las Vegas (formerly Marina and MGM-Marina) is a hotel and casino located on the Las Vegas Strip in Paradise, Nevada. [SBD]  The MGM Grand is the largest single hotel in the United States with 5,124 rooms. [SBD]  It is also the third-largest hotel complex in the world by number of rooms and second-largest hotel resort complex in the United States behind the combined The Venetian and The Palazzo. [SBD]  When it opened in 1993, the MGM Grand was the largest hotel complex in the world.

title: Blue Monday (New Order song)
paragraph: "Blue Monday" is a song by the English rock/dance band New Order. [SBD]  It was released as a 12-inch single on 7 March 1983 through Factory Records and later remade by the band in 1988 and 1995. [SBD]  The song has been widely remixed and covered since its original release, and became a popular anthem in the dance club scene. [SBD]  It is the best-selling 12" single of all time. [SBD]  The song has been widely acclaimed and according to Acclaimed Music, the song is the 33rd most acclaimed song of all time.

title: New York-New York Hotel and Casino
paragraph: New York-New York Hotel & Casino is a hotel and casino located on the Las Vegas Strip at 3790 Las Vegas Boulevard South, in Paradise, Nevada. [SBD]  It is owned and operated by MGM Resorts International.

title: Shayna Fox
paragraph: Shayna Bracha Fox (born April 21, 1984) is a former American voice actress, the voice of Regina "Reggie" Rocket on Nickelodeon's animated series, "Rocket Power." [SBD]  She is also credited as the voice of Savannah on "All Grown Up! [SBD] ."

title: Index of geography articles
paragraph: Geography is the study of the world and its features and of the distribution of life on the earth, including human life and the effects of human activity. [SBD]  Geography research addresses both the questions of "where", as well as "why", geographical phenomena occur. [SBD]  Geography is a diverse field that seeks to understand the world and all of its human and natural complexities—not merely where objects are, but how they came to be, and how they have changed since then.

title: Portuguese personal pronouns
paragraph: The Portuguese personal pronouns and possessives display a higher degree of inflection than other parts of speech. [SBD]  Personal pronouns have distinct forms according to whether they stand for a subject (nominative), a direct object (accusative), an indirect object (dative), or a reflexive object. [SBD]  Several pronouns further have special forms used after prepositions.

title: List of places named for Richard Montgomery
paragraph: This is a list of places named for Richard Montgomery, a major general of the Continental Army killed in the 1775 Battle of Quebec.

title: Flash Comics
paragraph: Flash Comics was an anthology comic book published by All-American Publications and later National Periodicals (DC Comics). [SBD]  The title had 104 issues published from January 1940 to February 1949. [SBD]  Although the name of the comic book was "Flash Comics", the Flash was only one of many different series featured in the magazine.

title: Mandalay Resort Group
paragraph: Mandalay Resort Group (formerly Circus Circus Enterprises) was a hotel-casino operator based in Paradise, Nevada. [SBD]  Its major properties included Mandalay Bay, Luxor, Excalibur and Circus Circus, as well as half of the Monte Carlo. [SBD]  In terms of market capitalization, it was one of the largest casino operators in the world. [SBD]  Its stock traded on the New York Stock Exchange with the ticker symbol "CIR" and "MBG".

title: Columbia Basin
paragraph: The Columbia Basin is the drainage basin of the Columbia River in the Pacific Northwest region of North America. [SBD]  It covers 668000 km2 . [SBD]  In common usage, the term often refers to a smaller area, generally the portion of the drainage basin that lies within eastern Washington.

title: Gens du pays
paragraph: "Gens du pays" has been called the unofficial national anthem of Quebec. [SBD]  Written by poet, songwriter, and avowed Quebec nationalist Gilles Vigneault (with music co-written by Gaston Rochon), it was first performed by Vigneault on June 24, 1975 during a concert on Montreal's Mount Royal at that year's Fête nationale du Québec ceremony. [SBD]  It quickly became a folk classic, and it has been played frequently at Fête nationale ceremonies since then. [SBD]  The chorus is by far the most famous part of the song: "Gens du pays, c'est votre tour / De vous laisser parler d'amour", which, translated, says, "Folks of the land, it is your turn to let yourselves be lovingly spoken to."

title: Framheim
paragraph: Framheim was the name of explorer Roald Amundsen's base at the Bay of Whales on the Ross Ice Shelf in Antarctica during his quest for the South Pole. [SBD]  It was used between January 1911 and February 1912.

title: Hawkworld
paragraph: Hawkworld is a comic book series published by American company DC Comics from 1989 to 1993. [SBD]  The initial story line was published as a three-issue mini-series and then, based on the high sales and interest level generated by this limited series, launched as an ongoing monthly book. [SBD]  Katar Hol and Shayera Thal were rebooted in the prestige format limited series.

title: Kitchen Cabinet
paragraph: The Kitchen Cabinet was a term used by political opponents of President of the United States Andrew Jackson to describe his ginger group, the collection of unofficial advisers he consulted in parallel to the United States Cabinet (the "parlor cabinet") following his purge of the cabinet at the end of the Eaton affair and his break with Vice President John C. Calhoun in 1831.

title: Frederick Wills (Guyana)
paragraph: Frederick "Fred" Rudolph Wills (died 1992) was the Foreign Affairs Minister of Guyana in the 1970s He was a renowned statesman, lawyer, cricket expert and intellectual. [SBD]  Wills is cited for his intellectual and academic genius by oral stories from his fellow-Guyanese and globally.

title: Olav Bjaaland
paragraph: Olav Bjaaland (5 March 1873 – 8 June 1961) was a Norwegian ski champion and polar explorers. [SBD]  In 1911, he was one of the first five men to reach the South Pole as part of Amundsen's South Pole expedition.

title: Subject (music)
paragraph: In music, a subject is the material, usually a recognizable melody, upon which part or all of a composition is based. [SBD]  In forms other than the fugue this may be known as the theme.

title: Civic Forum
paragraph: The Civic Forum (Czech: "Občanské fórum", OF) was a political movement in the Czech part of Czechoslovakia, established during the Velvet Revolution in 1989. [SBD]  The corresponding movement in Slovakia was called Public Against Violence (Slovak: "Verejnosť proti násiliu" - VPN).

title: Theme (narrative)
paragraph: In contemporary literary studies, a theme is the central topic a text treats. [SBD]  Themes can be divided into two categories: a work's "thematic concept" is what readers "think the work is about" and its "thematic statement" being "what the work says about the subject".

title: Spanish web
paragraph: The Spanish web is an aerial circus skill, similar in appearance and style to corde lisse. [SBD]  The name refers to both the apparatus and the performance.

title: Man-Bat
paragraph: Man-Bat (Robert Kirkland "Kirk" Langstrom) is a fictional character, a supervillain appearing in American comic books published by DC Comics, commonly as an adversary of the superhero Batman. [SBD]  Man-Bat was created by Frank Robbins and Neal Adams in collaboration with editor Julius Schwartz, and the character debuted in "Detective Comics" #400 (June 1970).

title: Rainbow Bridge (Niagara Falls)
paragraph: The Niagara Falls International Rainbow Bridge, commonly known as the Rainbow Bridge, is an arch bridge across the Niagara River gorge, and is a world-famous tourist site. [SBD]  It connects the cities of Niagara Falls, New York, United States (to the east), and Niagara Falls, Ontario, Canada (west).

title: Rainbow Bridge (Tokyo)
paragraph: The Rainbow Bridge (レインボーブリッジ , Reinbō Burijji ) is a suspension bridge crossing northern Tokyo Bay between Shibaura Pier and the Odaiba waterfront development in Minato, Tokyo, Japan.

title: Miloš Jakeš
paragraph: Miloš Jakeš (born August 12, 1922) is a retired Czech communist politician. [SBD]  He was General Secretary of the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia from 1987 until 1989. [SBD]  He resigned from his position in late November 1989, amid the Velvet Revolution.

title: Alan White (Yes drummer)
paragraph: Alan White (born 14 June 1949) is an English drummer and songwriter best known for his tenure in the progressive rock band Yes, which he joined in 1972. [SBD]  Born and raised in County Durham, White took up piano and drum lessons as a youngster. [SBD]  In 1969, he joined the Plastic Ono Band after John Lennon invited him to play at the Toronto Rock and Roll Revival festival. [SBD]  White went on to play on other recordings from artists such as George Harrison, Ginger Baker's Air Force, and Terry Reid, including "Imagine" by Lennon.

title: Cabot Rea
paragraph: Cabot Rea is a former American reporter and television news anchorman. [SBD]  He was the evening and night co-anchorman for WCMH, the NBC affiliate in Columbus, Ohio.

title: Ave Maris Stella
paragraph: Ave Maris Stella (Latin, "Hail Star of the Sea") is a plainsong Vespers hymn to Mary from about the eighth century. [SBD]  It was especially popular in the Middle Ages and has been used by many composers as the basis of other compositions.

title: Judea Pearl
paragraph: Judea Pearl (born September 4, 1936) is an Israeli-American computer scientist and philosopher, best known for championing the probabilistic approach to artificial intelligence and the development of Bayesian networks (see the article on belief propagation). [SBD]  He is also credited for developing a theory of causal and counterfactual inference based on structural models (see article on causality). [SBD]  He is the 2011 winner of the ACM Turing Award, the highest distinction in computer science, "for fundamental contributions to artificial intelligence through the development of a calculus for probabilistic and causal reasoning".

title: Pascal's theorem
paragraph: In projective geometry, Pascal's theorem (also known as the hexagrammum mysticum theorem) states that if six arbitrary points are chosen on a conic (i.e., ellipse, parabola or hyperbola) and joined by line segments in any order to form a hexagon, then the three pairs of opposite sides of the hexagon (extended if necessary) meet in three points which lie on a straight line, called the Pascal line of the hexagon.

title: Maximilian Hell
paragraph: Maximilian Hell (Hungarian: "Hell Miksa" ) (May 15, 1720 – April 14, 1792) was a Hungarian astronomer and an ordained Jesuit priest from the Kingdom of Hungary.

title: Mudchute DLR station
paragraph: Mudchute is a Docklands Light Railway (DLR) station in Millwall next to Mudchute in Greater London, England. [SBD]  The station is situated on the Isle of Dogs within the East End of London which is on the Lewisham branch of the Docklands Light Railway and is in Travelcard Zone 2. [SBD]  The original station was on the route of the Millwall Extension Railway which was an old Victorian railway line that had been disused for many years. [SBD]  The original elevated station opened on 31 August 1987 and it was the last station before the terminus at Island Gardens. [SBD]  When the line was extended under the River Thames to Lewisham the station was rebuilt in a shallow cutting close to the tunnel entrance. [SBD]  The rebuilt station opened on 20 November 1999. [SBD]  In April 2008 work started on replacing the siding formed by the old route into a third platform for reversing trains and adding a canopy over the station. [SBD]  By October 2009 these works were complete.

title: Joseph Johann von Littrow
paragraph: Joseph Johann von Littrow (13 March 1781, Horšovský Týn (German: "Bischofteinitz" ) – 30 November 1840, Vienna) was an Austrian astronomer. [SBD]  In 1837, he was ennobled with the title Joseph Johann Edler von Littrow. [SBD]  He was the father of Karl Ludwig Edler von Littrow and the mentor of the mathematician Nikolai Brashman. [SBD]  His work took him to Russia for a time, which is where his son who succeeded him was born.

title: Ode to Newfoundland
paragraph: "Ode to Newfoundland" is the official provincial anthem of Newfoundland and Labrador, Canada. [SBD]  It was composed by Governor Sir Cavendish Boyle in 1902 as a four-verse poem titled "Newfoundland". [SBD]  On December 22, 1902 it was sung by Frances Daisy Foster at the Casino Theatre of St. John's during the closing of the play "Mamzelle". [SBD]  The original score was set to the music of E. R. Krippner, a German bandmaster living in St. John's but Boyle desired a more dignified score. [SBD]  It was then set to the music of British composer Sir Hubert Parry, a personal friend of Boyle, who composed two settings. [SBD]  On May 20, 1904 it was chosen as Newfoundland's official national anthem (national being understood as a self-governing Dominion of the British Empire on par with Canada, South Africa, Australia and other former British colonies). [SBD]  This distinction was dropped when Newfoundland joined the Canadian Confederation in 1949. [SBD]  Three decades later, in 1980, the province re-adopted the song as an official provincial anthem, the first province to do so. [SBD]  The "Ode to Newfoundland" is still sung at public events to this day as a tradition. [SBD]  Traditionally only the first and last verse is sung.

title: Warlord (comics)
paragraph: The Warlord is a sword and sorcery character appearing in comic books published by American company DC Comics. [SBD]  Created by writer-artist Mike Grell, he debuted in "1st Issue Special" #8 (Nov. 1975). [SBD]  The comic's protagonist, Travis Morgan, obtains the name "Warlord" as he fights for the freedom of the people of Skartaris.

title: Captain Tsubasa
paragraph: Captain Tsubasa (Japanese: キャプテン翼 , Hepburn: Kyaputen Tsubasa ) , is a popular long-running Japanese manga, animation and video game series, originally created by Yōichi Takahashi in 1981.

title: Northeast Texas
paragraph: Northeast Texas is a region in the northeast corner of the U.S. state of Texas. [SBD]  It is geographically centered on two metropolitan areas strung along Interstate 20: Tyler in the west and Longview/Marshall to the east. [SBD]  Mount Pleasant, Sulphur Springs, Paris and Texarkana in the north primarily along Interstate 30, Jacksonville and Palestine to the south are also major cities within the region. [SBD]  Most of Northeast Texas is included in the inter-state region of the Arklatex.

title: Firearms (video game)
paragraph: Firearms (commonly abbreviated as FA) is a first-person shooter video game for "Half-Life" which originated from a "Quake" modification. [SBD]  Initially developed in 1998, "Firearms" was created as a quasi-realistic team-based FPS. [SBD]  The mod's main feature is the large amount of playable weapons in the game.

title: Targa Newfoundland
paragraph: Targa Newfoundland is a tarmac-based rally race in Newfoundland. [SBD]  It is an annual event covering 2200 km over a seven-day period in September of each year on eastern and central parts of Newfoundland.

title: Complex question
paragraph: A complex question, trick question, multiple question or plurium interrogationum (Latin, "of many questions") is a question that has a presupposition that is complex. [SBD]  The presupposition is a proposition that is presumed to be acceptable to the respondent when the question is asked. [SBD]  The respondent becomes committed to this proposition when he gives any direct answer. [SBD]  The presupposition is called "complex" because it is a conjunctive proposition, a disjunctive proposition, or a conditional proposition. [SBD]  It could also be another type of proposition that contains some logical connective in a way that makes it have several parts that are component propositions.

title: University of Cambridge Philharmonic Orchestra
paragraph: The University of Cambridge Philharmonic Orchestra (UCPO) is a student-run orchestra in Cambridge, England.

title: Warhammer 40,000: Fire Warrior
paragraph: Warhammer 40,000: Fire Warrior is a "Warhammer 40,000" video game available for the PlayStation 2, and Microsoft Windows. [SBD]  It was developed by Kuju Entertainment and released in October 2003.

title: Charles Foster (Ohio politician)
paragraph: Charles William Foster, Jr. (April 12, 1828January 9, 1904) was a U.S. Republican politician from Ohio. [SBD]  Foster was the 35th Governor of Ohio, and later went on to serve as Secretary of the Treasury under Benjamin Harrison.

title: Junior World Rally Championship
paragraph: The FIA Junior World Rally Championship (also known as the Junior WRC) is a complementary series to the FIA World Rally Championship (WRC) and is specifically aimed at offering young drivers a chance to gain experience and notoriety at an affordable cost. [SBD]  The category has been a stepping stone in the career of many current WRC drivers including Sébastien Loeb, Dani Sordo, Sébastien Ogier, Jari-Matti Latvala and Thierry Neuville.

title: California State University Maritime Academy
paragraph: The California State University Maritime Academy (Cal Maritime or CSU Maritime Academy), formerly known as the California Maritime Academy, is one of 23 campuses in the California State University system and is one of seven degree-granting maritime academies in the United States and the only one on the West Coast. [SBD]  It is located in Vallejo, California. [SBD]  The university offers six different Bachelor's degrees, and one Master's degree, but no Doctoral degrees.

title: Richard M. Bishop
paragraph: Richard Bishop (November 4, 1812 – March 2, 1893), also known as Richard M. Bishop and Papa Richard, was an American politician from the U.S. state of Ohio. [SBD]  Bishop served as the 34th Governor of Ohio.

title: California State University, Bakersfield
paragraph: California State University, Bakersfield (often abbreviated CSUB or shortened to CSU Bakersfield) is a public university located in Bakersfield, California, United States, and was founded in 1965. [SBD]  CSUB opened in 1970 on a 375 acre campus, becoming the 19th school in the 23-campus California State University system. [SBD]  The university offers 91 different Bachelor's degrees, 20 types of Master's degrees, and 12 teaching credentials. [SBD]  The university does not confer Doctoral degrees.

title: Josh Gracin
paragraph: Joshua Mario Gracin (born October 18, 1980) is an American country music singer. [SBD]  A former member of the United States Marine Corps, he first gained public attention as the fourth-place finalist on the second season of the Fox Network talent competition "American Idol".

title: California State University Channel Islands
paragraph: California State University Channel Islands (CSUCI, CSU Channel Islands, known informally as CI) is a four-year public comprehensive university located outside Camarillo, California in Ventura County. [SBD]  CI opened in 2002, as the 23rd campus in the California State University system, succeeding the Ventura County branch campus of CSU Northridge. [SBD]  CI is located midway between Santa Barbara and Los Angeles in Camarillo, at the intersection of the Oxnard Plain and northern most edge of the Santa Monica Mountain range. [SBD]  The Channel Islands are nearby where the university operates a scientific research station on Santa Rosa Island. [SBD]  CI faculty include one of the U.S.'s top economic forecasters, Sung Won Sohn; artist Jack Reilly; and biologist Sean Anderson.

title: California State University, Dominguez Hills
paragraph: California State University, Dominguez Hills (also known as CSUDH, Dominguez Hills, or Cal State Dominguez Hills) is a public university within the 23-school California State University (CSU) system. [SBD]  It is located in the city of Carson, California in the South Bay region of Los Angeles County and was founded in 1960.

title: Thomas L. Young
paragraph: Thomas Lowry Young (December 14, 1832July 20, 1888) was an American politician from the U.S. state of Ohio. [SBD]  Young, a Republican, served as the 33rd Governor of Ohio from March 2, 1877 to January 14, 1878.

title: California State University, Monterey Bay
paragraph: California State University, Monterey Bay (CSUMB) is a public university in the 23-campus California State University system, located in Marina and Seaside, in Monterey County, California. [SBD]  It is on the site of the former U.S. Army base Fort Ord in the northern Central Coast of California region, and is accredited by the Western Association of Schools and Colleges.

title: Terry O'Quinn
paragraph: Terrance Quinn (born July 15, 1952), known professionally as Terry O'Quinn, is an American actor. [SBD]  He played John Locke on the TV series "Lost", the title role in "The Stepfather" and "Stepfather II" and was cast in 1996 as Peter Watts in "Millennium", which ran for three seasons (1996–1999).

title: Maximilian Jenius
paragraph: Maximilian Jenius (マクシミリアン・ジーナス , Makushimirian Jīnasu ) is a fictional character in the science fiction television series "Macross", voiced by Shō Hayami. [SBD]  In the new English adaptation by ADV Films, he is voiced by Chris Patton.

title: California State University, Stanislaus
paragraph: California State University, Stanislaus (also known as Stanislaus State or simply Stan State and formerly known as CSU Stanislaus) is a campus in the 23-school California State University system which was established in 1957 in Turlock, California, United States. [SBD]  It is also the only campus in the CSU system to offer a bachelor's degree in cognitive studies. [SBD]  The university offers 133 Bachelor's degrees, 35 Master's degrees, two Doctoral degrees (Doctor of Education), and 14 teaching credentials.

title: One-loop Feynman diagram
paragraph: In physics, a one-loop Feynman diagram is a connected Feynman diagram with only one cycle (unicyclic). [SBD]  Such a diagram can be obtained from a connected tree diagram by taking two external lines of the same type and joining them together into an edge.

title: Overloading (chess)
paragraph: Overloading (also overworking) is a chess tactic in which a defensive piece is given an additional defensive assignment which it cannot complete without abandoning its original defensive assignment.

title: Maria Minna
paragraph: Maria Minna, PC, (born March 14, 1948) is a former Canadian politician who represented the Toronto riding of Beaches—East York in the House of Commons as a member of the Liberal Party from 1993 to 2011.

title: Devon Island
paragraph: Devon Island (Inuit: "Tatlurutit") is the largest uninhabited island on Earth. [SBD]  It is located in Baffin Bay, Qikiqtaaluk Region, Nunavut, Canada. [SBD]  It is one of the larger members of the Canadian Arctic Archipelago, the second-largest of the Queen Elizabeth Islands, Canada's sixth largest island, and the 27th-largest island in the world. [SBD]  It comprises 55247 km2 (slightly smaller than Croatia) of Precambrian gneiss and Paleozoic siltstones and shales. [SBD]  The highest point is the Devon Ice Cap at 1920 m which is part of the Arctic Cordillera. [SBD]  Devon Island contains several small mountain ranges, such as the Treuter Mountains, Haddington Range and the Cunningham Mountains.

title: Semiclassical physics
paragraph: Semiclassical physics, or simply semiclassical refers to a theory in which one part of a system is described quantum-mechanically whereas the other is treated classically. [SBD]  For example, external fields will be constant, or when changing will be classically described. [SBD]  In general, it incorporates a development in powers of Planck's constant, resulting in the classical physics of power 0, and the first nontrivial approximation to the power of (−1). [SBD]  In this case, there is a clear link between the quantum-mechanical system and the associated semi-classical and classical approximations, as it is similar in appearance to the transition from physical optics to geometric optics.

title: Bank Mandiri
paragraph: Bank Mandiri, headquartered in Jakarta, is the largest bank in Indonesia in term of assets, loans and deposits. [SBD]  Total assets as of Q3 2012 were IDR 588.4 trillion (or USD 59.8 billion). [SBD]  It also has Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR) of 16.08% (including market risk), Return on Asset (RoA) of 3.45%, and Return on Equity (RoE) of 22.18%. [SBD]  As of September 2012, Bank Mandiri is the first largest bank in Indonesia by total assets.

title: Edward Follansbee Noyes
paragraph: Edward Follansbee Noyes (October 3, 1832September 4, 1890) was a Republican politician from Ohio. [SBD]  Noyes served as the 30th Governor of Ohio.

title: West Humboldt Range
paragraph: The West Humboldt Range is a short mountain range in the western Great Basin in northwestern Nevada in the United States.

title: Richard Conte
paragraph: Richard Conte (born Nicholas Peter Conte; March 24, 1910 – April 15, 1975) was an American actor. [SBD]  He appeared in more than 100 films from the 1940s through 1970s, including "I'll Cry Tomorrow", "Ocean's 11", and "The Godfather".

title: Inherit
paragraph: Ps: When you inherit something , you inherit something from someone.

title: WKB approximation
paragraph: In mathematical physics, the WKB approximation or WKB method is a method for finding approximate solutions to linear differential equations with spatially varying coefficients. [SBD]  It is typically used for a semiclassical calculation in quantum mechanics in which the wavefunction is recast as an exponential function, semiclassically expanded, and then either the amplitude or the phase is taken to be slowly changing.

title: Remaster
paragraph: Remaster (also digital remastering and digitally remastered) refers to enhancing the quality of the sound or of the image, or both, of previously created recordings, either audiophonic, cinematic, or videographic.

title: Hari Kostov
paragraph: Hari Kostov (Macedonian: Хари Костов ) (born November 13, 1959 in s.Pishica Probištip) was the Prime Minister of Macedonia from May 2004 to November 2004. [SBD]  He was appointed to the position of Prime Minister by the parliament on May 31, 2004, two weeks after being nominated by President Branko Crvenkovski. [SBD]  Kostov was an economic advisor to the Macedonian government and the World Bank during the 1980s and 1990s. [SBD]  He was the interior minister in the previous government, which was led by Crvenkovski and lasted from 2002 until 2004, and ended when Crvenkovski was elected president. [SBD]  Kostov retained most officials from the Crvenkovski government.

title: John Hodiak
paragraph: John Hodiak (April 16, 1914 – October 19, 1955) was an American actor who worked in radio, stage and film.

title: D.R.I. (band)
paragraph: D.R.I. (abbreviation for Dirty Rotten Imbeciles) is an American crossover thrash band that formed in Houston, Texas in 1982. [SBD]  As of 2015, the band comprises two of its founding members, vocalist Kurt Brecht and guitarist Spike Cassidy, as well as drummer Walter "Monsta" Ryan and bassist Harald Oimoen.

title: Jacob Dolson Cox
paragraph: Jacob Dolson Cox, (Jr.) (October 27, 1828August 4, 1900) was a statesman, lawyer, Union Army general during the American Civil War, and later a Republican politician from Ohio. [SBD]  He served as the 28th Governor of Ohio and as United States Secretary of the Interior. [SBD]  As Governor of Ohio, Cox sided for a time with President Andrew Johnson's Reconstruction plan and was against African American suffrage in the South, though he supported it in Ohio. [SBD]  Seeing himself caught between Johnson and the Radical Republicans, Cox decided not to run for reelection. [SBD]  He stayed out of politics for a year, though both Sherman and Grant advocated that Cox replace Stanton as Secretary of War as a means of stemming the demands for Johnson's impeachment. [SBD]  But Johnson declined. [SBD]  When Ulysses S. Grant became President he nominated Cox Secretary of Interior and Cox immediately accepted. [SBD]  Secretary of Interior Cox implemented the first civil service reform in a federal government department, including examinations for most clerks. [SBD]  Grant initially supported Cox and civil service reform, creating America's first Civil Service Commission. [SBD]  However, Cox was opposed by Republican Party managers, who ultimately convinced Grant to cease civil service reforms. [SBD]  President Grant and Secretary Cox were at odds over the fraudulent McGarahan Claims and the Dominican Republic annexation treaty. [SBD]  Secretary Cox advocated a lasting, honest, and comprehensive Indian policy legislated by Congress after the Piegan Indian massacre. [SBD]  Cox resigned as Secretary of Interior having been unable to gain Grant's support over civil service reform. [SBD]  Although Cox was a reformer, Grant had believed Cox had overstepped his authority as Secretary of Interior and had undermined his authority as President. [SBD]  In 1872 Cox joined the Liberal Republicans in opposition to Grant's renomination. [SBD]  In 1876 Cox returned to politics and was elected to and served one term as United States Congressman of Ohio. [SBD]  Congressman Cox supported President Hayes's reform efforts, but his term as Congressman was unsuccessful at establishing permanent Civil Service reform. [SBD]  Cox retired and did not return to active politics, using his time to write several books on Civil War campaigns which remain today respected histories and memoirs.

title: Jason James Richter
paragraph: Jason James Richter (born January 29, 1980) is an American actor, most commonly known for his role in the "Free Willy" series as Jesse, the boy who befriends Willy.

title: Goldust
paragraph: Dustin Patrick Runnels (born April 11, 1969) is an American professional wrestler who is currently signed to WWE on the Raw brand under the ring name Goldust. [SBD]  He is the son of the late WWE Hall of Famer Dusty Rhodes and the half-brother of former WWE wrestler Cody Rhodes. [SBD]  Runnels' enigmatic, flamboyant, sexually ambiguous gimmick of "Goldust" has remained popular in WWF/E.

title: Road Dogg
paragraph: Brian Girard James (born May 20, 1969) is an American professional wrestler and former United States Marine, currently signed to the WWE as a producer.

title: Naval History and Heritage Command
paragraph: The Naval History and Heritage Command, formerly the Naval Historical Center, is an Echelon II command responsible for the preservation, analysis, and dissemination of U.S. naval history and heritage located at the historic Washington Navy Yard. [SBD]  The NHHC is composed of 42 facilities in 13 geographic locations including the Navy Department Library, 10 museums and 1 heritage center, USS "Constitution" repair facility and detachment, and historic ship ex-USS "Nautilus".

title: Jacques Rougeau
paragraph: Jacques Rougeau Jr. (born June 13, 1960) is a Canadian retired professional wrestler best known for his appearances in the 1980s and 1990s with the World Wrestling Federation. [SBD]  Rougeau began his career by wrestling under his real name, as part of a tag team with his brother Raymond Rougeau, with whom he is a former WWF Tag Team Champion (albeit unofficially). [SBD]  Later Rougeau began a singles career where he wrestled as The Mountie, winning the WWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship once. [SBD]  Later still, he formed the tag team The Quebecers with Pierre Ouellet, and won the WWF Tag Team Championship three more times.

title: Art world
paragraph: The art world comprises everyone involved in producing, commissioning, presenting, preserving, promoting, chronicling, criticizing, and selling fine art.

title: Matrix of ones
paragraph: In mathematics, a matrix of ones or all-ones matrix is a matrix over the real numbers where every element is equal to one. [SBD]  Examples of standard notation are given below:

title: Raymond Rougeau
paragraph: Raymond Rougeau (born February 18, 1955) is a Canadian television presenter,

title: List of rivers of Missouri
paragraph: List of rivers in Missouri (U.S. state).

title: Marcel Tabuteau
paragraph: Marcel Tabuteau (2 July 18874 January 1966) was a French-American oboist who is considered the founder of the American school of oboe playing.

title: William Regal
paragraph: Darren Kenneth Matthews (born 10 May 1968) is an English retired professional wrestler, color commentator and trainer. [SBD]  He is currently signed to WWE on the NXT brand under the ring name William Regal, acting as the brand's general manager. [SBD]  He is also known for his time in World Championship Wrestling (WCW) under the ring name Steven Regal. [SBD]  Having started his career on a rare surviving carnival booth in Britain, he moved on to wrestle for national-level promotions on the British wrestling circuit and on British television. [SBD]  He then progressed to touring around the world, in countries such as Germany and South Africa, before being called up to WCW in 1993.

title: Jeff Hardy
paragraph: Jeffrey Nero Hardy (born August 31, 1977) is an American professional wrestler, singer-songwriter, painter and musician currently signed to WWE on the Raw brand, where he is one-half of The Hardy Boyz tag team with his real-life brother, Matt. [SBD]  He is currently inactive due to a torn right rotator cuff, which will require surgery.

title: Regions of Senegal
paragraph: Senegal is subdivided into 14 regions (French: "régions", singular"région"), each of which is administered by a "Conseil Régional" (pl.: "Conseils Régionaux") elected by population weight at the arrondissement level.

title: Districts of Uganda
paragraph: Uganda is divided into 111 districts and one city (the capital city of Kampala), which are grouped into four administrative regions.

title: Davey Boy Smith
paragraph: David "Davey Boy" Smith (27 November 1962 – 18 May 2002) was a British professional wrestler. [SBD]  Born in Golborne, Lancashire, Smith is best known for his appearances in the United States with the World Wrestling Federation under his own name and under the ring name The British Bulldog.

title: Baptism (Lenny Kravitz album)
paragraph: Baptism is the seventh studio album by American rock musician Lenny Kravitz, released on May 17, 2004, by Virgin Records. [SBD]  It reached #14 on the "Billboard" 200 and #74 on the UK Albums Chart. [SBD]  As of March 2008, "Baptism" has sold 551,000 units in the U.S.

title: Emirates of the United Arab Emirates
paragraph: The United Arab Emirates consists of seven emirates (Arabic: إمارات‎ ‎ "ʾimārāt"; singular: إمارة "ʾimārah"):

title: The Coming Global Superstorm
paragraph: The Coming Global Superstorm (ISBN  ) is a 1999 book by Art Bell and Whitley Strieber, which warns that global warming might produce sudden and catastrophic climatic effects.

title: Korean hip hop
paragraph: Korean hip hop, also known as K-hip hop, is a subgenre of hip hop music from South Korea. [SBD]  It is widely considered to have originated in the late 1980s and early 1990s and has since become increasingly popular, both in Korea and abroad. [SBD]  In 2016, the Korea Foundation cited Korean hip hop as a new trend in the Korean Wave.

title: CityLine
paragraph: Cityline is a Canadian talk show and lifestyle television program hosted by Tracy Moore and produced by City Toronto. [SBD]  Each show has a theme that changes daily. [SBD]  These include "Around the House", "Family Day", "Home Day", and "Fashion Friday". [SBD]  It is Canada's longest running, daytime show specifically targeted to women.

title: Billy Gunn
paragraph: Monty Kip Sopp (born November 11, 1963), better known by his ring name Billy Gunn, is an American professional wrestler and former professional bull rider, currently working for New Japan Pro Wrestling (NJPW). [SBD]  Gunn is best known for his appearances in the World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment (WWF/E) from 1993 to 2004 and from 2012 to 2015. [SBD]  He also served as a coach on WWE's "Tough Enough", and was a trainer in its developmental branch, NXT. [SBD]  He is also known for his appearances with Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (TNA) from 2005 to 2009.

title: Governorates of Yemen
paragraph: Yemen is divided into twenty-one governorates ("muhafazah") and one municipality (amanah [أمانة]):

title: Choice
paragraph: Choice involves decision making. [SBD]  It can include judging the merits of multiple options and selecting one or more of them. [SBD]  One can make a choice between imagined options ("What would I do if...?") [SBD]  or between real options followed by the corresponding action. [SBD]  For example, a traveller might choose a route for a journey based on the preference of arriving at a given destination as soon as possible. [SBD]  The preferred (and therefore chosen) route can then follow from information such as the length of each of the possible routes, traffic conditions, etc. [SBD]  The arrival at a choice can include more complex motivators such as cognition, instinct, and feeling.

title: National Congress of Brazil
paragraph: The National Congress of Brazil (Portuguese: "Congresso Nacional do Brasil" ) is the legislative body of Brazil's federal government. [SBD]  Unlike the state Legislative Assemblies and Municipal Chambers, the Congress is bicameral, composed of the Federal Senate (the upper house) and the Chamber of Deputies (the lower house). [SBD]  The Congress meets annually in its Brasília seat from 2 February to 27 July and from 1 August to 22 December.

title: Provinces of Papua New Guinea
paragraph: The provinces of Papua New Guinea are the primary administrative divisions of the country. [SBD]  Provincial governments are branches of the national government – Papua New Guinea is not a federation of provinces. [SBD]  The country has 22 province-level divisions: 20 provinces, one autonomous region (Bougainville) and the National Capital District.

title: Torquay, Victoria
paragraph: Torquay is a seaside resort in Victoria, Australia, which faces Bass Strait, 21 km south of Geelong and is the gateway to the Great Ocean Road. [SBD]  It is bordered on the west by Spring Creek and its coastal features include Point Danger and Zeally Bay. [SBD]  At the 2011 Census, Torquay had a population of 10,142.

title: Ukrainian culture
paragraph: Ukrainian culture and customs of Ukraine and ethnic Ukrainians. [SBD]  Ukraine has a shared culture and history with neighboring nations, dating back to the 9th century and the Land of Rus. [SBD]  Mutual customs are shared among the cultures of Ukraine, Belarus, Ukrainian Cossacks and Russians. [SBD]  Ukrainian customs are heavily influenced by the Eastern Orthodox Church and traditions from Slavic mythology. [SBD]  The Soviet era unified the cultures of many unrelated nations with a common language.

title: Denny's
paragraph: Denny's (also known as Denny's Diner on some of the locations' signage) is a full-service pancake house/coffee shop/fast casual family restaurant chain. [SBD]  It operates over 1,600 restaurants in the United States (including Puerto Rico and Guam), Canada, Mexico, Dominican Republic, El Salvador, Curaçao, Costa Rica, Venezuela, Honduras, Japan (transliterated as "デニーズ" "Denīzu" ), New Zealand, Qatar, Philippines, and United Arab Emirates.

title: Philippe de Vitry
paragraph: Philippe de Vitry (31 October 1291 – 9 June 1361) was a French composer, music theorist and poet. [SBD]  He was an accomplished, innovative, and influential composer, and may also have been the author of the "Ars Nova" treatise. [SBD]  He was widely acknowledged as the greatest musician of his day, with Petrarch writing a glowing tribute, calling him: "... the keenest and most ardent seeker of truth, so great a philosopher of our age."

title: Femslash
paragraph: Femslash (also known as "f/f slash", "femmeslash", "altfic" and "saffic") is a subgenre of slash fan fiction which focuses on romantic and/or sexual relationships between female fictional characters. [SBD]  Typically, characters featured in femslash are heterosexual in the canon universe; however, similar fan fiction about lesbian characters is commonly labeled as femslash for convenience. [SBD]  The term is generally applied only to fanworks based on Western fandoms; the nearest anime/manga equivalents are more often called yuri and shōjo-ai fanfiction. [SBD]  "Saffic" is a portmanteau of Sapphic from the term Sapphic love and fiction. [SBD]  "Altfic" as a term for fanfiction about loving relationships between women was popularized by Xena fans.

title: Provinces of Panama
paragraph: Panama is divided into ten provinces (Spanish: "provincias" ). [SBD]  There are three provincial-level indigenous regions (Spanish: "comarcas indígenas", often foreshortened to "comarcas").

title: Michael D. Barnes
paragraph: Michael Darr Barnes (born September 3, 1943, in Washington, D.C.) represented the eighth district of Maryland in the United States House of Representatives from 1979 to 1987.

title: Congress of Paraguay
paragraph: Paraguay's bicameral Congress "(Congreso)" consists of a 45-member Senate and an

title: Governorates of Oman
paragraph: Oman is divided into eleven governorates ("muhafazah"), and has been since 28 October 2011:

title: U.S. Route 141
paragraph: US Highway 141 (US 141) is a north–south United States Numbered Highway in the states of Wisconsin and Michigan. [SBD]  The highway runs north-northwesterly from an interchange with Interstate 43 (I-43) in Bellevue, Wisconsin, near Green Bay, to a junction with US 41/M-28 near Covington, Michigan. [SBD]  In between, it follows city streets in Green Bay and has a concurrent section with US 41 in Wisconsin. [SBD]  North of Green Bay, US 141 is either a freeway or an expressway into rural northern Wisconsin before downgrading to an undivided highway. [SBD]  In Michigan, US 141 is an undivided highway that runs through rural woodlands. [SBD]  The highway has two segments in each state; after running through Wisconsin for about 103 mi , it crosses into Michigan for approximately another 8 mi . [SBD]  After that, it crosses back into Wisconsin for about 14+1/2 mi before crossing the state line one last time. [SBD]  The northernmost Michigan section is about 43+1/2 mi , making the overall length about 169 mi .

title: List of ancient Milesians
paragraph: The Milesians were the inhabitants of Miletus, an ancient Greek city in Anatolia, modern-day Turkey, near the coast of the Mediterranean Sea and at the mouth of the Meander River. [SBD]  Settlers from Crete moved to Miletus sometime in 16th century BC. [SBD]  By the 6th century BC, Miletus had become a maritime empire, and the Milesians spread out across Anatolia and even as far as the Crimea and Olbia, Ukraine, founding new colonies.

title: States and federal territories of Malaysia
paragraph: The states and federal territories of Malaysia are the principal administrative divisions of Malaysia. [SBD]  Malaysia is a federation comprising thirteen states ("Negeri") and three federal territories ("Wilayah Persekutuan").

title: Regions of Mali
paragraph: Since 2016, Mali has been divided into ten regions and one capital district. [SBD]  A reorganization of the country from eight to nineteen regions was passed into law in 2012, but of the new regions, only Taoudénit (formerly part of Tombouctou Region) and Ménaka (formerly Ménaka Cercle in Gao Region) have begun to be implemented. [SBD]  Each of the regions bears the name of its capital. [SBD]  The regions are divided into 56 cercles. [SBD]  The cercles and the capital district are divided into 703 communes.

title: Marquis Grissom
paragraph: Marquis Deon Grissom (born April 17, 1967) is an American former professional baseball center fielder. [SBD]  He played in Major League Baseball (MLB) for the Montreal Expos, Atlanta Braves, Cleveland Indians, Milwaukee Brewers, Los Angeles Dodgers, and San Francisco Giants between 1989 and 2005.

title: Regions of Ethiopia
paragraph: Ethiopia is a federal state subdivided into ethno-linguistically based regional states (plural: "kililoch"; singular: "kilil") and chartered cities (plural: "astedader akababiwach"; singular: "astedader akabibi"). [SBD]  This system of administrative regions replaced the provinces of Ethiopia in 1992 under the Transitional Government of Ethiopia and was formalised in 1995 when the current Constitution of Ethiopia came into force.

title: Pyrotechnic star
paragraph: Pyrotechnic stars are pellets or simply pieces of pyrotechnic composition which may contain metal powders, salts or other compounds that, when ignited, burn a certain color or make a certain spark effect. [SBD]  They are a part of all projectile-type fireworks. [SBD]  The most common is the aerial shell. [SBD]  When watching this firework, it will launch into the sky, burning a lifting charge. [SBD]  Once the shell has attained proper altitude, due to other mechanisms within the firework, it will ignite the stars.

title: Castleisland
paragraph: Castleisland (in Irish "Oileán Ciarraí", meaning "people of Ciar's island") is a town and commercial centre in County Kerry in south west Ireland. [SBD]  The town is renowned for the width of its main street. [SBD]  According to the 2011 Census, Castleisland has a population of 2,513.

title: Season (sports)
paragraph: In an organized sports league, a typical season is the portion of one year in which regulated games of the sport are in session. [SBD]  For example, in Major League Baseball, one season lasts approximately from April 1 to October 1; in football, it is generally from August until May (although in some countries, especially those in Northern Europe(except Denmark) and East Asia, the season starts in the spring and finishes in the autumn, due either to weather conditions encountered during the winter or to limit conflict with locally more popular football codes).

title: Signal strength in telecommunications
paragraph: In telecommunications, particularly in radio frequency, signal strength (also referred to as field strength) refers to the transmitter power output as received by a reference antenna at a distance from the transmitting antenna. [SBD]  High-powered transmissions, such as those used in broadcasting, are expressed in dB-millivolts per metre (dBmV/m). [SBD]  For very low-power systems, such as mobile phones, signal strength is usually expressed in dB-microvolts per metre (dBµV/m) or in decibels above a reference level of one milliwatt (dBm). [SBD]  In broadcasting terminology, 1 mV/m is 1000 µV/m or 60 dBµ (often written dBu).

title: Regions of Mauritania
paragraph: Mauritania is divided into 15 regions:

title: Vermont (automobile)
paragraph: The Vermont was the first automobile to cross the United States. [SBD]  It traveled from San Francisco, California to Manhattan, New York. [SBD]  It was a 1903 Winton. [SBD]  The crew was owner Horatio Nelson Jackson, mechanic Sewall K. Crocker and their dog Bud.

title: Grahm Junior College
paragraph: Grahm Junior College was a non-profit junior college located in Boston, Massachusetts. [SBD]  The school opened in 1951 (4) under the name Cambridge School, as part of a private chain of schools from New York City. [SBD]  The school was originally located at 18 Tremont street. [SBD]  Other branches were later based in Chicago and Philadelphia. [SBD]  The Cambridge School became accredited as a Junior College of business in 1964(1) The curriculum was later expanded to include radio and TV broadcasting. [SBD]  In 1967 the school was renamed Grahm Junior College, after its first director, Milton Grahm (4). [SBD]  The college radio station was known as WCSB, as was a closed-circuit television station.

title: M-185 (Michigan highway)
paragraph: M-185 is a state trunkline highway in the U.S. state of Michigan that circles Mackinac Island, a popular tourist destination on the Lake Huron side of the Straits of Mackinac, along the island's shoreline. [SBD]  A narrow paved road of 8.004 mi , it offers scenic views of the straits that divide the Upper and the Lower peninsulas of Michigan and Lakes Huron and Michigan. [SBD]  It has no connection to any other Michigan state trunkline highways—as it is on an island—and is accessible only by passenger ferry. [SBD]  The City of Mackinac Island, which shares jurisdiction over the island with the Mackinac Island State Park Commission (MISPC), calls the highway Main Street within the built-up area on the island's southeast quadrant, and Lake Shore Road elsewhere. [SBD]  M-185 passes by several important sites within Mackinac Island State Park, including Fort Mackinac, Arch Rock, British Landing, and Devil's Kitchen. [SBD]  Lake Shore Road carries the highway next to the Lake Huron shoreline, running between the water's edge and woodlands outside the downtown area.

title: Administrative divisions of Georgia (country)
paragraph: The subdivisions of Georgia are autonomous republics (Georgian: ავტონომიური რესპუბლიკა , "avtonomiuri respublika"), regions (მხარე, "mkhare"), and municipalities (მუნიციპალიტეტი, "munits'ipaliteti").

title: Toronto Roadrunners
paragraph: The Toronto Roadrunners were an ice hockey team in the American Hockey League. [SBD]  They played in Toronto, Ontario, Canada at the Ricoh Coliseum. [SBD]  In their only season the Roadrunners featured players such as Jani Rita, Brad Winchester, Jamie Wright and Steve Valiquette who helped them advance to the AHL playoffs where they lost the first round to the Cleveland Barons.

title: Counties of Hungary
paragraph: Hungary is subdivided administratively into 19 counties ("megyék", singular: "megye") and the capital city ("főváros") Budapest. [SBD]  The counties are further subdivided into 174 districts ("járások", singular: "járás"). [SBD]  The capital Budapest is subdivided into 23 districts ("kerületek", singular: "kerület").

title: Josh Duhamel
paragraph: Joshua David Duhamel ( ; born November 14, 1972) is an American actor and former fashion model. [SBD]  After various modeling work, he made his acting debut as Leo du Pres on the ABC daytime soap opera "All My Children" and later starred as Danny McCoy on NBC's "Las Vegas".

title: Vanessa Marcil
paragraph: Vanessa Marcil ( ; born Sally Vanessa Ortiz; October 15, 1968 is an American actress. [SBD]  She is best known for her television roles as Brenda Barrett on "General Hospital", Gina Kincaid on "Beverly Hills, 90210", and Sam Marquez on "Las Vegas".

title: Subdivisions of Kiribati
paragraph: In Kiribati, there are no more official subdivisions but it is possible to divide Kiribati geographically into three groups of islands:

title: Civic
paragraph: Civic is something being related to a city or municipality. [SBD]  It also can refer to multiple other things:

title: Mandala (political model)
paragraph: Maṇḍala is a Sanskrit word that means "circle". [SBD]  The mandala is a model for describing the patterns of diffuse political power distributed among Mueang or Kedatuan (principalities) in early Southeast Asian history, when local power was more important. [SBD]  The concept of a mandala counteracts modern tendencies to look for unified political power, i.e., the power of large kingdoms and nation states of later history — an inadvertent byproduct of 15th-century advances in map-making technologies. [SBD]  In the words of O. W. Wolters who further explored the idea in 1982:

title: Cairo Metro
paragraph: The Cairo Metro (Arabic: مترو أنفاق القاهرة‎ ‎ "Metro Anfāq al-Qāhirah", lit. [SBD]  "Cairo Tunnel Metro" or مترو الأنفاق   ] ) is the rapid transit system in Greater Cairo, Egypt. [SBD]  It was the first of only two full-fledged metro systems in Africa and only four in the Arab world. [SBD]  It was opened in 1987 as Line 1 from Helwan to Ramsis square with a length of 29 km . [SBD]  As of 2014, the Cairo Metro has 61 stations (mostly At-grade), of which 3 are transfer stations, with a total length of 77.9 km . [SBD]  The system consists of three operational lines numbered from 1 to 3. [SBD]  As of 2013, the metro carried nearly 4 million passengers per day.

title: Administrative divisions of Peru
paragraph: The administrative divisions of Peru have changed from time to time, since the nation gained independence from Spain in the early 19th century. [SBD]  The old territorial subdivisions have split or merged due to several reasons, the most common ones being the need for decentralization, and population increase, especially in Lima.

title: Committee for the Prevention of Destruction of Antiquities on the Temple Mount
paragraph: Committee for the Prevention of Destruction of Antiquities on the Temple Mount

title: John of Nikiû
paragraph: John of Nikiû (fl 680-690) was an Egyptian Coptic bishop of Nikiû (Pashati) in the Nile Delta and general administrator of the monasteries of Upper Egypt in 696. [SBD]  He is the author of a "Chronicle" extending from Adam to the end of the Muslim conquest of Egypt. [SBD]  John of Nikiû's "Chronicle" contains important historical details otherwise unknown.

title: Renée Estevez
paragraph: Renée Pilar Estevez (born April 2, 1967) is an American actress and writer.

title: Thai literature
paragraph: Thai literature is the literature of the Thai people, almost exclusively written in the Thai language.

title: Thomas Moulson
paragraph: Sir Thomas Moulson (sometimes spelled "Mowlson") (1582–1638), an alderman and member of the Grocers' Company, was a Sheriff of London in 1624 and Lord Mayor of London in 1634. [SBD]  He represented the City of London as a Member of Parliament in 1628.

title: Osage River
paragraph: The Osage River is a 276 mi tributary of the Missouri River in central Missouri in the United States. [SBD]  The Osage River is the 8th largest river in Missouri. [SBD]  The river drains a mostly rural area of 15300 sqmi . [SBD]  The watershed includes an area of east-central Kansas and a large portion of west-central and central Missouri where it drains northwest areas of the Ozark Plateau. [SBD]  The river flows generally easterly, then northeasterly for the final 80 mi where it joins the Missouri River. [SBD]  It is impounded in two major locations. [SBD]  Most of the river has been converted into a chain of two reservoirs, the Harry S. Truman Reservoir and the Lake of the Ozarks.

title: Freddie Hart
paragraph: Frederick Segrest (born December 21, 1926), known professionally as Freddie Hart, is an American country musician and songwriter best known for his chart-topping country song and lone pop hit "Easy Loving," which won the Country Music Association Song of the Year award in 1971 and 1972.

title: Buddha-nature
paragraph: Buddha-nature or Buddha Principle refers to several related terms, most notably "tathāgatagarbha" and "buddhadhātu". [SBD]  "Tathāgatagarbha" means "the womb" or "embryo" ("garbha") of the "thus-gone" ("tathagata"), or "containing a tathagata", while "buddhadhātu" literally means "Buddha-realm" or "Buddha-substrate". [SBD]  The terms refer to the notion that the luminous mind of the Buddhas is inherently present in every sentient being, and will shine forth when it is cleansed of the defilements, c.q. when the nature of mind is recognised for what it is.

title: Benjamin Grierson
paragraph: Benjamin Henry Grierson (July 8, 1826 – August 31, 1911) was a music teacher, then a career officer in the United States Army. [SBD]  He was a cavalry general in the volunteer Union Army during the Civil War and later led troops in the American Old West. [SBD]  He is most noted for an 1863 expedition through Confederate-held territory that severed enemy communication lines between Vicksburg, Mississippi and Confederate commanders in the Eastern Theater. [SBD]  After the war he organized and led the Buffalo Soldiers of the 10th Cavalry Regiment from 1866 to 1890.

title: Bumbershoot
paragraph: Bumbershoot is an annual international music and arts festival held in Seattle, Washington. [SBD]  One of North America's largest such festivals, it takes place every Labor Day weekend at the 74-acre (299,000 m²) Seattle Center, which was built for the 1962 World's Fair. [SBD]  Seattle Center includes both indoor theaters and outdoor stages. [SBD]  The name of the festival was taken from "", a colloquial term for umbrella, probably coined in the 19th century as a portmanteau of the words umbrella and parachute.

title: Dolly grip
paragraph: In cinematography, the dolly grip is a dedicated technician trained to operate the camera dolly. [SBD]  This technician places, levels, and moves the dolly track, then pushes and pulls the dolly and usually a camera operator and camera assistant as riders. [SBD]  If the dolly has a moveable vertical axis, such as a hydraulic arm, then the dolly grip also operates the "boom". [SBD]  If both axes are used simultaneously, this type of dolly shot is known as a compound move.

title: Supermarine Swift
paragraph: The Supermarine Swift was a British single-seat jet-propelled fighter aircraft that was operated by the Royal Air Force (RAF). [SBD]  It was developed and manufactured by Supermarine during the 1940s and 1950s. [SBD]  The Swift featured many of the new jet age innovations, such as a swept wing. [SBD]  On 26 September 1953, an Swift F.4 piloted by Commander Mike Lithgow broke the world absolute speed record, reaching a speed of 737.7 mph (1,187 km/h); thus, the Swift held the distinction of being the world's fastest aircraft.

title: Ann (Radcliffe) Mowlson
paragraph: Lady Anne Moulson (sometimes Ann and/or Mowlson), born Anne Radcliffe (sometimes Radclyffe) (1576-1661), was an early benefactor of the fledgling colonial Harvard College. [SBD]  She is remembered today in the name of Radcliffe College.

title: Apalit
paragraph: Apalit is a first class municipality in the province of Pampanga, on Luzon Island in the Philippines. [SBD]  According to the 2015 census, it has a population of 107,965 inhabitants.

title: Fleet Week
paragraph: Fleet Week is a United States Navy, United States Marine Corps, and United States Coast Guard tradition in which active military ships recently deployed in overseas operations dock in a variety of major cities for one week. [SBD]  Once the ships dock, the crews can enter the city and visit its tourist attractions. [SBD]  At certain hours, the public can take a guided tour of the ships. [SBD]  Often, Fleet Week is accompanied by military demonstrations and air shows such as those provided by the Blue Angels.

title: John C. Stennis Space Center
paragraph: The John C. Stennis Space Center (SSC) is a NASA rocket testing facility. [SBD]  It is located in Hancock County, Mississippi (United States), on the banks of the Pearl River at the Mississippi–Louisiana border. [SBD]  s of 2012 , it is NASA's largest rocket engine test facility. [SBD]  There are over 30 local, state, national, international, private, and public companies and agencies using SSC for their rocket testing facilities.

title: Josef von Sternberg
paragraph: Josef von Sternberg, (29 May 1894 – 22 December 1969) was an Austrian-American film director. [SBD]  His family emigrated permanently to the United States when he was fourteen, and he grew up in New York City. [SBD]  He started working at World Film Company in Fort Lee, New Jersey, where he was mentored by French director Emile Chautard.

title: Sunthorn Phu
paragraph: Phra Sunthonwohan (Thai: พระสุนทรโวหาร ), known as Sunthorn Phu (Thai: สุนทรภู่ , rtgs: "Sunthonphu" ,  ] ; 26 June 1786 – 1855), is Thailand's best-known royal poet. [SBD]  He wrote during the Rattanakosin period.

title: Hire purchase
paragraph: A hire purchase (British English; abbreviated HP) or an installment plan (American English) is an arrangement whereby a customer acquires an asset by paying an initial installment (e.g. 40% of the total) and repays the other part of the cost of the asset over a period of time or term for a contract, in which a purchaser agrees to pay for goods in parts or a percentage over a number of months. [SBD]  Other analogous practices are described as closed-end leasing or rent to own.

title: Juan Ponce de León II
paragraph: Juan Ponce de León II (1524 - 1591) was the first person to be born in Puerto Rico who served as acting governor of the island.

title: German champions
paragraph: German champions (German: "Deutsche Meister" ) is the general name given to winners of a Bundesliga (national league) sporting competition in Germany.

title: Radial artery
paragraph: In human anatomy, the radial artery is the main artery of the lateral aspect of the forearm.

title: Canal Street (Manhattan)
paragraph: Canal Street is a major east-west street in Lower Manhattan, New York City, running from East Broadway between Essex and Jefferson Streets in the east, to West Street between Watts and Spring Streets in the west. [SBD]  It runs through the neighborhood of Chinatown, and forms the southern boundaries of SoHo and Little Italy as well as the northern boundary of Tribeca. [SBD]  The street acts as a major connector between Jersey City, New Jersey, via the Holland Tunnel (I-78), and Brooklyn, New York City, via the Manhattan Bridge. [SBD]  It is a two-way street for most of its length – from West Street to the Manhattan Bridge – with two unidirectional stretches between Forsyth Street and the Manhattan Bridge.

title: Liquid Television
paragraph: Liquid Television is an animation showcase that appeared on MTV. [SBD]  The first season of "Liquid Television" also aired on BBC Two in co-production with MTV. [SBD]  Ultimately, MTV commissioned three seasons of the show, which was produced by Colossal Pictures. [SBD]  It has served as the launching point for several high-profile original cartoons, including "Beavis and Butt-head" and "Æon Flux". [SBD]  The show was eventually succeeded by "Cartoon Sushi". [SBD]  The bulk of "Liquid Television"<nowiki>'</nowiki>s material was created by independent animators and artists specially for the show, and some previously produced segments were compiled from festivals such as Spike and Mike's Sick and Twisted Festival of Animation. [SBD]  Mark Mothersbaugh composed the show's theme music. [SBD]  It was broadcast in New Zealand on TV3 and in Australia on SBS.

title: Akaike information criterion
paragraph: The Akaike information criterion (AIC) is an estimator of the relative quality of statistical models for a given set of data. [SBD]  Given a collection of models for the data, AIC estimates the quality of each model, relative to each of the other models. [SBD]  Thus, AIC provides a means for model selection.

title: Ahmad Shah Qajar
paragraph: Ahmad Shāh Qājār (Persian: احمد شاه قاجار‎ ‎ ; January 1898 – 21 February 1930) was Shah of Iran from 16 July 1909, to 15 December 1925, and the last ruling member of the Qajar dynasty.

title: Draw play
paragraph: A draw play, or simply draw for short, is a type of American football play. [SBD]  The draw is a running play disguised as a passing play. [SBD]  It is the opposite of a play-action pass, which is a passing play disguised as a running play. [SBD]  The play is often used in long yardage situations.

title: Richard Walther Darré
paragraph: Richard Walther Darré (born Ricardo Walther Oscar Darré; 14 July 1895 – 5 September 1953) was one of the leading Nazi "blood and soil" (German: "Blut und Boden") ideologists and served as Reich Minister of Food and Agriculture from 1933 to 1942. [SBD]  He was a high-ranking functionary in the SS and the seventh most senior commander in the organisation.

title: Laki
paragraph: Laki or Lakagígar ("Craters of Laki") is a volcanic fissure in the south of Iceland, not far from the canyon of Eldgjá and the small village of Kirkjubæjarklaustur. [SBD]  Lakagígar is the correct name, as Laki mountain itself did not erupt, as fissures opened up on each side of it. [SBD]  Lakagígar is part of a volcanic system centered on the volcano Grímsvötn and including the volcano Thordarhyrna. [SBD]  It lies between the glaciers of Mýrdalsjökull and Vatnajökull, in an area of fissures that run in a southwest to northeast direction.

title: Shingō, Aomori
paragraph: Shingō (新郷村 , Shingō-mura ) is a village located in Aomori Prefecture, Japan. [SBD]  s of 01 2016 , the village has an estimated population of 2,495, and a population density of 16.5 persons per km². [SBD]  Its total area of the village is 150.77 km² . [SBD]  The village promotes itself as the home of the "Grave of Christ" (キリストの墓 , Kirisuto no Haka ) after a local legend.

title: Mannus
paragraph: Mannus, according to the Roman writer Tacitus, was a figure in the creation myths of the Germanic tribes. [SBD]  Tacitus is the only source of these myths.

title: Gloria Grahame
paragraph: Gloria Grahame (November 28, 1923 – October 5, 1981) was an American stage, film and television actress.

title: Kapampangan language
paragraph: The Pampangan language or Kapampangan (Kulitan script: ) is one of the major languages of the Philippines. [SBD]  It is the language spoken in the province of Pampanga, on the plains of Central Luzon, the southern portion of the province of Tarlac and northeastern Bataan, most of whom belong to the Kapampangan ethnic group. [SBD]  Kapampangan is also understood in some municipalities of Bulacan and Nueva Ecija and by the Aitas or Aeta of Zambales. [SBD]  The language is also called as "Pampango" and honorifically in the Kapampangan language, as "Amánung Sísuan", meaning "breastfed/nurtured language". [SBD]  In 2012, Kapampangan is one of the major languages of the Philippines that is being taught and studied formally in schools and universities.

title: Black-throated munia
paragraph: The black-throated munia or Jerdon's mannikin ("Lonchura kelaarti") is a small passerine bird. [SBD]  This estrildid finch is a resident breeding bird in the hills of southwest India, the Eastern Ghats and Sri Lanka.

title: Eldgjá
paragraph: Eldgjá (] , "fire canyon") is a volcano and a canyon in Iceland. [SBD]  Eldgjá and the Katla volcano are part of the same volcanic system in the south of the country.

title: José Campeche
paragraph: José Campeche y Jordán (December 23, 1751 – November 7, 1809), is the first known Puerto Rican visual artist and considered by art critics as one of the best rococo artists in the Americas. [SBD]  Campeche y Jordán loved to use colors that referenced the landscape of Puerto Rico, as well as the social and political crème de la crème.

title: Play-action pass
paragraph: A play-action pass (also known as a play fake or simply "play-action") is a football play. [SBD]  The play action starts with what appears to be a running play, but turns out to be a pass play; in this way, it can be considered the opposite of a draw play. [SBD]  Play-action passes are often used against defenses that are focused on stopping the run. [SBD]  By initially simulating a running play, the offense attempts to deceive the defense into acting on the fake run and being out of position in their pass coverage, giving receivers more time and room to be free to receive passes behind the linebackers.

title: Fraunces Tavern
paragraph: Fraunces Tavern is a landmark museum and restaurant in New York City, situated at 54 Pearl Street at the corner of Broad Street. [SBD]  The location played a prominent role in history before, during and after the American Revolution, serving as a headquarters for George Washington, a venue for peace negotiations with the British, and housing federal offices in the Early Republic. [SBD]  It has been owned since 1904 by Sons of the Revolution in the State of New York Inc., which carried out a major conjectural reconstruction, and claim it is Manhattan's oldest surviving building. [SBD]  The museum interprets the building and its history, along with varied exhibitions of art and artifacts. [SBD]  The tavern is a tourist site and a part of the American Whiskey Trail and the New York Freedom Trail.

title: List of Church of the Nazarene schools
paragraph: This is a list of Bible colleges, liberal arts colleges, and seminaries owned and operated by the Church of the Nazarene. [SBD]  They are listed by continent and country.

title: Seattle Asian Art Museum
paragraph: The Seattle Asian Art Museum (SAAM) is a museum of Asian art located inside Volunteer Park in the Capitol Hill neighborhood of Seattle, Washington, United States. [SBD]  Part of the Seattle Art Museum, the SAAM occupies the 1933 Art Deco building (designed by Carl F. Gould of the architectural firm Bebb and Gould and listed on the National Register of Historic Places) which was originally home to the Seattle Art Museum's main collection. [SBD]  In 1991 the main collection moved to a newly constructed Seattle Art Museum building in downtown Seattle. [SBD]  The building in Volunteer Park remained closed until 1994, when it reopened as the Seattle Asian Art Museum. [SBD]  Admission is free on the first Thursday and the first Saturday of every month.

title: A. J. Langer
paragraph: Allison Joy Courtenay, Countess of Devon (née Langer, born May 22, 1974), commonly known as A. J. Langer, is an American actress most notable for her role as "Rayanne Graff" on the television series "My So-Called Life".

title: Hvítárvatn
paragraph: Hvítárvatn (also known as Hvítárlón) is a lake in the Highlands of Iceland and the source of the glacial river Hvítá. [SBD]  It is located 45 km northeast of Gullfoss waterfall. [SBD]  Its surface is about 30 km² and its greatest depth is 84 m.

title: Bounty (reward)
paragraph: A bounty (from Latin "bonitās", goodness) is a payment or reward often offered by a group as an incentive for the accomplishment of a task by someone usually not associated with the group. [SBD]  Bounties are most commonly issued for the capture or retrieval of a person or object. [SBD]  They are typically in the form of money. [SBD]  By definition bounties can be retracted at any time by whomever issued them. [SBD]  Two modern examples of bounties are the bounty placed for the capture of Saddam Hussein and his sons by the United States government and Microsoft's bounty for computer virus creators. [SBD]  Those who make a living by pursuing bounties are known as bounty hunters.

title: Samuel Dash
paragraph: Samuel Dash (February 27, 1925 – May 29, 2004) was an American lawyer who was chief counsel for the Senate Watergate Committee during the Watergate scandal. [SBD]  Dash became famous for his televised interrogations during the hearings held by the United States Congress on the Watergate incident.

title: Apavatn
paragraph: Apavatn is a lake in southwest Iceland. [SBD]  With a surface area of around 13 km² it is much larger than the neighbouring lake of Laugarvatn, which lies to the north of Apavatn.

title: Laugarvatn
paragraph: Laugarvatn is a lake and small town in the south of Iceland. [SBD]  The lake is a bit smaller than the neighbouring Apavatn.

title: Seward Park, Seattle
paragraph: Seward Park is a neighborhood in southeast Seattle, Washington just west of the park of the same name. [SBD]  It is part of Seattle's South End. [SBD]  The park itself occupies all of Bailey Peninsula, a prominent, forested peninsula that juts into Lake Washington. [SBD]  The attached map is accurate, broadly speaking, in capturing "Greater Seward Park," though real estate sites, such as Zillow, will refer to the part of the neighborhood north of Orcas Street as Lakewood, which is reasonable, since that neighborhood is the historic home of a "community club" (which owns its own house and land) once known as the "Lakewood Community Club" (built on or around the 1920s), and now known as the "Lakewood-Seward Community Club".

title: Moving Mars
paragraph: Moving Mars is a science fiction novel written by Greg Bear. [SBD]  Published in 1993, it won the 1994 Nebula Award for Best Novel, and was also nominated for the 1994 Hugo, Locus, and John W. Campbell Memorial Awards, each in the same category. [SBD]  The main focus of "Moving Mars" is the coming of age and development of Casseia Majumdar, the narrator, as political tensions over revolutionary scientific discoveries build between Earth and Martian factions, and Mars tries to unify itself.

title: Kamehameha III
paragraph: Kamehameha III (born Kauikeaouli) (1813 – December 15, 1854) was the King of Hawaii from 1825 to 1854. [SBD]  His full Hawaiian name was Keaweaweʻ ula Kīwalaʻ ō Kauikeaouli Kaleiopapa and then lengthened to Keaweaweʻ ula Kīwalaʻ ō Kauikeaouli Kaleiopapa Kalani Waiakua Kalanikau Iokikilo Kīwalaʻ ō i ke kapu Kamehameha when he ascended the throne.

title: The New Criterion
paragraph: The New Criterion is a New York-based monthly literary magazine and journal of artistic and cultural criticism, edited by Roger Kimball (editor and publisher) and James Panero (executive editor). [SBD]  It has sections for criticism of poetry, theater, art, music, the media, and books. [SBD]  It was founded in 1982 by Hilton Kramer, former art critic for "The New York Times", and Samuel Lipman, a pianist and music critic. [SBD]  The name is a reference to "The Criterion", a British literary magazine edited by T. S. Eliot from 1922 to 1939.

title: West Seattle, Seattle
paragraph: West Seattle comprises two of Seattle, Washington's thirteen districts, Delridge and Southwest, and encompasses all of Seattle west of the Duwamish River. [SBD]  It was incorporated as an independent town in 1902 and was annexed by Seattle in 1907. [SBD]  Among the area's attractions are its saltwater beach parks along Elliott Bay and Puget Sound, including Alki Beach Park and Lincoln Park. [SBD]  The area is also known for its views of the Olympic Mountains to the west and the Cascade Range to the east. [SBD]  Fully 1/3 of Seattle's green space and urban forest is located in West Seattle, much of it found in the West Duwamish Greenbelt.

title: Kamehameha V
paragraph: Kamehameha V (1830–1872), born as Lot Kapuāiwa, reigned as monarch of the Kingdom of Hawaiʻi from 1863 to 1872. [SBD]  His motto was "Onipa`a": immovable, firm, steadfast or determined; he worked diligently for his people and kingdom and was described as the last great traditional chief. [SBD]  His full Hawaiian name prior to his succession was Lota Kapuāiwa Kalanimakua Aliʻiōlani Kalanikupuapaʻīkalaninui.

title: Edge coloring
paragraph: In graph theory, an edge coloring of a graph is an assignment of "colors" to the edges of the graph so that no two adjacent edges have the same color. [SBD]  For example, the figure to the right shows an edge coloring of a graph by the colors red, blue, and green. [SBD]  Edge colorings are one of several different types of graph coloring. [SBD]  The edge-coloring problem asks whether it is possible to color the edges of a given graph using at most k different colors, for a given value of k , or with the fewest possible colors. [SBD]  The minimum required number of colors for the edges of a given graph is called the chromatic index of the graph. [SBD]  For example, the edges of the graph in the illustration can be colored by three colors but cannot be colored by two colors, so the graph shown has chromatic index three.

title: Virgil Bogue
paragraph: Virgil Gay Bogue was born in Norfolk, New York, on July 20, 1846. [SBD]  He received a degree in civil engineering from the Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in Troy, New York, in 1868. [SBD]  Bogue worked consecutively on Oroya Railway in Peru to 1879, the Northern Pacific Railway to 1886. [SBD]  On the Northern Pacific, he named Pasco, Washington, after a region known for vicious sandstorms he had seen while in South America), built the Northern Pacific and Puget Sound Shore Railroad connecting Tacoma, Washington to Seattle, Washington, and discovered Stampede Pass

title: Julia (mother of Mark Antony)
paragraph: Julia (104 BC-after 39 BC) or Julia Antonia (known from the sources to distinguish her from other Juliae) was a daughter of Lucius Julius Caesar, the consul of 90 BC, and mother of the future triumvir and deputy of Caesar, Mark Antony. [SBD]  She was a sister of the Lucius Julius Caesar who was consul in 64 BC. [SBD]  Her mother is unknown. [SBD]  She was born and raised in Rome. [SBD]  Julia was a cousin of Julius Caesar.

title: Ascot Gold Cup
