paragraph: The Gold Cup is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged four years or older. [SBD]  It is run at Ascot over a distance of 2 miles 3 furlongs and 210 yards , and it is scheduled to take place each year in June.

title: Luis Rivas
paragraph: Luis Wilfredo Rivas (born August 30, 1979) is a former Major League Baseball infielder. [SBD]  He played for the Minnesota Twins from 2000 to 2005, Cleveland Indians in 2007, and Pittsburgh Pirates in 2008. [SBD]  He batted and throws right-handed.

title: Coronation Stakes
paragraph: The Coronation Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to three-year-old fillies. [SBD]  It is run at Ascot over a distance of 7 furlong and 213 yards , and it is scheduled to take place each year in June.

title: Tom Yawkey
paragraph: Thomas Austin Yawkey, born Thomas Yawkey Austin (February 21, 1903 – July 9, 1976), was an American industrialist and Major League Baseball executive. [SBD]  Born in Detroit, Yawkey became president of the Boston Red Sox in 1933, and was the sole owner of the team for 44 seasons, longer than anyone else in baseball history. [SBD]  He was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1980.

title: Diamond Jubilee Stakes
paragraph: The Diamond Jubilee Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged four years or older. [SBD]  It is run at Ascot over a distance of 6 furlongs , and it is scheduled to take place each year in June.

title: Dmitry Yazov
paragraph: Dmitry Timofeyevich Yazov (Russian: Дми́трий Тимофе́евич Я́зов ; born 8 November 1924) was the last Marshal of the Soviet Union to be appointed before the collapse of the Soviet Union (on 28 April 1990). [SBD]  He was the only Marshal of the Soviet Union to be born in Siberia. [SBD]  A veteran of the Great Patriotic War, Yazov is the last surviving Marshal and the only one not to have been awarded the title Hero of the Soviet Union.

title: Eclipse Stakes
paragraph: The Eclipse Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged three years or older. [SBD]  It is run at Sandown Park over a distance of 1 mile, 1 furlongs and 209 yards , and it is scheduled to take place each year in early July.

title: Gustaf af Wetterstedt
paragraph: Count Gustaf af Wetterstedt (29 December 1776 – 15 May 1837) was a Swedish statesman. [SBD]  He served as the Prime Minister for Foreign Affairs from 1824 to 1837. [SBD]  In 1811 he was elected into the Swedish Academy, and later he also became a member of the Royal Swedish Academies of Agriculture, Music and Sciences (1817). [SBD]  He was also invested as a Knight in the Order of the Seraphim.

title: George Yeardley
paragraph: Sir George Yeardley (1587–1627) was a planter and three time colonial Governor of the British Colony of Virginia. [SBD]  A survivor of the Virginia Company of London's ill-fated Third Supply Mission, whose flagship, the "Sea Venture", was shipwrecked on Bermuda for 10 months in 1609-10, he is best remembered for presiding over the initial session of the first representative legislative body in Virginia in 1619. [SBD]  With representatives from throughout the settled portion of the colony, the group became known as the House of Burgesses. [SBD]  It has met continuously since, and is known in modern times as the Virginia General Assembly.

title: Falmouth Stakes
paragraph: The Falmouth Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to fillies and mares aged three years or older. [SBD]  It is run on the July Course at Newmarket over a distance of 1 mile , and it is scheduled to take place each year in July.

title: Terenure
paragraph: Terenure (Irish: "Tír an Iúir" , meaning "land of the yew tree" ) is a mainly residential suburb of Dublin, Ireland, largely in the administrative area of Dublin City Council but with parts in the administrative county of South Dublin (within the Terenure-Templeogue electoral area).

title: Gaius Antonius Hybrida
paragraph: Gaius Antonius Hybrida (flourished 1st century BC) was a politician of the Roman Republic. [SBD]  He was the second son of Marcus Antonius and brother of Marcus Antonius Creticus; his mother is unknown. [SBD]  He was also the uncle of the famed triumvir Mark Antony. [SBD]  He had two children, Antonia Hybrida Major and Antonia Hybrida Minor.

title: Adly Yakan Pasha
paragraph: Adly Yakan Pasha (18 January 1864 – 22 October 1933) (Arabic: عدلي يكن باشا‎ ‎ ), sometimes referred to as Adly Pasha, was an Egyptian political figure. [SBD]  He served as the 14th Prime Minister of Egypt between 1921 and 1922, again between 1926 and 1927, and finally in 1929. [SBD]  He held several prominent political posts including Foreign Minister, Interior Minister and Speaker of the Egyptian Senate.

title: July Cup
paragraph: The July Cup is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged three years or older. [SBD]  It is run on the July Course at Newmarket over a distance of 6 furlongs <smalll>(1,207 metres)</small>, and it is scheduled to take place each year in July.

title: Robert Prosinečki
paragraph: Robert Prosinečki (] ; born 12 January 1969) is a Croatian football manager and former football midfielder. [SBD]  He is one of the few footballers to have played for both the Spanish rival clubs Real Madrid and FC Barcelona.

title: Adolphe Yvon
paragraph: Adolphe Yvon (1817–1893) was a French painter known for his paintings of the Napoleonic Wars. [SBD]  Yvon studied under Paul Delaroche, rose to fame during the Second Empire, then finished his career as a teacher.

title: King George VI and Queen Elizabeth Stakes
paragraph: The King George VI and Queen Elizabeth Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged three years or older. [SBD]  It is run at Ascot over a distance of 1 mile and 4 furlongs (2,414 metres), and it is scheduled to take place each year in July.

title: Coat of arms of the Drapers Company
paragraph: The Worshipful Company of Drapers, informally known as the Drapers' Company and formally known as The Master and Wardens and Brethren and Sisters of the Guild or Fraternity of the Blessed Mary the Virgin of the Mystery of Drapers of the City of London was probably the first corporate body in England to be granted a coat of arms, on 10 March 1438/9 by Sir William Bruges, Garter King of Arms. [SBD]  The patent dated 1439 is the earliest surviving such grant of arms made to a corporate body in England. [SBD]  The arms were modified in 1561, when the crest was added and the lion supporters granted. [SBD]  These grants were superseded in 1613 with minor modifications. [SBD]  The Queen as Freeman of the Fraternity possesses a small jewelled and enamelled brooch depicting its arms and circumscribed by the motto, known as "The Drapers Company Badge". [SBD]  She wears the brooch when performing royal engagements connected with the Drapers Company. [SBD]  The modern blazon is: "Azure, three clouds radiated proper each adorned with a triple crown or". [SBD]  The triple crown contains a cap (velvet/fabric lining visible through the gold structure) "gules".

title: Yuri II of Vladimir
paragraph: Yuri II (Russian: Ю́рий–II ), also known as George II of Vladimir or Georgy II Vsevolodovich (11894 March 1238), was the fourth Grand Prince of Vladimir (1212–1216, 1218–1238) who presided over Vladimir-Suzdal at the time of the Mongol invasion of Russia.

title: Sussex Stakes
paragraph: The Sussex Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged three years or older. [SBD]  It is run at Goodwood over a distance of 1 mile <smalll>(1,609 metres)</small>, and it is scheduled to take place each year in late July or early August.

title: Nassau Stakes
paragraph: The Nassau Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to fillies and mares aged three years or older. [SBD]  It is run at Goodwood over a distance of 1 mile, 1 furlong and 197 yards , and it is scheduled to take place each year in late July or early August.

title: Yun Posun
paragraph: Yun Posun (Hangul: 윤보선 ; Hanja: 尹潽善 ; ] or ] ] ; August 26, 1897 – July 18, 1990) was a Korean independence activist and politician, who served as President of South Korea from 1960 to 1962 before being replaced by the long-serving Park Chung-hee as a result of the May 16 coup in 1961.

title: International Stakes
paragraph: The International Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged three years or older. [SBD]  It is run at York over a distance of 1 mile, 2 furlongs and 56 yards , and it is scheduled to take place each year in August.

title: Yorkshire Oaks
paragraph: The Yorkshire Oaks is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to fillies and mares aged three years or older. [SBD]  It is run at York over a distance of 1 mile 3 furlongs and 188 yards , and it is scheduled to take place each year in August.

title: Yu Hung-chun
paragraph: Yu Hung-chun () (4 January 1898 – 1 June 1960), widely known as O. K. Yui, was a Chinese political figure who served as mayor of Shanghai, chairman of the Taiwan Provincial Government and Premier of the Republic of China.

title: Nunthorpe Stakes
paragraph: The Nunthorpe Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged two years or older. [SBD]  It is run at York over a distance of 5 furlongs , and it is scheduled to take place each year in August.

title: Guarded Command Language
paragraph: The Guarded Command Language (GCL) is a language defined by Edsger Dijkstra for predicate transformer semantics. [SBD]  It combines programming concepts in a compact way, before the program is written in some practical programming language. [SBD]  Its simplicity makes proving the correctness of programs easier, using Hoare logic.

title: Paul Niclausse
paragraph: Paul Niclausse (1879–1958) was a French sculptor, most famous for his art deco medals cast in bronze.

title: Haydock Sprint Cup
paragraph: The Sprint Cup is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to thoroughbreds aged three years or older. [SBD]  It is run at Haydock Park over a distance of 6 furlongs , and it is scheduled to take place each year in early September.

title: Paavo Yrjölä
paragraph: Paavo Ilmari Yrjölä (18 June 1902 in Hämeenkyrö – 11 February 1980 in Vilppula), also known as the "Bear of Hämeenkyrö" ("Hämeenkyrön karhu"), was a Finnish track and field athlete who won the gold medal in the decathlon at the 1928 Summer Olympics. [SBD]  He also competed in shot put and high jump at the same Games, and in decathlon in 1924 and 1932, but less successfully.

title: Fillies' Mile
paragraph: The Fillies' Mile is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to two-year-old fillies. [SBD]  It is run on the Rowley Mile at Newmarket over a distance of 1 mile (1,609 metres), and it is scheduled to take place each year in October.

title: Samuel Youngs
paragraph: Samuel Youngs (December 4, 1760 – September 12, 1839) was an American school teacher. [SBD]  He was a friend of Washington Irving and elements of his life may be included in the character Ichabod Crane in Irving's story "The Legend of Sleepy Hollow", along with the character inspiration from Kinderhook Schoolteacher, Jesse Merwin.

title: Queen Elizabeth II Stakes
paragraph: The Queen Elizabeth II Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to horses aged three years or older. [SBD]  It is run at Ascot over a distance of 1 mile (1,609 metres), and it is scheduled to take place as part of British Champions Day each year in October.

title: Pinus cembra
paragraph: Pinus cembra, also known as Swiss pine, Swiss stone pine or Arolla pine or Austrian stone pine or just Stone pine, is a species of pine tree that grows in the Alps and Carpathian Mountains of central Europe, in Poland (Tatra Mountains), Switzerland, France, Italy, Austria, Germany, Slovenia, Slovakia (Tatra Mountains), Ukraine and Romania. [SBD]  It typically grows at 1,200 m to 2,300 m altitude. [SBD]  It often reaches the alpine tree line in this area. [SBD]  The mature size is typically between 25 m and 35 m in height, and the trunk diameter can be up to 1.5 m . [SBD]  The species is long-lasting and can reach an age between 500 and 1000 years. [SBD]  However, it grows very slowly and it may take 30 years for the tree to reach 1.3 m .

title: Frederick Holbourn
paragraph: Frederick William Holbourn (16 July 1896 - 1967) was a totally disabled war pensioner who worked to achieve justice for war pensioners in the United Kingdom in the years following World War I.

title: Crisis (Fleetway)
paragraph: Crisis was a British comic book magazine published from 1988 to 1991 as an experiment by Fleetway to see if intelligent, mature, politically and socially aware comics were saleable in the United Kingdom. [SBD]  The comic was initially published fortnightly, and was one of the most visible components of the late-1980s British comics boom, along with "Deadline", "Revolver", and "Toxic! [SBD] ".

title: Cheveley Park Stakes
paragraph: The Cheveley Park Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to two-year-old fillies. [SBD]  It is run on the Rowley Mile at Newmarket over a distance of 6 furlongs (1,207 metres), and it is scheduled to take place each year in late September.

title: Michelle Smith
paragraph: Michelle Smith de Bruin (born 16 December 1969 in Rathcoole, County Dublin) is a retired Irish swimmer who achieved notable success in the 1996 Summer Olympics in Atlanta, becoming Ireland's most successful Olympian to date, and whose career ended with a ban from the sporting authorities for tampering with a urine sample. [SBD]  She was a triple gold medallist at the Atlanta Games, for the 400 m individual medley, 400 m freestyle and 200 m individual medley, and also won the bronze medal for the 200 m butterfly event: these events were marked by allegations of doping which were, however, never proven. [SBD]  Michelle Smith, now more commonly referred to by her married name, Michelle Smith de Bruin, is currently a practising barrister.

title: Middle Park Stakes
paragraph: The Middle Park Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to two-year-old colts. [SBD]  It is run on the Rowley Mile at Newmarket over a distance of 6 furlongs (1,207 metres), and it is scheduled to take place each year in September.

title: Dewhurst Stakes
paragraph: The Dewhurst Stakes is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to two-year-old colts and fillies. [SBD]  It is run on the Rowley Mile at Newmarket over a distance of 7 furlongs (1,408 metres), and it is scheduled to take place each year in October.

title: Fermoy
paragraph: Fermoy (Irish: "Mainistir Fhear Maí" , meaning "monastery of the Men of the Plain" ) is a town on the River Blackwater in east County Cork, Ireland. [SBD]  As of the 2011 census, the town and environs had a population of approximately 6,500 people. [SBD]  It is located in the barony of Fermoy.

title: La Spezia–Rimini Line
paragraph: The La Spezia–Rimini Line (also known as the Massa–Senigallia Line), in the linguistics of the Romance languages, is a line that demarcates a number of important isoglosses that distinguish Romance languages south and east of the line from Romance languages north and west of it. [SBD]  The line runs through northern Italy, very roughly from the cities of La Spezia to Rimini. [SBD]  Romance languages on the eastern half of it include Italian and the Eastern Romance languages (Romanian, Aromanian, Megleno-Romanian, Istro-Romanian), whereas Spanish, French, Catalan, Portuguese as well as Gallo‒Italic languages are representatives of the Western group. [SBD]  (Sardinian does not fit into either Western or Eastern Romance.)

title: Champion Stakes
paragraph: "This page is about the British horse race. [SBD]  For other uses, see Champion Stakes (disambiguation)"

title: Gerber format
paragraph: The Gerber format is an open ASCII vector format for 2D binary images. [SBD]  It is the de facto standard used by printed circuit board (PCB) industry software to describe the printed circuit board images: copper layers, solder mask, legend, etc.

title: Racing Post Trophy
paragraph: The Racing Post Trophy is a Group 1 flat horse race in Great Britain open to two-year-old thoroughbred colts and fillies. [SBD]  It is run at Doncaster over a distance of 1 mile (1,609 metres), and it is scheduled to take place each year in late October.

title: Toy Manchester Terrier
paragraph: The Toy Manchester Terrier is a breed of dog, categorized as a terrier. [SBD]  The breed was bred down in size in North America from the Manchester Terrier, and is placed in the Toy Group by the American Kennel Club and the Canadian Kennel Club (the Manchester Terrier is placed in the Terrier Group.) [SBD]  Neither the Fédération Cynologique Internationale nor The Kennel Club recognize a Toy variety of the Manchester Terrier.

title: Tomás Pérez
paragraph: Tomás Orlando Pérez Garcia (born December 29, 1973) is a former Major League Baseball infielder. [SBD]  Pérez was a utility infielder who throws right-handed and switch hits.

title: Samuel Baldwin Marks Young
paragraph: Samuel Baldwin Marks Young (January 9, 1840 – September 1, 1924) was a United States Army general. [SBD]  He also served as the first president of Army War College between 1902 and 1903. [SBD]  He then served from 1903 until 1904 as the first Chief of Staff of the United States Army.

title: British Columbia Action Party
paragraph: The BC Action Party was a minor political party in British Columbia, Canada. [SBD]  It nominated six candidates in the 2001 British Columbia election. [SBD]  These candidates won 1,718 votes (1.31% of the total in the ridings in which they ran). [SBD]  BCAP candidates ran in ridings in Okanagan, Kelowna and Surrey, and placed last in all six ridings. [SBD]  The party’s best showing was in Okanagan Westside, where its candidate won 921 votes (4.4% of the total). [SBD]  The party was later de-registered by the BC elections commission

title: Roy A. Young
paragraph: Roy Archibald Young (May 17, 1882 – December 31, 1960) was an American banker. [SBD]  Most significantly, he was chairman of the Federal Reserve Board between 1927 and 1930 during the presidencies of Calvin Coolidge and Herbert Hoover. [SBD]  During his tenure as chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, the Stock Market Crash of 1929 occurred and the United States went into an economic depression. [SBD]  He also was president of the Federal Reserve Banks in Minneapolis (1919-1927) and Boston (1930-1942).

title: Pinus sibirica
paragraph: Pinus sibirica, or Siberian pine, in the family Pinaceae is a species of pine tree that occurs in Siberia from 58°E in the Ural Mountains east to 126°E in the Stanovoy Range in southern Sakha Republic, and from Igarka at 68°N in the lower Yenisei valley, south to 45°N in central Mongolia.

title: Citizens Commonwealth Federation
paragraph: The Citizens Commonwealth Federation was a minor political party in British Columbia, Canada. [SBD]  It nominated one candidate in the 2001 British Columbia election, Laery Braaten, in the riding of Victoria-Hillside. [SBD]  He placed last out of 7 candidates, winning 49 votes (0.24% of the total).

title: Santiniketan
paragraph: Santiniketan (Bengali: শান্তিনিকেতন "Santiniketôn") is a small town near Bolpur in the Birbhum district of West Bengal, India, approximately 160 km north of Kolkata (formerly Calcutta). [SBD]  It was established by Maharshi Devendranath Tagore, and later expanded by his son Rabindranath Tagore whose vision became what is now a university town, Visva-Bharati University.

title: British Columbia Citizens Alliance Now
paragraph: The BC Citizens Alliance Now (BC CAN) was a minor political party in British Columbia, Canada. [SBD]  It nominated two candidates in the 2001 British Columbia election:

title: Freedom Party of British Columbia
paragraph: The Freedom Party of British Columbia was a minor political party in British Columbia, Canada. [SBD]  Several of its policies were based on fundamentalist Christian values.

title: Mark Aitchison Young
paragraph: Sir Mark Aitchison Young (楊慕琦, 30 June 1886 – 12 May 1974) was a British administrator who became the Governor of Hong Kong during the years immediately before and after the Japanese occupation of the territory.

title: Hamilton, Bermuda
paragraph: Hamilton is the capital of the British Overseas Territory of Bermuda. [SBD]  It is the territory's financial centre and a major port and tourist destination. [SBD]  Its population of 1,010 (2010) is one of the smallest of any capital cities.

title: All Nations Party of British Columbia
paragraph: The All Nations Party was a minor political party in British Columbia, Canada. [SBD]  Its primary base of support was the First Nations aboriginal peoples of Canada.

title: Dreamfall: The Longest Journey
paragraph: Dreamfall: The Longest Journey (Norwegian: "Drømmefall: Den lengste reisen" ) is an adventure video game developed by Funcom for Microsoft Windows and Xbox platforms in April 2006. [SBD]  On 1 March 2007, a sequel entitled "Dreamfall Chapters" was announced, and Funcom reportedly considered the idea of a massively multiplayer online game set in "The Longest Journey" universe.

title: John Russell Young
paragraph: John Russell Young (November 20, 1840 – January 17, 1899) was an American journalist, author, diplomat, and the seventh Librarian of the United States Congress from 1897 to 1899. [SBD]  He was invited by Ulysses S. Grant to accompany him on a world tour for purposes of recording the two-year journey, which he published in a book.

title: Franz Vranitzky
paragraph: Franz Vranitzky (born 4 October 1937) is an Austrian politician. [SBD]  A member of the Social Democratic Party of Austria (SPÖ), he was Chancellor of Austria from 1986 to 1997.

title: Frank Edward Young (physician)
paragraph: Frank Edward Young (born 1931 in Mineola, New York) is a physician and former senior U.S. government official. [SBD]  He served as Commissioner of Food and Drugs, or Director of the Food and Drug Administration (FDA), between 1984 and 1989 and later as a Deputy Assistant Secretary in the United States Department of Health and Human Services. [SBD]  In 2013 he joined Braeburn Pharmaceuticals as Executive Vice President, Clinical and Regulatory Affairs.

title: Ann Eliza Young
paragraph: Ann Eliza Young (September 13, 1844 – December 7, 1917) also known as Ann Eliza Webb Dee Young Denning was one of Brigham Young's fifty-five wives and later a critic of polygamy. [SBD]  She spoke out against the suppression of women and was an advocate for women's rights during the 19th century.

title: 23 Thalia
paragraph: 23 Thalia is a large main-belt asteroid. [SBD]  It was discovered by J. R. Hind on December 15, 1852, at the private observatory of W. Bishop, located in Hyde Park, London, England. [SBD]  Bishop named it after Thalia, the Muse of comedy and pastoral poetry in Greek mythology.

title: Chagossians
paragraph: The Chagossians (also Îlois or Chagos Islanders) are people of African, Indian and Malay ancestry who inhabited the Chagos Islands, specifically Diego Garcia, Peros Banhos, and the Salomon island chain, as well as other parts of the Chagos Archipelago, from the late 18th to the late 20th century. [SBD]  Most Chagossians now live in Mauritius and the United Kingdom after being forcibly evicted by the British government in the late 1960s and early 1970s so that Diego Garcia, the island where most Chagossians lived, could serve as the location for a United States military base. [SBD]  Today, no Chagossians live on the island of Diego Garcia, as it is now the site of the military base Camp Justice.

title: Escalante River
paragraph: The Escalante River is a tributary of the Colorado River. [SBD]  It is formed by the confluence of Upper Valley and Birch Creeks near the town of Escalante in south-central Utah, and from there flows southeast for approximately 90 mi before joining Lake Powell. [SBD]  Its watershed includes the high forested slopes of the Aquarius Plateau, the east slope of the Kaiparowits Plateau and the high desert north of Lake Powell. [SBD]  It was the last river of its size to be discovered in the 48 contiguous U.S. states.

title: Cervical spine disorder
paragraph: Cervical spine disorders are illnesses that affect the cervical spine, which is made up of the upper first seven vertebrae, encasing and shielding the spinal cord. [SBD]  This fragment of the spine starts from the region above the shoulder blades and ends by supporting and connecting the Skull.

title: Avco World Trophy
paragraph: The Avco World Trophy, also known as the Avco Cup, is the championship trophy of the defunct World Hockey Association (1972–1979). [SBD]  The trophy's naming rights were sold to the former Avco Corporation (a name originally derived from "Aviation Company"), a defense contractor who bought the rights to advertise their consumer finance division. [SBD]  The trophy was mocked by some for its corporate sponsorship and never developed anything approaching the significance and sentiment of the Stanley Cup, its National Hockey League rival. [SBD]  Still, the cup's design was often seen as creative in that it involved a freely-floating etched crystal globe embedded in the "stem" of the cup. [SBD]  The cup was designed by Frank Bonnerkopf of Boise, Idaho.

title: Universal Wrestling Federation (Japan)
paragraph: The original Japanese-based Universal Wrestling Federation (UWF) was a Japanese professional wrestling promotion from 1984 to 1986, formed by wrestlers who had left New Japan Pro Wrestling. [SBD]  It was a pioneer in the shoot-style of pro-wrestling, which emphasized realistic moves. [SBD]  It was revived as the Newborn UWF in 1988. [SBD]  Newborn UWF lasted until 1990. [SBD]  It was revived again in 1991 as Union of Wrestling Forces International (UWF International or UWFi), which in turn lasted until 1996.

title: Fulbert Youlou
paragraph: Abbé Fulbert Youlou (9 June, 17 June or 19 July 1917 – 6 May 1972) was a laicized Brazzaville-Congolese Roman Catholic priest, nationalist leader and politician, who became the first President of Congo-Brazzaville on its independence.

title: Edward Youde
paragraph: Sir Edward Youde {'1': ", '2': ", '3': ", '4': "} (Chinese: 尤德; Cantonese: "Yau Tak"; 19 June 1924 – 5 December 1986) was a British administrator, diplomat and Sinologist. [SBD]  He served as Governor of Hong Kong between 20 May 1982 and 5 December 1986.

title: Party of Citizens Who Have Decided to Think for Themselves and Be Their Own Politicians
paragraph: Party of Citizens Who Have Decided to Think for Themselves and Be Their Own Politicians

title: Babylon 5 Collectible Card Game
paragraph: The Babylon 5 Collectible Card Game (B5 CCG) is a discontinued collectible card game set in the "Babylon 5" universe. [SBD]  The game is ideally set for 5 players but can be played from a minimum of two players to as many as 20 if using multiple Non-Aligned Factions and Home Factions. [SBD]  This CCG is distinct from most others of the genre for being specifically designed to be played by more than two players. [SBD]  The gameplay tends to have strong political elements encouraging significant player interaction aka "table talk" which is appropriate for a game based on a series which featured such a strong element of political intrigue. [SBD]  During its brief six-year existence under the Precedence Entertainment banner it released two core sets, five expansions sets and one revision set. [SBD]  There were two World Championships during that time. [SBD]  The game still continues to have a cult following as two further releases were made available online.

title: Jim Dickinson
paragraph: James Luther Dickinson (November 15, 1941 – August 15, 2009) was an American record producer, pianist, and singer who fronted, among others, the band Mud Boy and the Neutrons, based in Memphis, Tennessee.

title: Fielding H. Yost
paragraph: Fielding Harris Yost (April 30, 1871 – August 20, 1946) was an American football player, coach and college athletics administrator. [SBD]  He served as the head football coach at: Ohio Wesleyan University (1897), the University of Nebraska–Lincoln (1898), the University of Kansas (1899), Stanford University (1900), San Jose State University (1900), and the University of Michigan (1901–1923, 1925–1926), compiling a college football career record of 198–35–12. [SBD]  During his 25 seasons as the head football coach at Ann Arbor, Yost's Michigan Wolverines won six national championships, captured ten Big Ten Conference titles, and amassed a record of 165–29–10.

title: Alex Leigh
paragraph: Alexandra Dallas Leigh (born 2 October 1978) is an English fashion model. [SBD]  She was born in Manchester on 2 October 1978 and was formerly a waitress for William's Tavern. [SBD]  She went to school at Altrincham Grammar School for girls and speaks fluent Spanish, having lived there as a child.

title: Major (disambiguation)
paragraph: Major is a military rank. [SBD]  The word derives from the Latin "maior" (also spelled "major"), which means "greater".

title: Engram (neuropsychology)
paragraph: Engrams are theorized to be means by which memories are stored as biophysical or biochemical changes in the brain (and other neural tissue) in response to external stimuli.

title: Association football positions
paragraph: In the sport of association football, each of the 11 players on a team is assigned to a particular position on the field of play. [SBD]  A team is made up of one goalkeeper and ten outfield players who fill various defensive, midfield, and attacking positions depending on the formation deployed. [SBD]  These positions describe both the player's main role and their area of operation on the pitch.

title: Snark (graph theory)
paragraph: In the mathematical field of graph theory, a snark is a simple, connected, bridgeless cubic graph with chromatic index equal to 4. [SBD]  In other words, it is a graph in which every vertex has three neighbors, and the edges cannot be colored by only three colors without two edges of the same color meeting at a point. [SBD]  (By Vizing's theorem, the chromatic index of a cubic graph is 3 or 4.) [SBD]  In order to avoid trivial cases, snarks are often restricted to have girth at least 5.

title: TWIRL
paragraph: In cryptography and number theory, TWIRL (The Weizmann Institute Relation Locator) is a hypothetical hardware device designed to speed up the sieving step of the general number field sieve integer factorization algorithm. [SBD]  During the sieving step, the algorithm searches for numbers with a certain mathematical relationship. [SBD]  In distributed factoring projects, this is the step that is parallelized to a large number of processors.

title: Harold H. Seward
paragraph: Harold H. Seward (July 24, 1930 – June 19, 2012) was a computer scientist, engineer, and inventor. [SBD]  Seward developed the radix sort and counting sort algorithms in 1954 at MIT. [SBD]  He also worked on the Whirlwind Computer and developed instruments that powered the guidance systems for the Apollo spacecraft and Polaris missile.

title: Kiki Gyan
paragraph: Kiki Gyan (7 June 1957 – 10 June 2004), also known as Kiki Djan, was a Ghanaian musician. [SBD]  He was the keyboardist of the band Osibisa, once popular in the 1970s. [SBD]  He also recorded and produced a series of disco records. [SBD]  He was a prodigy who could play keyboards exceptionally well.

title: Charles Woodruff Yost
paragraph: Charles Woodruff Yost (November 6, 1907 – May 21, 1981) was a career U.S. diplomat who was assigned as his country's representative to the United Nations from 1969 to 1971.

title: 25 Phocaea
paragraph: 25 Phocaea is a main-belt asteroid. [SBD]  It was discovered by J. Chacornac at Marseille, on April 6. [SBD]  1853. [SBD]  It was his first asteroid discovery out of a total of six. [SBD]  It is named after Phocaea, the Greek name of Foça in Turkey, whence the founders of Marseille came.

title: 2001 QR322
paragraph: 2001 QR is a minor planet and the first Neptune trojan discovered on 21 August 2001, by the Deep Ecliptic Survey at Cerro Tololo Observatory in Chile. [SBD]  It orbits ahead of Neptune at its L Lagrangian point.

title: Harry Potter (character)
paragraph: Harry James Potter is the title character and protagonist of J. K. Rowling's "Harry Potter" series. [SBD]  The majority of the books' plot covers seven years in the life of the orphan Potter, who, on his eleventh birthday, learns he is a wizard. [SBD]  Thus, he attends Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry to practise magic under the guidance of the kindly headmaster Albus Dumbledore and other school professors. [SBD]  Harry also discovers that he is already famous throughout the novel's magical community, and that his fate is tied with that of Lord Voldemort, the internationally feared Dark Wizard and murderer of his parents, Lily and James.

title: 26 Proserpina
paragraph: 26 Proserpina is a main-belt asteroid discovered by R. Luther on May 5, 1853. [SBD]  It is named after the Roman goddess Proserpina, the daughter of Ceres and the Queen of the Underworld.

title: Yoshimasa
paragraph: Yoshimasa (written: 芳正, 義正, 義政, 義昌, 佳正, 慶昌 or 吉政) is a masculine Japanese given name. [SBD]  Notable people with the name include:

title: David Keith
paragraph: David Lemuel Keith (born May 8, 1954) is an American actor and director. [SBD]  His breakthrough role was that of aspiring Navy pilot Sid Worley in "An Officer and a Gentleman" (1982), for which he was nominated for two Golden Globe Awards. [SBD]  The positive reception for this role led to leading parts in the films "The Lords of Discipline" (1983), "Firestarter" (1984) and "White of the Eye" (1987). [SBD]  Keith had notable supporting roles in features including "The Indian in the Cupboard" (1995), "U-571" (2000), "Men of Honor" (2000) and "Daredevil" (2003).

title: 27 Euterpe
paragraph: 27 Euterpe is a large main-belt asteroid. [SBD]  It was discovered by J. R. Hind on November 8, 1853, and named after Euterpē, the Muse of music in Greek mythology.

title: Iceland Defense Force
paragraph: The Iceland Defense Force (IDF) was a military command of the United States Armed Forces from 1951 to 2006. [SBD]  The IDF, created at the request of NATO, came into existence when the United States signed an agreement to provide for the defense of Iceland, which has only limited defense forces.

title: Osibisa
paragraph: Osibisa are a British Afro-rock band, founded in London in 1969 by four expatriate African and three Caribbean musicians. [SBD]  Their music is a fusion of African, Caribbean, jazz, funk, rock, Latin, and R&B. [SBD]  Osibisa were one of the first African-heritage bands to become widely popular and linked with the establishment of world music as a marketable genre.

title: Rocky Mountain Institute
paragraph: Rocky Mountain Institute (RMI) is an organization in the United States dedicated to research, publication, consulting, and lecturing in the general field of sustainability, with a special focus on profitable innovations for energy and resource efficiency. [SBD]  RMI was established in 1982 and has grown into a broad-based institution with 150+ staff and an annual budget of some $30 million. [SBD]  RMI's work is independent and non-adversarial, with a strong emphasis on market-based solutions. [SBD]  The institute, including recently merged Carbon War Room, operates across 9 different initiative areas: Electricity Platform, Renewables Solutions, Buildings, Reinventing Fire: China, Smart Island Economies, Mobility Transformation, Shipping Efficiency, Sunshine for Mines, Sustainable Aviation, and Trucking Efficiency. [SBD]  The work of RMI has benefited more than 80 Fortune 500 companies in a diverse range of sectors. [SBD]  RMI is headquartered in Basalt, Colorado, and also maintains offices in Boulder, Colorado, New York City, Washington D.C. and Beijing, China.

title: Joachim Yhombi-Opango
paragraph: Jacques Joachim Yhombi Opango (born 12 January 1939) is a Congolese politician. [SBD]  He was an army officer who became Congo-Brazzaville's first general and served as Head of State of the People's Republic of the Congo from 1977 to 1979. [SBD]  He is currently the President of the Rally for Democracy and Development (RDD), a political party, and served as Prime Minister from 1993 to 1996. [SBD]  He was in exile from 1997 to 2007.

title: Paria River
paragraph: The Paria River is a tributary of the Colorado River, approximately 95 mi long, in southern Utah and northern Arizona in the United States. [SBD]  It drains a rugged and arid region northwest of the Colorado, flowing through roadless slot canyons along part of its course.

title: List of Hawaii politicians
paragraph: Below is a List of Hawaiʻ i politicians from the monarchical, republican, territorial, and statehood eras of history who have articles devoted to them on Wikipedia. [SBD]  Also listed are politicians who were born and raised in Hawaiʻ i but have assumed political roles in other states or countries.

title: Suporn Watanyusakul
paragraph: Suporn Watanyusakul is a plastic and reconstructive surgeon in Chonburi Province, Thailand. [SBD]  He is considered by some to be a world leader in surgical procedures for transgender individuals. [SBD]  He performs facial feminization surgery and male-to-female (MTF) sex reassignment surgery (SRS).

title: Dor Daim
paragraph: The Dardaim or Dor daim (דרדעים), are adherents of the Dor Deah movement in Orthodox Judaism . [SBD]  (דור דעה; Hebrew: "generation of knowledge", an allusion to the Israelites who witnessed the Exodus.) [SBD]  That movement took its name in 1912 in Yemen under Rabbi Yiḥyah Qafiḥ, and had its own network of synagogues and schools, although, in actuality, the movement existed long before that name had been coined for it. [SBD]  According to ethnographer and historian, Shelomo Dov Goitein, author and historiographer Hayyim Habshush had been a member of this movement before it had been given the name "Dor Deah", writing, “...He (i.e. Hayyim Habshush) and his friends, partly under European influence, but driven mainly by developments among the Yemenite Jews themselves, formed a group who ardently opposed all those forces of mysticism, superstition and fatalism which were then so prevalent in the country and strove for exact knowledge and independent thought, and the application of both to life.” [SBD]  It was only some years later, when Rabbi Yihya Qafih became the headmaster of the new Jewish school in Sana'a built by the Ottoman Turks and where he wanted to introduce a new curriculum in the school whereby boys would also learn arithmetic and the rudiments of the Arabic and Turkish languages that Rabbi Yihya Yitzhak Halevi gave to Rabbi Qafih's movement the name "Daradʻah", a word which is an Arabic broken plural made-up of the Hebrew words "Dör Deʻoh", and which means "Generation of Knowledge."

title: Ann Taylor (newscaster)
paragraph: Ann Taylor (born c. 1945 in Johnson City, Tennessee) is a newscaster who reported for National Public Radio (NPR), contributing to "All Things Considered" from 1989 to 2011.

title: Clayton Yeutter
paragraph: Clayton Keith "Clay" Yeutter, ONZM ( ; December 10, 1930 – March 4, 2017) served as United States Secretary of Agriculture under President George H. W. Bush from 1989 to 1991 before serving as Counselor to the President in 1992. [SBD]  He served as United States Trade Representative from 1985 to 1989 and as Chairman for the Republican National Committee from 1991 until 1992. [SBD]  Yeutter was employed as a Senior Advisor at the international law firm Hogan Lovells in Washington, D.C.

title: 28 Bellona
paragraph: 28 Bellona is a large main-belt asteroid. [SBD]  It was discovered by R. Luther on March 1, 1854, and named after Bellōna, the Roman goddess of war; the name was chosen to mark the beginning of the Crimean War.

title: 29 Amphitrite
paragraph: 29 Amphitrite is one of the largest S-type asteroids, probably third in diameter after Eunomia and Juno, although Iris and Herculina are similar in size.

title: Alexandre Yersin
paragraph: Alexandre Emile Jean Yersin (22 September 1863 – 1 March 1943) was a Swiss and naturalized French physician and bacteriologist. [SBD]  He is remembered as the discoverer of the bacillus responsible for the bubonic plague or pest, which was later named in his honour ("Yersinia pestis").

title: Fundão, Espírito Santo
paragraph: Fundão (] ) is a municipality in Espírito Santo, south eastern Brazil. [SBD]  Its population was 16,431 (2009) and its area is 280 km².

title: 30 Urania
paragraph: 30 Urania is a large main-belt asteroid that was discovered by English astronomer John Russell Hind on July 22, 1854. [SBD]  It was his last asteroid discovery. [SBD]  This object is named after Urania, the Greek Muse of astronomy. [SBD]  Initial orbital elements for 30 Urania were published by Wilhelm Günther, an assistant at Breslau Observatory.

title: Café au lait
paragraph: Café au lait (] ; French for "coffee with milk") is coffee with hot milk added. [SBD]  It differs from white coffee, which is coffee with cold milk or other whitener added.

title: Kenny Chesney
paragraph: Kenneth Arnold "Kenny" Chesney (born March 26, 1968) is an American country music singer, songwriter and record producer. [SBD]  He has recorded 20 albums, 14 of which have been certified Gold or higher by the RIAA. [SBD]  He has also produced more than 40 top 10 singles on the U.S. "Billboard" Hot Country Songs and Country Airplay charts, 29 of which have reached number one on the charts. [SBD]  Most of these have also charted high within the top 40 of the US "Billboard" Hot 100, making him one of the few successful crossover country artists. [SBD]  He has sold over 30 million albums worldwide.

title: Viktor Yerin
paragraph: Viktor Fyodorovich Yerin (Russian: Виктор Фёдорович Ерин , born 17 January 1944, Kazan, Russian SFSR) is a Russian politician and General of the Army who served as the country's first post-Soviet Minister of Internal Affairs (1992—1995). [SBD]  Hero of the Russian Federation (1993).

title: Frank Yerby
paragraph: Frank Yerby ((1916--) 05, 1916 – (1991--) 29, 1991 ) was a popular American writer, best known for his 1946 historical novel "The Foxes of Harrow", which was the first novel written by an African-American to become a best seller.

title: Stephanie Cheng
paragraph: Stephanie Cheng (born 10 October 1984) is a female cantopop singer in Hong Kong introduced by Go East Music (consolidated with Universal Music in 2003). [SBD]  She was born in Hong Kong and studied at Heep Yunn School and the Australian International School. [SBD]  After her graduation, she began modeling jobs until she was invited to be a singer.

title: Brad Renfro
paragraph: Brad Barron Renfro (July 25, 1982 – January 15, 2008) was an American actor and musician. [SBD]  He made his film debut at the age of eleven in the lead role in "The Client", going on to star in 21 feature films, several short films, and two television episodes. [SBD]  His career faded rapidly due to alcoholism and substance abuse. [SBD]  He died from a heroin overdose at the age of 25.

title: Mary Lou McDonald
paragraph: Mary Louise McDonald (born 1 May 1969) is an Irish Sinn Féin politician who has served as Deputy Leader of Sinn Féin since February 2009. [SBD]  She has been a Teachta Dála (TD) since 2011, currently for the Dublin Central constituency. [SBD]  She previously served as Member of the European Parliament (MEP) for the Dublin constituency constituency from 2004 to 2009.

title: Muttley
paragraph: Muttley is a fictional character originally voiced by Don Messick. [SBD]  In the 2000 "Wacky Races" videogame, he was voiced by Billy West. [SBD]  The character is known best for his mischievous, wheezing laughter.

title: M*A*S*H
paragraph: M*A*S*H is an American media franchise consisting of a series of novels, a film, several television series, plays, and other properties, owned by 20th Century Fox and based on the semi-autobiographic fiction of Richard Hooker.

title: Kathy Sinnott
paragraph: Kathy Sinnott ("née" Kelly; born 29 September 1950) is a disability rights campaigner and a former politician. [SBD]  She represented the South constituency in Ireland in the European Parliament from 2004 to 2009.

title: Estádio Ilha do Retiro
paragraph: Estádio Adelmar da Costa Carvalho, commonly known as Estádio Ilha do Retiro or simply Ilha do Retiro, is a football stadium situated in Recife, State of Pernambuco, in Northeastern Brazil, and owned by Sport Recife.

title: Analytic capacity
paragraph: In complex analysis, the analytic capacity of a compact subset "K" of the complex plane is a number that denotes "how big" a bounded analytic function on C \ "K" can become. [SBD]  Roughly speaking, "γ"("K") measures the size of the unit ball of the space of bounded analytic functions outside "K".

title: Staats Island
paragraph: Staats Island is an uninhabited island of the Beaver Island Group in the Falkland Islands. [SBD]  It lies between Beaver Island and Weddell Island, parallel to Tea Island and is 500 ha in area.

title: HP LaserJet
paragraph: LaserJet as a brand name identifies the line of dry electrophotographic (DEP) laser printers marketed by the American computer company Hewlett-Packard (HP). [SBD]  The HP LaserJet was the world's first desktop laser printer. [SBD]  As of 2016, Canon supplies both mechanisms and cartridges for all HP's laser printers.

title: Moeenuddin Ahmad Qureshi
paragraph: Moeenuddin Ahmad Qureshi (Urdu: معین الدین احمد قریشی‎; 26 June 1930 – 22 November 2016) (known as Moeen Qureshi) was a Pakistani economist and civil servant who served as Prime Minister of Pakistan in an acting capacity from July to October 1993. [SBD]  Qureshi also served as the senior vice president of World Bank.

title: Moeen
paragraph: Moeen or Moein is a given name and surname. [SBD]  It is a Quranic name which means: helper, supporter, or provider of refuge.

title: Stephen P. Synnott
paragraph: Stephen P. Synnott (born 1946) is an American astronomer and Voyager scientist at JPL, and expert in spacecraft optical navigation techniques. [SBD]  He has discovered several natural satellites of outer Solar System planets such as Metis, Puck, Larissa (recovered), Cressida, Thebe and Proteus.

title: Chaos (Sesame Park)
paragraph: Chaos is the name of a fictional character, a puppet cat in the Canadian children's television show "Sesame Park". [SBD]  She mostly addressed herself in the third person, much like Elmo does in the American series, and is also known to get herself in sticky situations.

title: Hundun
paragraph: Hundun () is both a "legendary faceless being" in Chinese mythology and the "primordial and central chaos" in Chinese cosmogony, comparable with the World egg.

title: Chaos (cosmogony)
paragraph: Chaos (Greek χάος , "khaos") refers to the formless or void state preceding the creation of the universe or cosmos in the Greek creation myths, or to the initial "gap" created by the original separation of heaven and earth.

title: Facundo Quiroga
paragraph: Juan Facundo Quiroga (1788 – February 16, 1835) was an Argentine caudillo (military strongman) who supported federalism at the time when the country was still in formation.

title: Hungry Hungry Hippos
paragraph: Hungry Hungry Hippos is a tabletop game made for 2–4 players, produced by Hasbro, under the brand of its subsidiary, Milton Bradley. [SBD]  The idea for the game was published in 1967 by toy inventor Fred Kroll and it was introduced in 1978. [SBD]  The objective of the game is for each player to collect as many marbles as possible with their 'hippo' (a toy hippo model). [SBD]  The game is marketed under the "Elefun and Friends" banner, along with "Elefun", "Mouse Trap" and "Gator Golf". [SBD]  The game was referenced in the 2010 Disney Pixar movie, "Toy Story 3" and the 2001 cult film "Donnie Darko". [SBD]  There is also a battle level based on the game in the 2016 Micro Machines game.

title: Richard J. Terrile
paragraph: Richard John Terrile (born March 22, 1951 in New York) is a Voyager scientist who discovered several moons of Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune. [SBD]  He works for NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.

title: Akhenaten, Dweller in Truth
paragraph: Akhenaten, Dweller in Truth is a novel written and published by Nobel Prize-winning Egyptian author Naguib Mahfouz in 1985. [SBD]  It was translated from Arabic into English in 1998 by Tagreid Abu-Hassabo.

title: Triaugmented triangular prism
paragraph: In geometry, the triaugmented triangular prism or tetracaidecadeltahedron is one of the Johnson solids ("J"). [SBD]  As the name suggests, it can be constructed by attaching square pyramids ("J") to each of the three equatorial faces of the triangular prism. [SBD]  It is a deltahedron.

title: Eddie Cheever
paragraph: Edward McKay "Eddie" Cheever Jr. (born January 10, 1958) is an American former racing driver who raced for almost 30 years in Formula One, sports cars, CART, and the Indy Racing League. [SBD]  Cheever participated in 143 Formula One World Championship races and started 132, more than any other American, driving for nine different teams from 1978 through 1989. [SBD]  In 1997, he formed his own IRL team and won the 1998 Indianapolis 500 as both owner and driver. [SBD]  The team now competes in sports cars.

title: Jeremy Harris
paragraph: Jeremy Harris (born December 7, 1950) is an American politician who served as Mayor of Honolulu from 1994 to 2004. [SBD]  A biologist by training, Harris started his political career as a delegate to the 1978 Hawai'i State Constitutional Convention. [SBD]  As chief executive of the City & County of Honolulu, the city was named "America's Greatest City" by the official American governance journal, "Governing Magazine". [SBD]  Harris is the founder of the "China-U.S. Conference of Mayors and Business Leaders" and "Japan-American Conference of Mayors and Chamber of Commerce Presidents". [SBD]  He is married to Ramona Sachiko Akui Harris and lives in Kalihi Valley on the Island of O'ahu.

title: Fernando Quijano
paragraph: Fernando Quijano (1805–1871) was an Uruguayan songwriter.

title: Pentagonal bipyramid
paragraph: In geometry, the pentagonal bipyramid (or dipyramid) is third of the infinite set of face-transitive bipyramids. [SBD]  Each bipyramid is the dual of a uniform prism.

title: Departments of El Salvador
paragraph: El Salvador is divided into 14 departments (Spanish: "departamentos") for administrative purposes, subdivided into 262 municipalities (Spanish: "municipios"). [SBD]  The country is a unitary state.

title: James Henry Quello
paragraph: James Henry Quello (April 21, 1914 – January 24, 2010) was a broadcaster and later government official who oversaw the communications industry. [SBD]  Quello was born in Laurium, Michigan. [SBD]  He was a Commissioner of the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) and, in 1993, from February 5 to November 28, served as the acting chairman of the commission. [SBD]  His term as acting chairman ended when Reed Hundt was confirmed by the U.S. Senate. [SBD]  He stepped down as an FCC commissioner in 1998. [SBD]  Quello was a Democrat who was appointed to the FCC by a Republican president, Richard Nixon.

title: Ahuachapán Department
paragraph: Ahuachapán is a department of El Salvador in the west of the country. [SBD]  The capital is Ahuachapán. [SBD]  In the South it has the Apenca-Ilamatepec Range and the Cerro Grande de Apaneca (Apaneca Grand Hill). [SBD]  Its extension is 1,240 km² and has more than 333,000 people living in the department.

title: Preston Smith (Georgia state politician)
paragraph: Preston W. Smith is an American politician from the U.S. state of Georgia.

title: Morgan Falls Dam
paragraph: Bull Sluice Lake is created by Morgan Falls Dam, a small hydroelectric dam located along the Chattahoochee River at the northern end of Sandy Springs, Georgia, and crossing the river westwards into eastern Cobb County in north metro Atlanta. [SBD]  Originally constructed in 1904 by Georgia Power to provide electricity for Atlanta's streetcars, it now provides enough power for about 4,400 homes. [SBD]  It was named for then recently deceased Georgia Power president S. Morgan Smith's mother whose maiden name was Morgan. [SBD]  At the time it was by far the largest hydroelectric plant in the state. [SBD]  In 1924 it was rebuilt as a 60 cycle plant with 15,000 kilowatts (up from the original 10,500 kW). [SBD]  In 1957 it was raised to regulate the flow from the larger Buford Dam, 36 mi upstream, in order to give Atlanta water during the hours it was needed most. [SBD]  It is 896 ft long, and 56 ft tall. [SBD]  The dam's license from the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) was issued in May 2008, and expires in February 2039. [SBD]  The Morgan Falls Dam is currently licensed at an authorized capacity of 16,800 kW.

title: Preston Smith (governor)
paragraph: Preston Earnest Smith (March 7, 1912 October 18, 2003) was the 40th Governor of Texas from 1969 to 1973, who previously served as the lieutenant governor from 1963 to 1969.

title: Cabañas Department
paragraph: Cabañas is a department of El Salvador in the north central part of the country. [SBD]  Its capital is Sensuntepeque and it is one of coolest parts of El Salvador. [SBD]  Classified as a department in February 1873, it covers an area of 1103.5 km2 and has over 164,900 inhabitants. [SBD]  The other major city of the department is Ilobasco. [SBD]  Agricultural produce includes coffee, sugar cane and sesame seeds, as well as dairy products. [SBD]  Gold, silver and copper are the principal minerals mined in the department. [SBD]  Its main industrial activity is oriented to manufacture of potteries, cheese, lime and also distilleries.

title: Marilyn Quayle
paragraph: Marilyn Tucker Quayle (born July 29, 1949) is an American lawyer and novelist. [SBD]  She is the wife of the 44th Vice President of the United States, Dan Quayle, and served as Second Lady of the United States from 1989 until 1993.

title: 31 Euphrosyne
paragraph: 31 Euphrosyne is the 12th-largest and the 5th-most-massive asteroid in the asteroid belt, discovered by James Ferguson on September 1, 1854. [SBD]  It was the first asteroid found from North America. [SBD]  It is named after Euphrosyne, one of the Charites in Greek mythology.

title: Chalatenango Department
paragraph: Chalatenango is a department of El Salvador, located in the northwest of the country. [SBD]  The capital is the city of Chalatenango. [SBD]  The Chalatenango Department encompasses 2,017 km² and contains more than 204,000 inhabitants. [SBD]  "Las Matras Archaeological Ruins" contains the relics of prehistoric populations and caves in which rock writing is found. [SBD]  The "5 de Noviembre" Hydroelectric Dam is found in Chalatenango Department, near the border with Cabañas. [SBD]  The highest point in the country, El Pital with an elevation of 2730.06 m, is also located in Chalatenango Department.

title: Mel Read
paragraph: Imelda Mary Read, known as Mel Read is a British politician, and former Labour Party member of the European Parliament for the East Midlands.

title: Jan de Quay
paragraph: Jan Eduard de Quay (August 26, 1901 – July 4, 1985) was a Dutch politician of the defunct Catholic People's Party (KVP) now merged into the Christian Democratic Appeal (CDA). [SBD]  He served as Prime Minister of the Netherlands from May 19, 1959 until July 24, 1963.

title: 32 Pomona
paragraph: 32 Pomona is a stony main-belt asteroid that is 81 km across. [SBD]  It was discovered by German-French astronomer Hermann Mayer Salomon Goldschmidt on October 26, 1854, and is named after Pōmōna, the Roman goddess of fruit trees.

title: Cuscatlán Department
paragraph: Cuscatlán is a department of El Salvador, located in the center of the country. [SBD]  With a surface area of 756.19 km2 , it is El Salvador's smallest department. [SBD]  It is inhabited by over 252,000 people. [SBD]  Cuscatlán or Cuzcatlán was the name the original inhabitants of the Western part of the country gave to most of the territory that is now El Salvador. [SBD]  In their language it means "land of precious jewels". [SBD]  It was created on 22 May 1835. [SBD]  Suchitoto was the first capital of the department but on 12 November 1861, Cojutepeque was made the capital. [SBD]  It is known in producing fruits, tobacco, sugar cane, and coffee among other items. [SBD]  The department is famous for its chorizos from the city of Cojutepeque.

title: La Libertad Department (El Salvador)
paragraph: La Libertad is one of the departments of El Salvador and is located in the southwest of the country. [SBD]  The capital is Santa Tecla. [SBD]  It has area 1,653 km² and a population of more than 747,600 people. [SBD]  It was classified as a department on January 28, 1865. [SBD]  The population was settled on the Ulliman Plains, which is where rubber is harvested. [SBD]  The city was called "Nueva Ciudad de San Salvador" (New City of San Salvador) and made the department's capital on the same date as the department was declared. [SBD]  The department's capital was renamed Santa Tecla on December 22, 2003. [SBD]  The agricultural products that are cultivated are the basic grains, balsam, sugar cane, coffee, grass, hortenses plants, cocoa, and fruits. [SBD]  They also develop the bovine, equine and pig cattle, the raising of poultry and beekeeping. [SBD]  It also stands out the textile industry and the productions of candles, soaps, furniture, clothes, footwear, dairy products, and many diverse products and liquors.

title: William Quarter
paragraph: William J. Quarter (January 21, 1806 – April 10, 1848) was an Irish American prelate of the Roman Catholic Church. [SBD]  He was the first Bishop of Chicago (1844–1848).

title: Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway
paragraph: The Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway (reporting mark ATSF) , often referred to as the Santa Fe or AT&SF, was one of the larger railroads in the United States. [SBD]  Chartered in February 1859, the railroad reached the Kansas-Colorado border in 1873 and Pueblo, Colorado, in 1876. [SBD]  To create a demand for its services, the railroad set up real estate offices and sold farm land from the land grants that it was awarded by Congress. [SBD]  Despite the name, its main line never served Santa Fe, New Mexico, as the terrain was too difficult; the town ultimately was reached by a branch line from Lamy.

title: Warsaw University of Technology
paragraph: The Warsaw University of Technology (Polish: "Politechnika Warszawska" ; literally, "Warsaw Polytechnic") is one of the leading institutes of technology in Poland and one of the largest in Central Europe. [SBD]  It employs 2,453 teaching faculty, with 357 professors (including 145 titular professors). [SBD]  The student body numbers 36,156 (as of 2011), mostly full-time. [SBD]  There are 19 faculties (divisions) covering almost all fields of science and technology. [SBD]  They are in Warsaw, except for one in Płock.

title: La Paz Department (El Salvador)
paragraph: La Paz is a department of El Salvador in the south central area of the country. [SBD]  The capital is Zacatecoluca. [SBD]  La Paz has an area of 1,228 km² and a population of more than 328,000. [SBD]  The department was created in 1852. [SBD]  There are various caves containing rock writing. [SBD]  The department has a church in Zacatecoluca where the Independence Hero Dr Jose Simeon Cañas y Villacorta was born. [SBD]  He was known as "The Liberator of the Slaves in Central America". [SBD]  In 1833, Anastasio Aquino, an indigenous person, proclaimed himself as "The Emperor of the Nonualcos".

title: USS Porpoise (SS-172)
paragraph: USS "Porpoise" (SS–172), the fifth United States Navy ship to bear her name, was the lead ship of her class of submarines.

title: Nick Clegg
paragraph: Nicholas William Peter Clegg {'1': ", '2': ", '3': ", '4': "} (born 7 January 1967) is a British Liberal Democrat politician who was the Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom and Lord President of the Council from 2010 to 2015 in the Cameron–Clegg coalition. [SBD]  Clegg was Member of Parliament (MP) for Sheffield Hallam from 2005 to 2017 and was the Leader of the Liberal Democrats from 2007 to 2015.

title: Bull Sluice Lake
paragraph: Bull Sluice Lake is a small reservoir located along the Chattahoochee River in northern Georgia, in the northern suburbs of metro Atlanta. [SBD]  It is 673 acre , and is impounded by the Morgan Falls Dam. [SBD]  Besides the hydroelectric power produced by the dam, the lake's primary use is recreation, including fishing and rowing.

title: Khwae Noi River
paragraph: The River Kwai, more correctly Khwae Noi (Thai: แควน้อย ,  ] , "small tributary") or Khwae Sai Yok (Thai: แควไทรโยค  ] ), is a river in western Thailand. [SBD]  It rises to the east of the Salween in the north-south spine of the Bilauktaung range near, but not over the border with Burma. [SBD]  It begins at the confluence of Ranti, Songkalia and Bikhli Rivers. [SBD]  At Kanchanaburi it merges with the Khwae Yai River to form the Mae Klong river, which empties into the Gulf of Thailand at Samut Songkhram.

title: La Unión Department
paragraph: The most important agricultural products are: coffee, grass, fruits, cocoa, oleaginous seeds, and sugar cane. [SBD]  The manufacture of palm objects, tortoiseshell objects, panela, mangrove extraction, and fish. [SBD]  It has locations of gold, iron, barium, and mercury.

title: Morazán Department
paragraph: Morazán (] ) is a department of El Salvador. [SBD]  Located in the northeast part of the country, its capital is San Francisco Gotera. [SBD]  It covers a total surface area of 1,447 km² and has a population of more than 199,500.

title: Faerie Tale
paragraph: Faerie Tale is a supernatural thriller, falling within the subgenre of contemporary fantasy, by American writer Raymond E. Feist, first published in 1988.

title: Qian Qichen
paragraph: Qian Qichen (; 5 January 1928 – 9 May 2017) was a Chinese diplomat and politician. [SBD]  He served as China's Foreign Minister from April 1988 to March 1998, and as Vice Premier from 1993 to 2003. [SBD]  Since then, no other diplomat-turned-politician has attained such a lofty status in China's political hierarchy.

title: San Miguel Department (El Salvador)
paragraph: San Miguel is a department in the eastern part of El Salvador. [SBD]  The capital is San Miguel. [SBD]  The department is 2,077 km² in area and has a population of over 478,000.

title: USS Pollack (SS-180)
paragraph: USS "Pollack" (SS-180), a "United States Porpoise"-class submarine , was the first ship of the United States Navy to be named for the pollack, a food fish resembling the true cod, but with the lower jaw projecting and without the barbel.

title: San Salvador Department
paragraph: San Salvador is a department of El Salvador in the west central part of the country. [SBD]  The capital is San Salvador, which is also the national capital. [SBD]  The department has North of the Rio Lempa Valley, the "Valle de las Hamacas" (Hammock Valley) and a section of Lake Ilopango. [SBD]  Some of the department's cities that are densely populated are: San Salvador, Ciudad Delgado, Mejicanos, Soyapango, Panchimalco and Apopa. [SBD]  The department covers an area of 886.2 km² and the last census count in 2007 reported 1,567,156 people. [SBD]  It was classified as a department on June 12, 1824. [SBD]  During the time of the colony, the department was the San Salvador Party, from where territory was taken to make the departments of Chalatenago, La Libertad, Cuscatlán and La Paz. [SBD]  This department produces beans, coffee, sugar cane, etc. for agriculture, on the other hand San Salvador Department holds many headquarters for banking companies in El Salvador and Central America, and for many communication services, also the headquarters of the electric companies are located in the San Salvador Department, last years these companies took a step and started exporting electricity to all Central America. [SBD]  The current mayor of the department is Norman Quijano (2012-2015).

title: San Vicente Department
paragraph: San Vicente is a department of El Salvador in the center of the country. [SBD]  The capital is San Vicente. [SBD]  On October 4, 1834, San Vicente City of Austria and Lorenzana (Ciudad de San Vicente de Austria y Lorenzana) was made the capital of State of El Salvador during the Federal Republic of Central America. [SBD]  In 1840, it stopped to be the capital of the State of El Salvador but it continues to be of the department. [SBD]  The department was created on June 12, 1824. [SBD]  The San Vicente department has 1,184 km² and a population in excess of 174,500.

title: La Aurora International Airport
paragraph: La Aurora International Airport (Spanish: "Aeropuerto Internacional La Aurora" ) (IATA: GUA, ICAO: MGGT) serves Guatemala City, Guatemala. [SBD]  It is located 6.4 km south of Guatemala City's center and 25 km from Antigua Guatemala. [SBD]  It is administered by the "Dirección General de Aeronáutica Civil".

title: Agency (philosophy)
paragraph: Agency is the capacity of an actor to act in a given environment. [SBD]  The capacity to act does not at first imply a specific moral dimension to the ability to make the choice to act, and moral agency is therefore a distinct concept. [SBD]  In sociology, an agent is an individual engaging with the social structure. [SBD]  Notably, though, the primacy of social structure vs. individual capacity with regard to persons' actions is debated within sociology. [SBD]  This debate concerns, at least partly, the level of reflexivity an agent may possess.

title: Stephen Maguire
paragraph: Stephen Maguire (born 13 March 1981) is a Scottish professional snooker player. [SBD]  He has been a professional snooker player since 1998, ranked in the top 16 consecutively for 11 years from 2005 to August 2016, reaching as high as 2nd for two of those seasons. [SBD]  He has won five major ranking tournaments, including the UK Championship in 2004. [SBD]  As a prolific break-builder, Maguire has compiled more than 350 century breaks, including three maximum breaks.

title: Cyclorama
paragraph: A cyclorama is a panoramic image on the inside of a cylindrical platform, designed to give viewers standing in the middle of the cylinder a 360° view, and also a building designed to show a panoramic image. [SBD]  The intended effect is to make viewers, surrounded by the panoramic image, feel as if they were standing in the midst of the place depicted in the image.

title: Kirstine Meyer
paragraph: Kirstine Bjerrum Meyer (12 October 1861 – 28 September 1941) was a Danish physicist. [SBD]  She was a high school teacher for many years, working on her education and research in physics at the same time. [SBD]  She won the Gold Medal of the Royal Danish Academy of Science and Letters in 1899, for a paper examining whether there exists a general equation of state for all fluid bodies, "Om overensstemmende Tilstande hos Stofferne". [SBD]  She received her Ph.D in physics from the University of Copenhagen in 1909, becoming the first Danish woman to earn a doctorate in natural sciences. [SBD]  Her dissertation, "Temperaturbegrebets Udvikling gennem Tiderne" (The Development of the Temperature Concept through Time), was an in-depth treatment of the history of the concept of temperature.

title: Circular
paragraph: Forms of communication used in conveying information and directives within an organization. [SBD]  It is sometimes called office instructions.

title: Bomba (cryptography)
paragraph: The bomba, or bomba kryptologiczna (Polish for "bomb" or "cryptologic bomb") was a special-purpose machine designed about October 1938 by Polish Cipher Bureau cryptologist Marian Rejewski to break German Enigma-machine ciphers.

title: Hassan Gouled Aptidon
paragraph: Hassan Gouled Aptidon (Somali: "Xasan Guuleed Abtidoon" . [SBD]  Arabic: حسن جوليد أبتيدون‎ ‎ ) (October 15, 1916 – November 21, 2006) was the first President of Djibouti from 1977 to 1999.

title: Horace Lindrum
paragraph: Horace Lindrum (born Horace Norman William Morrell, 15 January 1912 – 20 June 1974) was an Australian professional snooker and billiards player. [SBD]  Although the dominant snooker player in Australia, he was eclipsed by Joe Davis, whom he never beat on level terms. [SBD]  Lindrum contested three World Championship finals against Davis, in 1936, 1937 and 1946, losing all three but coming closer than anyone to beating him. [SBD]  When past his best, Lindrum won the 1952 World Championship which, because of a dispute between the governing body and the players' association, was only contested by himself and New Zealander Clark McConachy.

title: Eternal flame
paragraph: An eternal flame is a flame, lamp or torch that burns continuously for an indefinite period. [SBD]  Most eternal flames are ignited and tended intentionally, but some are natural phenomena caused by natural gas leaks, peat fires and coal seam fires, all of which can be initially ignited by lightning, piezoelectricity or human activity, some of which have burned for thousands of years.

title: Driver (video game series)
paragraph: Driver is a video game series developed by Reflections Interactive (now Ubisoft Reflections), and originally published by GT Interactive, later by Atari and now by Ubisoft. [SBD]  The gameplay consists of a mixture of action-adventure and driving in open world environments. [SBD]  Since the series began in 1999, there have been five main installments released.

title: Zimbabwe Cricket
paragraph: Zimbabwe Cricket (ZC), known as the Zimbabwe Cricket Union (ZCU) until 2004, is the governing body for the sport of cricket in Zimbabwe. [SBD]  Zimbabwe Cricket is a full member of the International Cricket Council (ICC), and administers the Zimbabwe national cricket team, organising Test tours, One Day Internationals and Twenty20 Internationals with other nations. [SBD]  It also organises domestic cricket, including the Castle Logan Cup, the Coca-Cola Metbank Pro50 Championship and the Stanbic Bank 20 Series in Zimbabwe.

title: Rosaura Andreu
paragraph: Rosaura Andreu (1 January 1918 – 21 November 2010) was a Cuban-born actress who found wide fame in Puerto Rico as a children's television show host.

title: Robert S. Shankland
paragraph: Robert Sherwood Shankland (January 11, 1908 – March 1, 1982) was an American physicist and historian.

title: Quasar, Quasar, Burning Bright
paragraph: Quasar, Quasar, Burning Bright is a collection of seventeen scientific essays by Isaac Asimov. [SBD]  It was the thirteenth of a series of books collecting essays from "The Magazine of Fantasy and Science Fiction". [SBD]  These essays were first published between May 1976 and September 1977. [SBD]  It was first published by Doubleday & Company in 1978. [SBD]  Its title is derived from the first line of William Blake's 1794 poem "The Tyger".

title: Meet Joe Black
paragraph: Meet Joe Black is a 1998 American romantic fantasy film directed and produced by Martin Brest, and starring Brad Pitt, Anthony Hopkins, and Claire Forlani. [SBD]  The screenplay by Bo Goldman, Kevin Wade, Ron Osborn and Jeff Reno is loosely based on the 1934 film "Death Takes a Holiday".

title: Shmita
paragraph: The sabbath year ("shmita" Hebrew: שמיטה‎ , literally "release") also called the sabbatical year or "shǝvi'it" (, literally "seventh") is the seventh year of the seven-year agricultural cycle mandated by the Torah for the Land of Israel, and still observed in contemporary Judaism.

title: Chris Lowe
paragraph: Christopher Sean Lowe (born 4 October 1959) is an English musician, singer, songwriter and co-founder of the synthpop duo Pet Shop Boys which he formed with Neil Tennant in 1981.

title: Mesocortical pathway
paragraph: The mesocortical pathway is a dopaminergic pathway that connects the ventral tegmentum to the prefrontal cortex. [SBD]  It is one of the four major dopamine pathways in the brain. [SBD]  It is essential to the normal cognitive function of the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (part of the frontal lobe), and is thought to be involved in cognitive control, motivation, and emotional response.

title: Football at the 1912 Summer Olympics
paragraph: Football at the 1912 Summer Olympics was one of the 102 events at the 1912 Summer Olympics in Stockholm, Sweden. [SBD]  It was the fourth time that football was on the Olympic schedule. [SBD]  The tournament was contested between 11 nations, all of them from Europe, with Great Britain winning the gold medals (the IOC accredits Great Britain and Ireland with the medal). [SBD]  Replicating the 1908 tournament, Denmark won silver medals and the Netherlands won bronze medals.

title: Atong language (Sino-Tibetan)
paragraph: Atong is a Sino-Tibetan language related to Koch, Rabha, Bodo and Garo. [SBD]  It is spoken in the South Garo Hills and West Khasi Hills districts of Meghalaya state in Northeast India, southern Kamrup district in Assam, and adjacent areas in Bangladesh. [SBD]  The correct spelling "Atong" is based on the way the speakers themselves pronounce the name of their language. [SBD]  There is no glottal stop in the name and it is not a tonal language.

title: Wild rice
paragraph: Wild rice (Ojibwe: Manoomin; also called Canada rice, Indian rice, and water oats) are four species of grasses forming the genus Zizania, and the grain that can be harvested from them. [SBD]  The grain was historically gathered and eaten in both North America and China. [SBD]  While now a delicacy in North America, the grain is eaten less in China, where the plant's stem is used as a vegetable.

title: Gold (Asimov book)
paragraph: Gold: The Final Science Fiction Collection is a 1995 collection of stories and essays by American writer Isaac Asimov. [SBD]  The stories, which comprise the volume's first half, are short pieces which had remained uncollected at the time of Asimov's death. [SBD]  "Cal" describes a robot that wishes to write, and the title story "Gold" expresses both Asimov's admiration of "King Lear" and his thoughts on cinema adaptations of his own stories. [SBD]  The story "Gold" won a Hugo Award.

title: New Frankley
paragraph: New Frankley in Birmingham is a civil parish in Birmingham, England. [SBD]  As such, it has its own parish council.

title: Tytherington
paragraph: Places in the United Kingdom known as Tytherington:

title: Reach for Tomorrow
paragraph: Reach for Tomorrow is a collection of science fiction short stories by British writer Arthur C. Clarke. [SBD]  All the stories originally appeared in a number of different publications.

title: Nifedipine
paragraph: Nifedipine, sold under the brand names Adalat among others, is a medication used to manage angina, high blood pressure, Raynaud's phenomenon, and premature labor. [SBD]  It is one of the treatments of choice for Prinzmetal angina. [SBD]  It may be used to treat severe high blood pressure in pregnancy. [SBD]  Its use in preterm labor may allow more time for steroids to improve the baby's lungs and time to transfer the mother to a well qualified medical facility before delivery. [SBD]  Nifedipine is taken by mouth and comes in fast and slow release formulations.

title: Batam
paragraph: Batam is the largest city (kota) of Riau Islands Province of Indonesia as well the name of an island. [SBD]  The city of Batam administrative area covers of several islands: Batam Island is the core urban and industrial zone. [SBD]  Both Galang Island and Rempang Island are connected to Batam Island by short bridges, the 3 islands are collectively called Barelang. [SBD]  These latter two islands maintain their rural character, as does nearby Bulan Island, also administered as part of the municipality (kota). [SBD]  Batam is an industrial boomtown, an emerging transport hub, and part of a free trade zone the Indonesia–Malaysia–Singapore Growth Triangle, located 20 km off Singapore's south coast.

title: Clovelly
paragraph: Clovelly ( ) is a small village in the Torridge district of Devon, England. [SBD]  It has a harbour and is a tourist attraction notable for its steep pedestrianised cobbled main street, donkeys and views over the Bristol Channel. [SBD]  At the 2011 census, the parish population was 443, which was 50 fewer than ten years previously. [SBD]  The ward of Clovelly Bay includes the island of Lundy.
